WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.720
- The following is a conversation
with Don Lincoln, a particle

00:00:03.780 --> 00:00:07.240
physicist at Fermilab,
who has spent decades

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:11.040
working at the frontier of
high energy physics. This

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:15.060
was a mind-blowing and
inspiring conversation. Don

00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:18.270
turned out to be one of my favorite
people to talk to about physics.

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:22.640
Truly a unique mind with
that Richard Feynman ability

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:26.780
of taking very complicated ideas
and explaining them simply,

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:31.180
without losing any of the
essential, brilliant insights at

00:00:31.220 --> 00:00:35.040
the core of those ideas.
This is a Lex Fridman

00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:38.810
podcast. To support it, please check
out our sponsors in the description

00:00:38.840 --> 00:00:42.680
where you can also find ways
to contact me, ask questions,

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:48.220
give feedback, and so on. And now,
dear friends, here's Don Lincoln.

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:53.600
In describing the search for
a theory of everything in

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:57.460
physics, you describe the
history of physics can be told

00:00:57.540 --> 00:01:00.660
effectively as a kind of
history of unifications.

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:05.880
There's this centuries-long quest
to show that these distinct

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:09.740
phenomena are actually linked by some

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:13.920
unified underlying principles
even starting with

00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:19.980
Newton, that you can think of the effort
of physics as one is trying to unify-

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:23.740
... the laws of nature. So I was
wondering if we could talk through the

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:27.550
history of unification-
... that lens of physics.

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:32.040
- There are, of course, lots of different
ways to do physics, but the way

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:35.600
that I would say that particle
physicists, cosmologists do

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:39.140
is they are trying to really find

00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:43.700
basically the underlying
principles that govern the laws

00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:47.660
of nature. If we go back,
say, to the, I don't know,

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:51.480
1650s or so, you're the most
brilliant person around,

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:55.800
and you've noticed two things. One
you've noticed is that when you trip,

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:59.440
you fall. That is the nature
of gravity that we all

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:03.400
experience day to day. But then there's
sort of astronomy, where you look

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:07.260
out at the heavens and you see
the stars march across the sky.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:10.269
You see the planets
move through the stars.

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:14.840
And there, that seems to have
absolutely nothing to do

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.489
with what happens when you drop your
sandwich and the dog grabs it from you. So-

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:26.080
... the brilliant thing was when Newton
looked at that and he thought about,

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:30.840
maybe the moon is falling, but it's
missing the Earth. So what we had is

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:34.670
that in maybe 1650, you
had what we might call the

00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:38.660
laws of celestial gravity, the
gravity that governs the heavens,

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:42.970
and terrestrial gravity, the
gravity that is here on Earth. Now,

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:46.800
we don't think of it that way anymore.
We think of it as just gravity.

00:02:47.140 --> 00:02:51.120
But at that time, that wasn't
at all obvious. And in fact, if

00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:55.120
you look in the books, Newton's theory
is Newton's law of universal gravity.

00:02:55.190 --> 00:02:59.080
The universal is there, and the
reason is because he realized these

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:02.620
two things that seemed to have
nothing to do with one another were

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.540
indeed one and the same. I mean, this
is absolutely brilliant. I mean, Newton

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:11.660
is arguably one of the most brilliant
humans of which I'm ever aware.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:16.400
But at any rate, it is the first
sort of easily to describe

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:20.820
unification of physics that you
can state in a way that sort of

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:22.970
makes sense to modern-

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.580
... Humans. I mean, you can go back farther
than that, where people are talking

00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:30.290
about chemistry, the nature of atoms.
You go back to Democritus, who was

00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:33.800
wrong about very many things, but
the idea that there was a smallest

00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:37.760
particulate form of matter is right.
So it's kind of funny. You talk-- You

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:41.730
read the chemistry books, and they say that the
idea of atoms goes back to Democritus, and,

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:46.260
you know, he, his idea was that,
like, there was a smallest atom of

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:50.090
oil, which was smooth, and it was smooth,
of course, because, well, oil is smooth.

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:54.859
There was a smallest atom of vinegar because
vinegar is tart and it pricks your tongue-

00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:58.660
... so therefore, atoms were
little sharp, pointy things. Um,

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:02.310
and so he was wrong about a
lot, but he was right about the

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:06.360
idea that there was a small particle,

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:10.680
and we now know a very-- we have a
very different concept than he did.

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:15.180
So you can go back farther than that.
But getting the unification, there are

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:20.720
more examples. For instance, if
you go back to, say, 1830 or so,

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:25.400
scientists were trying to understand
electricity, for instance.

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:29.820
And there was a lot going on. People
really understood things. But at the time,

00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:34.410
you would have two phenomena
that are familiar to us now.

00:04:34.410 --> 00:04:38.100
One is a magnet, which, you
know, at the time, mostly

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:42.060
magnets were simply little pieces of
iron that had been magnetized and they

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:42.900
could stick to steel.

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:47.960
And then you had electricity, which was
at the time they were generating little

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:51.540
sparks that they could play
and, and have fun with, or more

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:55.520
broadly, a lightning bolt
blazing across the sky. And

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:59.320
so when you think about this, that
lightning bolt and that little

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:06.640
magnet seem to be really unrelated. Um,
but over the 1800s, a number of scientists

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:11.099
were exploring little aspects
of it. What happens when you

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:14.920
run electricity through a wire?
It seems to make a magnetic

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:18.760
field. You know, they, they-- There was a whole
bunch of experiments and there were a lot of names.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:22.680
But in about the 1860s or so, James Clerk

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:26.720
Maxwell took all of those ideas that had
been percolating around for the previous

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:30.050
50 years and wrote his laws of

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:33.880
electromagnetism, and they're really
fascinating. If you look at the laws of

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:37.720
electromagnetism, they are-- they're
differential equations or inter-

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:41.980
integral equations. But basically,
what they say is on one

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:45.810
side, you have a bunch of terms
that have electricity in them,

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:50.820
and then you have equals on the
other side, a magnetism thing.

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:54.640
So forgetting all of the mathematical
symbols, you have electricity

00:05:54.710 --> 00:05:58.300
side equals a magnetism side.
Electricity equals magnetism.

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:02.740
And that is a staggering
concept, the fact that these two

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:06.420
things, a lightning bolt and the magnet
that holds your kids' art to the

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:10.100
refrigerator, are one and the
same. And this was another case

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:14.110
where electricity and
magnetism became unified into

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:18.010
electromagnetism. So now we have two
examples: one, gravity being unified,

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:21.710
terrestrial and celestial gravity,
and then electricity and magnetism.

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:26.060
So I'll tell you about some more in a
moment, but one thing that's kind of

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:29.720
important because the
goal is, of course, to

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:34.010
unify everything. That if I could do what
I want to do, I would have some unified

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:37.930
theory that would explain all the behavior
of all energy, matter, space, and time,

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:39.180
which is a grand goal.

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:43.640
- And we should say that maybe
one of the goals of science

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:48.940
more broadly, outside of physics
even, is to construct models

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:55.430
that can generalize the world. So
if you look at Darwinian evolution-

00:06:55.460 --> 00:07:02.220
... that was a very beautiful theory
that captures another layer of reality

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:07.260
of, like, how this particular thing
that we see here on Earth happens.

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:07.800
- Right.

00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:11.160
- So when we talk about theory of
everything in physics, that's

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:15.800
capturing a different layer of abstraction
about the functioning of the universe.

00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:19.740
- Right. The whole Darwinian
evolution, the fact that our

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:23.029
genetics has significant
overlap with the genetics of a

00:07:23.100 --> 00:07:26.350
banana is pretty
staggering, is astonishing-

00:07:26.350 --> 00:07:30.120
... that that works. So
that is amazing. But

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:34.110
for at least the class
of scientists that I am,

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:38.130
what we think of is,
well, sure, biology is

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:41.990
interesting and all, but when
you get right down to it, it's,

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:45.880
it's caused-- whatever happens in
biology is caused by the movement of

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:50.370
molecules. And then you say, "Well,
that's great and all, but molecules,

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:52.570
they do what they do because
they're made of atoms."

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:57.040
And then the next step is, well, you know,
atoms, that's great, but atoms work the

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:01.040
way they do because of the nucleus and the
electrons, and then the nucleus is protons

00:08:01.060 --> 00:08:04.740
and neutrons. And so there
are those of us, myself

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:08.540
included, who want to dig down
to the very, very bottom and

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:12.560
find out what is the smallest
building block of nature from

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:17.480
which all of these other far more complex
and interesting and abstract things are.

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:21.660
But what is at the very, very
bottom? And also, that's great,

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:26.280
but if you know what the smallest
building blocks are, that doesn't tell

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:30.060
you the story. It's like having
a whole bunch of LEGOs, but

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:34.120
not knowing how to put them together. You
also need to know how they interact, how they

00:08:34.220 --> 00:08:38.000
work, and so that's why we study
forces. So there are the various

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:41.640
subatomic forces of which we're
familiar and for instance,

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:44.740
electricity and magnetism
are components of

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:48.700
electromagnetism, which then
governs the behavior of things

00:08:48.860 --> 00:08:51.860
like-- This is amazing. Electromagnetism

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:56.190
explains, of course, electricity,
magnetism, but it explains how light works.

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:03.180
It explains how much of chemistry
works. So electromagnetism, 1860 or '70

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:07.200
the wonderful thing about that is
if you take Maxwell's equations

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:11.090
and you apply a little bit of
calculus, it's very easy to see

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:15.120
that the laws of electricity and the
laws of magnetism combined together

00:09:16.300 --> 00:09:20.000
make what's called a wave
equation, which that shows

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:24.540
that these electric and magnetic
fields oscillate. They vary,

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:29.100
and if you have something that's
varied, that's a wave, and the

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:33.120
wave then moves. And if you do the
math, you find out that the speed

00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:36.340
at which these waves move is
the speed of light. And so

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:40.560
people said, "Wow, the speed
of light comes out of those

00:09:40.600 --> 00:09:43.980
equations." And that had
to be, I think, very

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:47.960
persuasive. And of course,
electromagnetism also plays a

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.920
really significant role in
chemistry because after all,

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:55.500
atoms are held together by
electromagnetic forces. There's more

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:59.520
to how atoms work. There is all
the quantum mechanics stuff.

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:03.380
But if you did not have electromagnetism,
or if electromagnetism was very

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:07.280
different, then atoms would be very
different. So it plays a very big role

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:13.000
in holding us together. So
it's a staggering advance in

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:18.750
science to have a good behavior on
that. And of course, being able to,

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:23.380
to tame electromagnetism is why

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:27.120
people can hear you when you do
your podcast because through the

00:10:27.160 --> 00:10:30.540
miracles of the internet just--
or just electricity running the

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:35.320
computers. I mean, this is a case
if I can get on a small soapbox,

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:39.960
where people back then said, "Well, why
are you messing around with magnets and

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:44.820
sparks?" And who cares? Well, that very

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:49.980
fundamental digging into
the laws of nature has

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:53.400
spinoffs, and it has spinoffs-- One
of the big spinoffs is our entire

00:10:53.420 --> 00:10:58.720
technological society. Without being able
to govern electricity, we'd still be

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:02.160
farmers and shoemakers in
cities. We certainly would not

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:06.800
have everything that we do, so
off my soapbox. But it's really a

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:13.730
lovely thing to show how this digging
into deep, fundamental, not understood,

00:11:13.920 --> 00:11:17.680
mysterious things can, a
hundred or two hundred

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:21.690
years later, transform the
world. And the type of

00:11:21.700 --> 00:11:25.620
science I do now, people often ask,
"Well, what good is knowing about how the

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:27.820
inside of atoms work, how
the inside of quarks work?"

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:32.560
And I don't know the answer to
that but just being a little more

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:37.140
pragmatic, if I go back, say, a hundred
years, where people were trying to

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:40.780
understand how the protons and neutrons

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:44.520
inside atoms held together,
how they split, how they,

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:48.480
how you could combine them
and so forth, this has led

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:52.400
to nuclear power. Now, whatever
you think about nuclear power, and

00:11:52.440 --> 00:11:55.760
some people like it and some people
don't, but it is powerful. It

00:11:55.860 --> 00:12:03.100
will generate energy for humanity, and it
may be that is the path that we take as

00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:06.970
we move away from digging
fossil fuels out of the

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:10.980
ground. Humanity is going to need
power no matter what. Nobody is

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:14.380
going to go back to the way
things were in the 1700s.

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:18.540
And one enormous source
of energy that is there

00:12:18.660 --> 00:12:22.560
for us to take if we so
choose is the modification

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:26.350
of the nucleus of atoms. Seemed to
have absolutely nothing to do with

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:29.780
anything, and yet it
provides humanity with an

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:33.440
opportunity, which of course requires
that we think carefully of how we do that

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:38.280
and if we want to, but it gives us
something that we didn't have before.

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:42.472
- Yeah, it's very clear that nuclear
fusion and nuclear fission will

00:12:42.492 --> 00:12:46.172
unlock huge amount of energy
that's required for a

00:12:46.292 --> 00:12:51.051
civilization to flourish, but
that's almost like near term.

00:12:52.172 --> 00:12:58.571
Longer term, you can think about things
like we'll talk about dark energy crisis-

00:12:59.082 --> 00:13:03.272
antimatter. Maybe if you figure out

00:13:04.212 --> 00:13:08.112
some of the mysteries around
antimatter, that too would lead

00:13:08.172 --> 00:13:12.002
to energy sources, how to
produce energy. That too might

00:13:12.072 --> 00:13:15.382
lead to counterintuitive
propulsion systems-

00:13:15.972 --> 00:13:19.832
... for us humans to travel through
the universe. Now, right now it seems

00:13:19.892 --> 00:13:23.632
far-fetched, too expensive, too
complicated, too difficult, but

00:13:24.492 --> 00:13:28.342
breakthroughs in fundamental
theoretical physics might

00:13:28.372 --> 00:13:32.232
lead us to unlock some incredible
energy sources, incredible technologies

00:13:32.412 --> 00:13:36.322
that will allow humans
to explore the universe.

00:13:36.432 --> 00:13:40.152
And of course, we should also
mention that as always with

00:13:40.192 --> 00:13:44.052
technology, it's a double-edged sword.
It will most likely lead to the

00:13:44.072 --> 00:13:46.292
development of more dangerous weapons or-

00:13:46.692 --> 00:13:53.302
... other sources of harm. And then we as
a civilization kinda have to walk that

00:13:53.592 --> 00:13:57.302
line and hope we figure out how to do more

00:13:57.332 --> 00:13:59.732
good than bad with the
technologies we build.

00:13:59.772 --> 00:14:03.332
- Right. But we have to really
remember, while people worry

00:14:03.652 --> 00:14:06.842
about nuclear weapons, which
are admittedly very dangerous,

00:14:07.332 --> 00:14:11.372
and even nuclear power, which has
waste that has to be dealt with,

00:14:12.792 --> 00:14:20.492
what science is doing is working out, finding
power that nature has presented to us.

00:14:20.552 --> 00:14:24.412
This is not new. Fire
is like that too. Fire

00:14:24.492 --> 00:14:28.362
can burn down your house or it
can cook your steak. Power is

00:14:28.392 --> 00:14:32.252
like that, and that's just something
that we have to understand as

00:14:32.272 --> 00:14:36.162
humanity, and that's why this needs to be a--
you know, when we talk about science, it has

00:14:36.192 --> 00:14:39.172
to be a broad conversation
by all of society

00:14:39.232 --> 00:14:43.072
because what scientists
can do is figure out how

00:14:43.172 --> 00:14:47.092
the world works. Society has to
figure out how we wish to apply

00:14:47.152 --> 00:14:48.972
that or not apply that.

00:14:49.332 --> 00:14:53.282
- Also, solving the
mysteries and the puzzles

00:14:53.312 --> 00:14:56.432
of the universe in itself
is effing awesome.

00:14:56.672 --> 00:14:57.732
- It is. It is.

00:14:58.392 --> 00:15:01.302
- So that means that's the thing
that makes us human in part is

00:15:02.152 --> 00:15:05.421
looking at a thing and
saying, "How does this work?"

00:15:05.962 --> 00:15:09.932
And then together a bunch of apes
get together, like poke the thing,

00:15:10.032 --> 00:15:11.772
kinda shake the thing.

00:15:11.782 --> 00:15:15.532
And then over time you have
rockets going all into space. You

00:15:15.592 --> 00:15:19.092
build roads and bridges. You
build the internet. Anyway,

00:15:19.752 --> 00:15:23.162
so we talked about Newton, we talked
about Maxwell. That takes us into

00:15:23.512 --> 00:15:28.022
20th century in terms of unification.
There's a guy named Einstein-

00:15:28.022 --> 00:15:30.182
... on whom you wrote a book, who did-

00:15:30.232 --> 00:15:33.272
... quite a lot of progress
on the effort of unification.

00:15:33.812 --> 00:15:37.692
- Sure. So Einstein, he's
a pretty amazing guy.

00:15:37.792 --> 00:15:41.432
In 1905, he had his miracle
year where he wrote multiple

00:15:41.512 --> 00:15:44.902
papers. The one that most people
know about is special relativity,

00:15:45.132 --> 00:15:52.742
where he showed something that
makes no sense to anybody who's not

00:15:52.852 --> 00:15:56.412
really dug into it very
hard, and that is that two

00:15:56.432 --> 00:15:58.942
people experience time differently.

00:15:59.912 --> 00:16:03.632
Time, you know, is a fascinating
thing. We don't really understand what

00:16:03.692 --> 00:16:07.212
time is, which is weird. You'd think that that'd
be something we'd understand very well, but we

00:16:07.312 --> 00:16:11.212
really don't. We know a
lot about it, but really

00:16:11.232 --> 00:16:15.092
understanding it, not so
much. But Newton thought

00:16:15.132 --> 00:16:18.892
that time was just universal
for everyone, so my time, your

00:16:18.972 --> 00:16:22.652
time, some person's time on
Mars or on Alpha Centauri,

00:16:23.132 --> 00:16:26.452
everybody experienced time the
same. What Einstein showed

00:16:26.812 --> 00:16:30.752
was that that wasn't the case,
that different people moving at

00:16:30.872 --> 00:16:34.852
different speeds with respect to one
another experience time differently, which

00:16:34.892 --> 00:16:38.792
is absolutely a mind-blowing concept. Now,

00:16:39.392 --> 00:16:43.322
most people think that Einstein then
said, well, he invented spacetime, that,

00:16:43.352 --> 00:16:47.252
that space and time are the
same thing, and he was behind

00:16:47.292 --> 00:16:51.192
that. But that actual insight came
from one of his teachers, a guy

00:16:51.212 --> 00:16:54.912
by the name of Minkowski,
who looked at Einstein's

00:16:54.952 --> 00:16:58.572
equations. Minkowski was a little bit more
mathematically inclined than Einstein,

00:16:59.111 --> 00:17:03.772
and he saw that if you look at
the equations, you have basically

00:17:04.672 --> 00:17:08.292
one person's space and
time equals some numbers

00:17:08.372 --> 00:17:12.072
times this person's space
and time. And so that's kind

00:17:12.152 --> 00:17:19.432
of a staggering thing. So that is where
Einstein and Minkowski really did this

00:17:20.432 --> 00:17:24.172
unbelievable concept that space and time

00:17:24.572 --> 00:17:28.312
are actually pretty much the
same thing. That runs afoul of

00:17:28.432 --> 00:17:32.172
our understanding of how the
world works because time just

00:17:32.252 --> 00:17:36.022
moves, it's continuous. We know
what it is at a visceral level

00:17:38.492 --> 00:17:42.472
and an experiential level. We might not
understand it at a formal level, but we know what

00:17:42.512 --> 00:17:46.092
time is. It's what keeps, makes
today today and not yesterday or

00:17:46.252 --> 00:17:50.042
tomorrow. Space is a little different.
You can walk somewhere, you can walk

00:17:50.072 --> 00:17:53.932
back, you can move around. You have more freedom
to move in space than you have to move in time.

00:17:54.692 --> 00:17:58.292
You can always move forward in time. It's just
moving backwards that turns out to be a little more

00:17:58.312 --> 00:18:02.092
difficult. But yeah,
Einstein's understanding

00:18:02.172 --> 00:18:05.422
that that is the case, it caused everybody

00:18:06.352 --> 00:18:10.272
to think about the world very, very
differently, and that was in 1908

00:18:10.652 --> 00:18:14.332
when Minkowski really laid it
out in a strict spacetime.

00:18:15.042 --> 00:18:19.022
- And that also led to the
work on special relativity,

00:18:19.072 --> 00:18:21.472
led to the speed limit,
the speed of light.

00:18:21.952 --> 00:18:25.872
- Well, it was a premise. He had two
premises. One was that the laws of

00:18:25.912 --> 00:18:29.852
nature are the same for everybody, so
if you're moving at some speed, or

00:18:29.872 --> 00:18:31.072
if I'm moving at some speed,

00:18:31.892 --> 00:18:34.652
I can say I'm not moving and saying
you're moving at some speed.

00:18:35.532 --> 00:18:39.022
That's not controversial.
That is what we call Galilean

00:18:39.152 --> 00:18:43.012
relativity. It's from hundreds
of years ago. But what

00:18:43.072 --> 00:18:47.012
Einstein said that was controversial
was that everybody measures

00:18:47.032 --> 00:18:52.544
that the speed of light is
the same. Irrespective of

00:18:52.604 --> 00:18:55.844
how we're moving with respect to each other,
you'll measure the speed of light to be a

00:18:55.884 --> 00:18:59.744
number, I'll measure the speed of light to
a number, and that's very, very different

00:18:59.804 --> 00:19:02.664
from what Newton would've said or
Galileo or any of the old guys.

00:19:03.704 --> 00:19:07.424
And it was taking those two
things together that caused

00:19:07.744 --> 00:19:09.694
all of the weirdnesses
of special relativity.

00:19:10.564 --> 00:19:14.284
Now, you could then very
easily say, well, that

00:19:14.344 --> 00:19:18.844
second premise that everybody measures the
speed of light to the same is just dumb,

00:19:19.834 --> 00:19:23.484
and that, you know, you
could test that. So

00:19:24.344 --> 00:19:27.744
that's where testing relativity
comes in. And Einstein's

00:19:27.804 --> 00:19:31.584
equations, which include
those two assumptions, it

00:19:31.644 --> 00:19:36.534
predicts the behavior of everything
perfectly well. Now we've actually measured,

00:19:37.444 --> 00:19:41.164
done experiments where we can say that
the speed of light is the same for

00:19:41.204 --> 00:19:45.494
everybody. That's not how that's
been in the beginning. It was really

00:19:46.764 --> 00:19:50.584
that assumption leads to predictions. The
predictions are true, so the assumption is true.

00:19:51.124 --> 00:19:55.044
Now, there is a-- for those people,
for your viewers who wanna say, "Well,

00:19:55.144 --> 00:19:57.844
how do you measure that the speed
of light is the same for everyone?"

00:19:58.944 --> 00:20:02.444
The particle physicists do
this, and the way you do this

00:20:02.844 --> 00:20:06.004
is the following: There are
some subatomic particles

00:20:06.504 --> 00:20:10.304
that when they decay, they emit
light. That's their decay product.

00:20:10.984 --> 00:20:16.244
And so you collide two things together so
you know when the particle was created,

00:20:17.164 --> 00:20:21.724
then you have surrounded your
collision point by a detector,

00:20:22.764 --> 00:20:26.264
and you measure how long it takes

00:20:26.324 --> 00:20:30.104
for light to get to your detector,
and by God, it's the speed of

00:20:30.144 --> 00:20:33.694
light, which it should be.
However, sometimes in these

00:20:33.784 --> 00:20:37.644
collisions, some of these
subatomic particles you make are

00:20:37.684 --> 00:20:41.204
coming out at very high speed. They
might be coming out at ninety-five or

00:20:41.244 --> 00:20:44.604
ninety-seven or very large
fraction of the speed of light,

00:20:45.384 --> 00:20:51.614
and then they decay into photons. And so
you measure how long it takes for the

00:20:51.704 --> 00:20:55.304
photon to get to your detector, and it

00:20:55.384 --> 00:20:59.584
says it's-- light travels at the
speed of light. Now, if it were that

00:21:00.824 --> 00:21:04.634
if Einstein's conjecture was incorrect, you'd
have a particle coming out at near the speed of

00:21:04.704 --> 00:21:08.584
light, it would be decaying into a particle
traveling at the speed of light, then that

00:21:08.624 --> 00:21:12.544
particle should have traveled at, say, two times
the speed of light or something like that, so it

00:21:12.564 --> 00:21:16.004
should have taken half as much time to
get to the detector, but it doesn't.

00:21:16.824 --> 00:21:21.224
So this is a hard, serious measurement
that shows that something,

00:21:22.204 --> 00:21:26.034
you know, we can measure the
speed at which light comes out of

00:21:26.084 --> 00:21:30.064
this stationary created particle,
and it's the speed of light.

00:21:30.074 --> 00:21:33.674
Then we can measure what the speed is of
it coming out of something that's moving,

00:21:34.424 --> 00:21:38.134
and it's still the speed of light. So that
is an actual measurement, but that is not

00:21:38.164 --> 00:21:41.664
something that was possible in
Einstein's day- ... but it is now.

00:21:42.144 --> 00:21:45.394
- Just to take a small
tangent, how weird is it

00:21:46.344 --> 00:21:50.164
in the full ranking of weirdness
that is physics, how weird is it

00:21:50.224 --> 00:21:52.684
that there's that speed
limit of the speed of light?

00:21:53.184 --> 00:21:56.584
- Well, I have to tell you, when I first
encountered this, it's pretty freaking weird.

00:21:56.624 --> 00:22:03.454
It peaks the weird meter. But as
you become more familiar with

00:22:03.484 --> 00:22:07.184
it, as you become more
comfortable with the idea, the

00:22:07.344 --> 00:22:15.564
thing to remember is the speed of light,
it's the speed of light through spacetime.

00:22:16.404 --> 00:22:20.374
Once you embrace that, that makes a whole
ton of sense. It all of a sudden makes

00:22:20.404 --> 00:22:22.284
everything fall much more into place.

00:22:23.304 --> 00:22:27.034
I think that there is an
ultimate speed isn't that

00:22:27.044 --> 00:22:30.644
shocking. It just simply
says that it's a property of

00:22:30.764 --> 00:22:34.364
space in the same way
that there is, you know,

00:22:34.484 --> 00:22:38.394
space can transmit a certain
strength electric field. It can

00:22:38.424 --> 00:22:42.314
transmit-- it can support certain
things. Whatever space is,

00:22:42.364 --> 00:22:46.244
and we don't know what space is,
but whatever it is, it has the

00:22:46.284 --> 00:22:50.144
capability of transmitting
these things at that one

00:22:50.204 --> 00:22:53.864
speed through space or time,
and everything else comes from

00:22:53.964 --> 00:22:57.624
our insisting that we keep
space and time different.

00:22:57.964 --> 00:23:00.704
That's how I view it, and at least for me,

00:23:01.964 --> 00:23:06.864
that once I accepted that, it
all became very comfortable.

00:23:06.963 --> 00:23:09.434
- So the nature of my
question actually here-

00:23:09.434 --> 00:23:13.204
... that will apply over and over is
trying to empathize, trying to put

00:23:13.224 --> 00:23:17.584
ourselves in the shoes of the people
before space and time are unified-

00:23:17.604 --> 00:23:21.424
... into space time and
really experience and

00:23:21.464 --> 00:23:24.044
think through how difficult
of a leap is that.

00:23:24.464 --> 00:23:24.944
- Huge.

00:23:25.004 --> 00:23:27.884
- The reason I sort of say that is

00:23:29.144 --> 00:23:31.634
we are now in the modern day
in the twenty-first century,

00:23:32.484 --> 00:23:36.174
and of course, we're gonna have to
make leaps like that in our future.

00:23:36.464 --> 00:23:40.184
So what are the unifications
we're not seeing in front of our

00:23:40.224 --> 00:23:44.204
eyes? So for example, there's so many
examples through your work, through your

00:23:44.304 --> 00:23:51.094
lectures of Paul Dirac
taking antimatter seriously.

00:23:51.524 --> 00:23:57.194
Looking at what the math shows and saying,
"I really think this thing exists."

00:23:57.504 --> 00:23:59.264
I mean, it just sounds insane.

00:23:59.524 --> 00:23:59.824
- It does.

00:24:00.304 --> 00:24:04.794
- And so I think this is a good
warm-up. The space-time unification-

00:24:04.794 --> 00:24:08.724
... is a good warm-up as we march through
the twentieth century 'cause it gets

00:24:09.044 --> 00:24:13.304
in my view at least, weirder and
weirder, even with Einstein himself.

00:24:13.504 --> 00:24:18.264
- Well, let me give you an even more
basic example, sodium and chloride.

00:24:19.404 --> 00:24:23.324
Sodium is an explosive metal. You
put it in water and it's kind of

00:24:23.424 --> 00:24:27.354
neat. You put it in water, and it just, it
doesn't quite explode, but it gets hot, and

00:24:27.384 --> 00:24:31.124
it pops around. Chlorine, it's
a gas. It's going to kill you.

00:24:31.804 --> 00:24:36.714
So these two things are deadly. They're
awful. And yet when you mix them,

00:24:37.664 --> 00:24:41.644
you put it on your food at night.
It's salt, right? And so this

00:24:41.704 --> 00:24:45.044
is a case where, where this whole, A,

00:24:45.244 --> 00:24:48.804
unification and B, this deeper
understanding, in this case of

00:24:48.844 --> 00:24:52.530
chemistry, of how—Two things that

00:24:52.620 --> 00:24:56.190
are dangerous can be brought together
and turned into something not only

00:24:56.240 --> 00:24:59.610
innocuous, but necessary
for human life. And so this

00:24:59.700 --> 00:25:03.400
is not unusual, what
you're describing. I mean,

00:25:03.820 --> 00:25:07.620
when you think about it, forget about everything
else, just the fact that, you know, we tell

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:12.080
little kids, little kids, that
the world is made of atoms. Now,

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:16.140
that's crazy. Most people have never
seen atoms, and yet nobody really

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:19.499
doubts it anymore. And I
think it's just a case of

00:25:19.660 --> 00:25:23.480
familiarity, and then the
culture slowly accepts it, and

00:25:23.540 --> 00:25:27.490
it's then, it's real even without
the evidence. In fact, one of

00:25:27.580 --> 00:25:31.340
the courses you described there, How
We Know What We Know, I think that's a

00:25:31.360 --> 00:25:35.280
valid question. How do we know there are
atoms? And, and of course, there are ways we

00:25:35.300 --> 00:25:35.480
do.

00:25:35.700 --> 00:25:38.760
- And by the way, on that
front, I would love to go

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:42.540
through how we know the building
blocks in the universe as we

00:25:42.600 --> 00:25:46.320
march towards quarks. That, in the course
that you mentioned, is one of the most

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:52.180
fascinating things of this philosophy of
atoms being around for a very long time.

00:25:52.680 --> 00:25:56.430
Then you concretize and you
actually can prove or have

00:25:57.840 --> 00:26:01.700
strong observations that indicate
that there is atoms, and then there

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:05.640
is a nucleus, there is electrons,
there is photons, there is quarks and

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:09.240
I mean, it gets weirder and
weirder, and now we're facing the

00:26:09.300 --> 00:26:12.300
mystery is there's building
blocks even smaller than that.

00:26:12.340 --> 00:26:16.420
But anyway, Einstein, turns out,
didn't just do special relativity.

00:26:17.360 --> 00:26:21.320
By the way, I really think he deserves
three Nobel Prizes. He got it

00:26:21.400 --> 00:26:24.820
for photoelectric effect. The fact
that he didn't get it for general

00:26:24.880 --> 00:26:28.440
relativity is a crime against
humanity. I don't understand.

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:33.110
Obviously should have gotten it for general
relativity and, and special relativity.

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:37.120
I mean, I think special relativity is
separate for general relativity in

00:26:37.160 --> 00:26:42.520
as far as Nobel Prizes go. So general
relativity is another unification.

00:26:42.580 --> 00:26:47.100
- Yes, that's right. What Einstein realized
was that if you were in a rocket ship

00:26:47.900 --> 00:26:49.600
and the rocket ship

00:26:50.420 --> 00:26:54.400
was a very quiet rocket ship and it was accelerating,
it would feel like you were experiencing

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:58.970
gravity. And so as you say, it's one of
his happiest moments when he realized that

00:26:58.970 --> 00:27:02.490
acceleration and gravity
feel very much the same.

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:08.120
What I'm impressed by is that idea,
which is already a pretty neat idea,

00:27:09.520 --> 00:27:15.090
somehow led him to take his
space-time idea, take this

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:18.340
acceleration gravity idea, and realize

00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:22.680
that he could describe
gravity as the bending of

00:27:22.920 --> 00:27:26.960
space-time. Space-time being constant
like east, west, north, south,

00:27:28.040 --> 00:27:31.970
that's already hard enough. But now he's
saying, "Well, you know, take your,

00:27:32.300 --> 00:27:35.829
your map and crinkle it and bend
it," and so forth, and that's

00:27:35.860 --> 00:27:40.180
gravity. That is a staggering,
mind-blowing idea.

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:44.060
- I guess, I wonder if you can
comment on what do you think is the

00:27:45.040 --> 00:27:48.960
idea generation process that
leads to that. So probably an

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.720
Einstein case has to start
with what if gravity

00:27:53.480 --> 00:27:58.820
is itself space-time geometry? You, you
have to have a thought like that, right?

00:27:59.260 --> 00:28:04.920
- Yes, I think so. There's a lot about science.
There's, of course, knowing what went

00:28:04.980 --> 00:28:08.880
before. There is knowing the
mathematics that allows you to figure

00:28:08.930 --> 00:28:12.639
out the implications of your
theory. There is the discipline

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:16.860
to argue with yourself and other
people because most ideas are

00:28:16.900 --> 00:28:20.760
wrong. But then there's what you just
described, that intuitive spark,

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:25.000
and that is something that
is very, very difficult to,

00:28:25.800 --> 00:28:29.560
to create. There's a reason that
we venerate these people, is

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:36.419
because it is an unusual feature,
and most people only have that aha

00:28:36.480 --> 00:28:40.020
moment once in their lifetime,
if they have it at all.

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:44.580
And then there's a tricky
business because I'm sure you do,

00:28:44.620 --> 00:28:46.220
and I get a lot of letters from,

00:28:47.220 --> 00:28:50.960
from creative thinkers who
don't have all of the history

00:28:51.180 --> 00:28:54.980
and the mathematical
discipline and the self, you

00:28:55.020 --> 00:28:58.820
know, self-critique that's
necessary. And so they come up with

00:28:58.860 --> 00:29:04.160
these ideas, and often it's easy to
see where they just don't play out.

00:29:04.940 --> 00:29:08.920
So in order to be that
person who changes the way

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:12.760
we see the world, ideas
themselves are not enough. These

00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:16.400
creative ideas, that's not
enough. You need it with the

00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:21.290
discipline and the critique, and
it's that amalgam of those things

00:29:22.140 --> 00:29:26.180
that you know, make you a
genius that history remembers.

00:29:26.680 --> 00:29:30.590
- But it's hard to know. In a
field of people you might

00:29:30.860 --> 00:29:34.740
be tempted to call crazy, there could
be geniuses there, and it's hard

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:38.240
to know which is which. We should
mention that Einstein himself

00:29:40.660 --> 00:29:43.620
couldn't see the genius in
quantum mechanics initially,

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:48.420
couldn't see the correctness,
I should say. So he could

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:56.240
see the insanity of gravity bending
space-time, but quantum mechanics

00:29:56.280 --> 00:29:57.640
was too weird for Einstein.

00:29:57.840 --> 00:30:01.260
- In all fairness, it's
weird for me too. But...

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:05.280
... but the thing is, even while
that is true, and Einstein

00:30:05.320 --> 00:30:09.080
maybe spent the last few
years of his life trying to

00:30:09.100 --> 00:30:13.029
blend electricity and
magnetism and gravity in a,

00:30:13.029 --> 00:30:16.670
a single thing, and he was
unsuccessful, but he still was a

00:30:16.860 --> 00:30:20.250
very, very valuable critic—

00:30:20.250 --> 00:30:22.410
... of quantum mechanics. It's
not that he didn't understand it,

00:30:23.300 --> 00:30:26.980
because he did understand it. He thought
about the implications and all this quantum

00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:30.910
entanglement business, you know, not
all of it. But he was responsible

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.850
for saying, "Well, if you're
right, then this." And of course,

00:30:35.180 --> 00:30:38.320
then people went out and found
out that, that Einstein's

00:30:38.360 --> 00:30:41.740
implication of quantum mechanics was
real, and so they could say, "See?

00:30:42.340 --> 00:30:48.620
Quantum mechanics is real." So, you know,
he was thinking deeply about it, and he

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:52.770
was doing exactly that thing I said.
There's that spark idea, but there's that

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:58.220
critique idea. And if you're able to
critique an idea, you might kill it.

00:30:58.660 --> 00:31:02.288
And that is—it's always depressing
when I have this brilliant

00:31:02.348 --> 00:31:06.288
idea and it gets killed, but it's
better to be killed than to keep

00:31:06.328 --> 00:31:13.118
it around and waste time on it.
And so he was, in that case, not

00:31:13.168 --> 00:31:17.068
generating the aha, what he was saying

00:31:17.088 --> 00:31:20.708
is, "All right, let's take your aha.
Let's see it's right. What does it mean?

00:31:21.108 --> 00:31:28.428
It means this." That allows people to go
test it, and so he was contributing very

00:31:28.488 --> 00:31:32.148
crucially to that other part of scientific

00:31:32.168 --> 00:31:37.598
advancement, which is not just the aha
moment, but the beat it to death, test it-

00:31:37.598 --> 00:31:39.528
... critique it, and make sure it's real.

00:31:40.478 --> 00:31:44.308
And it's only after all of that
has been done that you really

00:31:44.348 --> 00:31:46.608
assure you're right. And
that's why science is such

00:31:47.428 --> 00:31:51.188
a powerful tool. It is that, that

00:31:51.208 --> 00:31:55.188
combative, just downright kinda
jerky critique that most people

00:31:55.228 --> 00:31:58.928
don't like. They don't like people saying,
"Uh, your ideas, you know, might be

00:31:58.968 --> 00:32:04.288
wrong." But that is-- it is crucial. It is
a crucial part of the scientific process.

00:32:04.928 --> 00:32:08.588
- Plus, there's that quote on the
other side of it that I've heard you

00:32:08.608 --> 00:32:15.268
mention, which is you know, "I believe your
idea is crazy, but is it crazy enough?"

00:32:15.808 --> 00:32:16.888
Was that Niels Bohr?

00:32:17.048 --> 00:32:20.608
- I love that one. Yes, yes, we all agree that
your idea is crazy, but is it crazy enough?

00:32:21.068 --> 00:32:24.958
- And there is some degree of
taking those leaps of crazy,

00:32:25.068 --> 00:32:27.468
but it has to be backed with rigor.

00:32:27.568 --> 00:32:27.788
- Right.

00:32:28.228 --> 00:32:34.028
- And the unifications continue that as we
take steps towards the Standard Model-

00:32:34.068 --> 00:32:37.908
... which is such an incredible part of physics
in the 20th century. So can you describe

00:32:37.928 --> 00:32:38.808
that unification?

00:32:39.108 --> 00:32:43.708
- So, you know, we're sort of jumping forward
here now to the 1930s or thereabout.

00:32:44.528 --> 00:32:48.848
And at, by that time, people
had realized that there are

00:32:49.908 --> 00:32:56.788
four distinct forces that do not seem
to be connected. One is gravity,

00:32:57.388 --> 00:33:01.328
two is electromagnetism, and those are
things people are relatively familiar with.

00:33:01.828 --> 00:33:05.288
But there are two other forces
that only have any real

00:33:05.348 --> 00:33:09.048
importance inside the nucleus of
atoms, which is why most people

00:33:09.128 --> 00:33:12.758
have no experience with them.
One is the strong nuclear

00:33:12.788 --> 00:33:16.728
force, which holds the nucleus of the atoms
together, and the other one is what we

00:33:16.788 --> 00:33:20.748
call the weak nuclear force, which
is responsible for some types

00:33:20.848 --> 00:33:24.828
of radioactivity. And since
most people don't play

00:33:24.868 --> 00:33:28.788
around with nuclei, and most people don't play
around with radioactivity, they don't know what

00:33:28.848 --> 00:33:32.118
that is. But by the '30s,

00:33:33.068 --> 00:33:36.968
scientists had done enough
experiments, done enough theorizing

00:33:37.028 --> 00:33:40.908
to say that there were
these four forces, and

00:33:40.968 --> 00:33:44.868
that was already a triumph.
I mean, we, in our goal for

00:33:44.888 --> 00:33:48.868
a theory of everything, we'd like to think that
there is one force, which is what we're talking

00:33:48.908 --> 00:33:52.828
about, the unification. Maybe these
four forces are just different ways

00:33:52.868 --> 00:33:55.578
of looking at a single underlying
force. But in the '30s,

00:33:56.548 --> 00:34:01.508
that's where we were. There were
the four forces. So we move ahead,

00:34:02.408 --> 00:34:10.038
and in the late '50s and early
'60s, some people were thinking

00:34:10.038 --> 00:34:17.208
that maybe the weak nuclear force and
electromagnetism actually were the same.

00:34:18.368 --> 00:34:22.288
So they were working on trying
to bring together these

00:34:22.328 --> 00:34:24.228
two forces to show that they're connected.

00:34:25.068 --> 00:34:28.478
And it came true. They
were able to show that

00:34:28.508 --> 00:34:32.368
electricity and magnetism
were actually two

00:34:32.428 --> 00:34:37.078
different facets of a single force that
we now call the electroweak force.

00:34:37.548 --> 00:34:41.008
Now, the story that you're told in

00:34:41.508 --> 00:34:45.188
articles about this, about what
people have called the Higgs

00:34:45.248 --> 00:34:49.698
boson or the God particle, the
story is very, very simplified

00:34:50.848 --> 00:34:58.028
because in 1964, there were three
groups with six individuals

00:34:58.708 --> 00:35:02.408
who came up with important
papers talking about

00:35:02.508 --> 00:35:06.408
what's called the Higgs field. And I'll get back, get to
what that is in a minute, but the Higgs field is important.

00:35:06.988 --> 00:35:10.048
But it wasn't until 1967,
so three years later,

00:35:10.768 --> 00:35:14.068
that Steven Weinberg and some others

00:35:14.868 --> 00:35:17.928
actually unified electromagnetism
and the weak force.

00:35:18.388 --> 00:35:21.948
- Sheldon Glashow, Abdus Salam, and Steven

00:35:22.027 --> 00:35:25.628
Weinberg successfully unified
electromagnetism and the weak nuclear

00:35:25.728 --> 00:35:29.588
force that showing that at high energies-

00:35:30.328 --> 00:35:30.568
- Right

00:35:30.578 --> 00:35:34.728
- ... these two forces were merged
into a single electroweak force.

00:35:34.848 --> 00:35:38.468
- Right, and that was in '67,
all right? Everybody talks

00:35:38.568 --> 00:35:42.508
about this thing happening in '64,
but it really wasn't. It happened

00:35:42.588 --> 00:35:46.528
over quite a few years
actually. But all right, so now

00:35:46.588 --> 00:35:53.558
let's-- what you said is true. So
Weinberg, Glashow, and Salam showed that

00:35:53.588 --> 00:35:56.928
electromagnetism and the weak force
at high energies were the same.

00:35:57.408 --> 00:36:00.748
There was a problem,
however, and the problem

00:36:00.888 --> 00:36:04.608
is that electromagnetism
has an infinite range,

00:36:05.528 --> 00:36:09.148
And we know that because we can see
stars that are millions of light-years

00:36:09.208 --> 00:36:15.428
away. I mean, that shows you that the range
of that force is essentially infinite.

00:36:15.638 --> 00:36:22.928
The weak force, however basically becomes
nonexistent on distances much smaller

00:36:23.248 --> 00:36:25.508
than the size of a proton.

00:36:25.578 --> 00:36:29.468
So that, you know, to say, "Oh, they're
the same," and yet one can reach

00:36:29.508 --> 00:36:33.158
across the universe and one can't reach
out of an atom, well, that's just

00:36:33.168 --> 00:36:34.868
dumb. I mean, the obvious

00:36:36.348 --> 00:36:40.068
thought here is, well, we just
proved that that whole idea is

00:36:40.128 --> 00:36:44.048
stupid, so throw it away.
Ridiculous. And that

00:36:44.128 --> 00:36:49.368
is where these ideas from 1964
came in and saved the day. So

00:36:50.368 --> 00:36:58.268
how can it be true that the electroweak
force is real and electromagnetism

00:36:58.868 --> 00:37:01.698
and the weak force act so differently?

00:37:02.688 --> 00:37:08.956
The way that could happen is if
these forces were transmitted

00:37:09.696 --> 00:37:15.376
by a particle moving from one
subatomic particle to the other.

00:37:16.436 --> 00:37:18.596
In the case of electromagnetism,
it's the photon.

00:37:19.516 --> 00:37:23.426
In the case of the weak
force, we call them now

00:37:23.456 --> 00:37:27.426
the W and Z particles. So the idea is

00:37:27.496 --> 00:37:31.506
that Higgs and his colleagues came
up with is saying, "All right,

00:37:32.656 --> 00:37:34.056
electroweak force is real.

00:37:35.756 --> 00:37:39.716
The way we make it so that
there is now an electromagnetic

00:37:39.856 --> 00:37:47.296
force and a weak force is the force-carrying
particle of electromagnetism has no

00:37:47.336 --> 00:37:52.636
mass. The force-carrying
particle of the weak force has

00:37:52.656 --> 00:37:59.745
a mass." And so what
was done is a field was

00:37:59.896 --> 00:38:03.856
postulated that there was
this additional field

00:38:03.936 --> 00:38:07.926
that was kind of distinct
from this electroweak field,

00:38:08.296 --> 00:38:13.156
and we call it the Higgs field. And the
Higgs field permeates all of space.

00:38:14.336 --> 00:38:18.196
And here's the kicker, some
particles interact with the

00:38:18.236 --> 00:38:22.136
field, and some particles don't
interact with the field. The ones

00:38:22.196 --> 00:38:25.746
that interact with the field get
mass, and the ones that don't

00:38:25.776 --> 00:38:28.366
interact with the field
don't have mass. And

00:38:28.456 --> 00:38:34.876
so that's the idea, is that the Higgs
field gives the weak force particles mass.

00:38:35.546 --> 00:38:40.536
However, the photon laughs at the Higgs
field, doesn't see it, and it has no mass.

00:38:40.976 --> 00:38:44.556
- And I should say here, going
to Perplexity, the big-picture

00:38:44.636 --> 00:38:48.456
view, the Higgs field is the quantum
field that fills all of space and gives

00:38:48.476 --> 00:38:52.456
many elementary particles, just
as you're saying, their mass

00:38:52.466 --> 00:38:56.456
through their interaction with it.
The Higgs boson is the particle

00:38:56.476 --> 00:39:00.396
associated with ripples or
excitations of this field.

00:39:01.156 --> 00:39:05.136
In modern particle physics, every type of
particle corresponds to a field that exists

00:39:05.216 --> 00:39:09.136
everywhere. The Higgs field
is one such scalar field,

00:39:09.576 --> 00:39:13.496
meaning at each point in space,
it has a single numerical

00:39:13.596 --> 00:39:17.456
value rather than a direction.
The Higgs field differs

00:39:17.536 --> 00:39:21.116
from most other fields
because even in empty space,

00:39:21.436 --> 00:39:25.296
empty in quotes, by the way,
empty space, its average

00:39:25.356 --> 00:39:29.156
value is not zero. This non-zero
vacuum value is what enables

00:39:29.216 --> 00:39:31.496
it to endow particles with mass.

00:39:31.796 --> 00:39:35.696
- Right. So let's talk about something
a little more familiar just to try

00:39:35.716 --> 00:39:38.766
and hang some, some
intuition on those words.

00:39:38.896 --> 00:39:39.196
- Mm-hmm. Awesome.

00:39:39.216 --> 00:39:43.086
- All right, so right in front of us,
there is a gravitational field. Now-

00:39:43.116 --> 00:39:45.936
... you can't see it, but right
there. Right there. Check it out.

00:39:46.216 --> 00:39:46.316
- Yep.

00:39:47.076 --> 00:39:50.236
- If I were to take something, a pen
or whatever, and put it there,

00:39:50.936 --> 00:39:53.276
it feels a force, and it falls.

00:39:53.976 --> 00:39:57.716
Very insightful, I know. So
we have the gravity field,

00:39:58.136 --> 00:40:02.065
and we have the pen that has a
mass, and the mass and the gravity

00:40:02.196 --> 00:40:07.405
field interact, and it drops.
Now- ... if we had another-

00:40:07.856 --> 00:40:08.896
- I have a-

00:40:08.996 --> 00:40:09.176
- Oh, yes

00:40:09.186 --> 00:40:09.826
- ... object for you.

00:40:09.856 --> 00:40:10.405
- All right, so like-

00:40:10.436 --> 00:40:11.405
- Demonstration purposes. This is great.

00:40:11.416 --> 00:40:13.076
- Performance art. Here we go.

00:40:13.316 --> 00:40:13.616
- This is great.

00:40:13.636 --> 00:40:15.476
- This thing has mass, and we drop it.

00:40:16.816 --> 00:40:20.736
How remarkable. It falls. But
when we step back and think about

00:40:20.796 --> 00:40:23.076
what really happens, it's
the mass of this thing

00:40:23.936 --> 00:40:27.836
and the interaction with
this invisible field we see

00:40:27.896 --> 00:40:30.136
here. That's what gives this weight.

00:40:30.656 --> 00:40:34.976
Now, I have this particle here that you
can't see, but it's there. It has no mass.

00:40:36.056 --> 00:40:41.506
And I leave it there. Well, since it has
no mass, it doesn't feel gravity. It's

00:40:41.596 --> 00:40:47.536
still floating there. And that is
really all the Higgs field is. Some

00:40:47.576 --> 00:40:51.256
particles have effectively what you
could call the Higgs charge that

00:40:51.316 --> 00:40:54.845
interacts and sees the field,
and other particles don't. And

00:40:55.016 --> 00:40:58.656
and that is really what you read just

00:40:58.676 --> 00:41:02.536
basically means. Now, it's
kinda neat because in the

00:41:02.896 --> 00:41:06.726
ordinary day, there is a Higgs field
right there, and the Higgs field is

00:41:06.836 --> 00:41:10.676
not zero, just like gravity is not
zero, and things will get mass. But

00:41:10.716 --> 00:41:11.916
at super high energies,

00:41:12.916 --> 00:41:16.856
the Higgs field, the strength of the Higgs
field goes to zero. So whether things have mass

00:41:17.016 --> 00:41:20.796
or whether they have a Higgs charge or
not, they have no or they have the Higgs

00:41:20.856 --> 00:41:22.156
charge, Higgs field zero,

00:41:23.276 --> 00:41:27.136
they don't interact. It has no
mass. So that's kind of what,

00:41:27.176 --> 00:41:30.996
uh, Weinberg and Salam and Glashow
said, is at very high energies,

00:41:32.056 --> 00:41:33.256
the Higgs field is zero.

00:41:34.196 --> 00:41:38.076
Since the Higgs field is zero,
the weak force particles don't

00:41:38.116 --> 00:41:42.096
feel mass, and therefore, they can travel
at the speed of light, just like the

00:41:42.136 --> 00:41:45.036
photon does, and everything's happy.

00:41:45.296 --> 00:41:49.236
It is when the universe cooled
down. After the Big Bang, it

00:41:49.276 --> 00:41:52.256
was very hot, very high
energy. Nothing had mass.

00:41:53.176 --> 00:41:55.666
The universe cooled, and
at a certain temperature,

00:41:56.676 --> 00:42:00.376
what happened is the Higgs field turned
on. And at the moment it turned on,

00:42:00.936 --> 00:42:04.886
it gave mass to the weak force
particles, did not give mass to the

00:42:04.936 --> 00:42:08.726
photon. So that's what we call
electroweak symmetry breaking,

00:42:08.896 --> 00:42:12.536
so it's a mouthful. But all it
says is there was a moment in time

00:42:12.656 --> 00:42:16.476
early in the history of the universe at
10 to the minus 12 seconds after the Big

00:42:16.536 --> 00:42:24.036
Bang, the Higgs field turned on and
particles got mass. So that's the whole

00:42:24.136 --> 00:42:27.956
idea. So this is another
really neat thing. So the

00:42:28.016 --> 00:42:31.916
electroweak symmetry theory
doesn't need Higgs because that

00:42:31.976 --> 00:42:35.836
only really applies at
very, very high energies.

00:42:36.556 --> 00:42:40.516
But in order to make it work
at low energies, you need

00:42:40.556 --> 00:42:43.856
to fix the theory, and you
need to fix the theory by

00:42:43.916 --> 00:42:47.786
effectively putting a Band-Aid on
the theory. Higgs theory is just

00:42:47.786 --> 00:42:51.636
a Band-Aid on top of electroweak
symmetry theory, and

00:42:51.716 --> 00:42:57.196
that is the Band-Aid that fixes it because
it gives mass to particles at low energy.

00:42:57.276 --> 00:43:01.206
- But how does then the Higgs—
this Band-Aid, the field and

00:43:01.356 --> 00:43:06.916
the Higgs boson come into play on the
experimental front, on the evidence-

00:43:07.256 --> 00:43:07.476
- Okay.

00:43:07.576 --> 00:43:08.436
- ... discovery front?

00:43:08.536 --> 00:43:08.546
- Right.

00:43:08.556 --> 00:43:10.395
- So what is this Higgs boson thing then?

00:43:10.456 --> 00:43:14.256
- Okay, excellent. So we have never
seen the Higgs field. Higgs field

00:43:14.336 --> 00:43:19.740
is a hypothetical theoretical
thing. But that is true

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:23.920
of most of our fields. We've never seen the
electromagnetic field. We've never seen the

00:43:23.940 --> 00:43:27.540
gravity field. We've seen the effect
of the field. And so all of these

00:43:27.720 --> 00:43:31.620
theories are now what we call
quantum field theories, and that--

00:43:31.660 --> 00:43:36.620
the whole idea of quantum fields,
if you have a quantum field,

00:43:37.510 --> 00:43:41.500
but that field can vibrate
like a drumhead. And so it

00:43:41.540 --> 00:43:45.500
doesn't vibrate just exactly like a
drumhead, but it vibrates locally. So you

00:43:45.560 --> 00:43:49.250
can have specific localized
vibrations, and those

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:53.310
specific localized vibrations are the
particles. In the electromagnetic field,

00:43:53.380 --> 00:43:58.220
the vibration is the photon. In the Higgs
field, the vibration is the Higgs boson.

00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:05.040
And so what we can do is not
see the field, but we can

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:11.500
actually excite the field, make it vibrate,
and detect the vibrations. So the Higgs

00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:15.840
boson idea was predicted
in sixty-four. It became

00:44:15.900 --> 00:44:20.540
useful in sixty-seven, and then
scientists started looking for it. So

00:44:21.440 --> 00:44:27.680
in the early 2000s, people were starting
to think that we had built particle

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:31.720
accelerators powerful
enough to actually to

00:44:31.740 --> 00:44:35.540
be able to create these
vibrations and detect them.

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:39.330
So the accelerator that was
working at the time was

00:44:39.330 --> 00:44:44.210
a large particle accelerator outside
Chicago at Fermilab called the Tevatron.

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:48.380
And we were colliding protons and
antimatter protons at near the speed of

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:49.360
light at very high energy,

00:44:50.180 --> 00:44:54.360
and that was the accelerator at which the
top quark was discovered in ninety-five.

00:44:55.220 --> 00:44:58.800
But we had upgraded our
apparatus. We had ten

00:44:58.920 --> 00:45:02.410
times the number of collisions per
second. We had slightly more energy,

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:06.520
and we were banging the protons and
the antimatter protons together,

00:45:06.580 --> 00:45:09.660
hoping that we would actually
find the Higgs boson.

00:45:09.720 --> 00:45:13.340
- Can you actually back up a little bit
and look at the bigger picture? So

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:17.200
Fermilab has this legendary
accelerator that there's

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:21.220
also a personal story with you connected
to it because, I mean, there's a million

00:45:21.260 --> 00:45:25.140
questions I wanna ask you, and
we'll ask you about some aspects of

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:28.860
that. So this idea of an
accelerator, the design and the

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:32.270
physics of an accelerator, how is
that productive for understanding

00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:36.880
and discovering different
aspects of particle physics?

00:45:37.400 --> 00:45:42.380
- Well, I'm so glad you asked I mean,
this is fascinating. All right.

00:45:42.740 --> 00:45:46.640
Everybody has heard Einstein's
equation E equals MC squared. Nobody

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:50.640
knows what it means. Maybe they heard that energy
equals mass and mass equals energy. I don't know.

00:45:50.900 --> 00:45:54.820
You know. But they've heard the equation,
the most famous equation in all of science.

00:45:56.400 --> 00:46:04.000
But buried inside that equation is a really
thoroughly fascinating concept, that

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:11.060
energy and matter are equivalent, and you
can, in fact, convert movement energy

00:46:11.160 --> 00:46:17.590
into mass. And so this is something
that we've known for a long time. This

00:46:17.640 --> 00:46:21.280
was predicted back in basically 1928,

00:46:21.700 --> 00:46:25.690
so a long time ago, actually
almost a hundred years ago. And

00:46:26.020 --> 00:46:29.789
it is not in the slightest bit
controversial. We can do this all the

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:33.520
time. So the simplest thing is to take two

00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:38.420
particles that have no structure, so, you

00:46:38.460 --> 00:46:42.380
know, the closest thing you can
have to BBs that are just true

00:46:42.420 --> 00:46:46.110
mathematical BBs. If you smash
those two things together,

00:46:46.420 --> 00:46:50.120
it's coming in with a huge amount of energy
from one direction, a huge amount of

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:54.020
energy from the other direction.
The directions cancel, so the

00:46:54.160 --> 00:46:57.980
net momentum, the net energy of this
has no motion. So you have these two

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:01.170
things coming in with a, you
know, exactly balanced energy,

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:03.560
and if they collide, they could stop.

00:47:04.400 --> 00:47:08.340
Well, that energy has to go
somewhere, and that energy

00:47:08.400 --> 00:47:11.580
can literally create
mass, create particles.

00:47:12.080 --> 00:47:15.960
Now, there are special rules about
what happens. If you have two things

00:47:15.970 --> 00:47:19.660
coming together and it creates a
particle, it has to create an antimatter

00:47:19.700 --> 00:47:22.890
particle to balance it. That's just
kind of the rules of the laws of

00:47:22.920 --> 00:47:26.700
nature. Why is that the case?
Well, we have some ideas,

00:47:26.840 --> 00:47:30.539
but in many respects, the answer is
because those are the laws of the

00:47:30.580 --> 00:47:33.830
universe, and that's the things
that we try to understand.

00:47:33.919 --> 00:47:36.760
But this is absolutely true. So what,

00:47:37.740 --> 00:47:41.650
what particle accelerators do,
among other things, is simply

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:50.090
transform energy into particles.
And so basically, any particle

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:54.020
that doesn't exist in nature, we
can make in this way. You can

00:47:54.080 --> 00:47:57.990
make the antimatter electron
by taking two particles,

00:47:58.100 --> 00:48:01.900
smashing them together. The energy
sits there, and it will make an

00:48:01.920 --> 00:48:05.700
electron and an antimatter electron,
and it just does. And we know

00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:09.620
that. The antimatter electron
was discovered in 1932.

00:48:10.280 --> 00:48:14.050
This is all pretty easy.
The antimatter proton was

00:48:14.060 --> 00:48:17.180
discovered in 1955 at
the Berkeley Bevatron.

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:20.860
And so this is just what
you do. You can convert

00:48:21.580 --> 00:48:25.240
energy into a matter-antimatter
particle. Now, the

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:29.180
converse goes true, and that's something we
might talk about. You can take matter and

00:48:29.260 --> 00:48:32.970
antimatter and bring it together,
and it'll make energy. It's the

00:48:34.560 --> 00:48:38.450
the process can go both ways. Energy
can make matter and antimatter.

00:48:38.940 --> 00:48:42.929
Matter and antimatter can make energy,
and this is just true. We do it

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.050
all the time. There's no
question that this is the case.

00:48:45.070 --> 00:48:48.940
- And we should also mention that
this is the reason why Fermilab

00:48:48.980 --> 00:48:52.880
had a nice stash of
antimatter particles. So

00:48:52.960 --> 00:48:56.640
as a side effect, you can also collect
antimatter in this kind of way.

00:48:57.040 --> 00:48:59.970
You can produce antimatter, but
it's at an extremely costly-

00:49:00.340 --> 00:49:04.320
- Oh, very, very costly. In
order at, at the Fermilab

00:49:04.360 --> 00:49:09.119
machine, we would have to smash
100,000 protons into something

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:14.420
to make one antimatter proton.
So I mean, it took some work.

00:49:14.780 --> 00:49:21.780
- Is there some extremely precise recipe of
being able to produce particular kinds of

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:25.480
particles and all this kind of stuff?
When you smash two things together,

00:49:25.620 --> 00:49:29.380
together, is there like how
can you control accurately

00:49:29.940 --> 00:49:31.840
which kind of particles
you're trying to produce?

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:35.900
- If you wanna make antimatter
electrons, you smash together

00:49:35.980 --> 00:49:39.580
energy at a certain-- It's just

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:43.630
easier with electrons because the electrons,
to the best of our knowledge, have

00:49:43.630 --> 00:49:47.140
nothing inside them, so they're
simple. They have a certain mass,

00:49:47.560 --> 00:49:51.400
and that's that. So if you smash particles
together with the right energy, you

00:49:51.420 --> 00:49:55.170
can make them very, very easily
because you can-- It's like a old

00:49:55.320 --> 00:49:59.000
style radio back in the day where you had
to dial it in. You could get right on the

00:49:59.040 --> 00:50:02.340
station, and you could hear the, the signal,
and if you were off a little, it didn't work.

00:50:03.460 --> 00:50:07.440
The problem for things like protons
and so forth is they're not point-like

00:50:07.500 --> 00:50:10.780
particles. They're kind of like garbage
cans full of stuff, and so it's very

00:50:10.820 --> 00:50:17.060
difficult to make antimatter protons.
Now, you can get more of them

00:50:17.260 --> 00:50:20.900
by increasing the energy at which you

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:24.910
collide two particles together. If
you're at below a certain energy,

00:50:25.560 --> 00:50:29.550
the-- and say you collide two protons
together at kind of low energy,

00:50:29.920 --> 00:50:33.150
you just don't have enough
energy to make an antiproton.

00:50:33.240 --> 00:50:37.130
And so it doesn't happen. You get
to a certain energy, and you can

00:50:37.240 --> 00:50:41.110
just barely make them. The more
energy you collide them together,

00:50:41.140 --> 00:50:44.940
the more you make. So that is just
sort of how it works. More is better.

00:50:45.460 --> 00:50:49.420
- And then with CERN, if you
compare maybe CERN and

00:50:49.480 --> 00:50:53.460
Fermilab, going to Perplexity
here, CERN's accelerator, the

00:50:53.520 --> 00:50:57.170
Large Hadron Collider, LHC,
is the world's highest energy

00:50:57.240 --> 00:51:00.700
proton collider, while Fermilab's
current and planned accelerators

00:51:01.200 --> 00:51:04.980
focus on intense proton
beams for neutrino physics-

00:51:05.400 --> 00:51:05.410
- Correct

00:51:05.410 --> 00:51:09.290
- ... rather than pushing the absolute
energy frontier. Absolute energy

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:15.940
frontier meaning highest possible
energy smashing of protons together.

00:51:16.200 --> 00:51:20.960
- Correct. So one, we were talking
about, like, accumulating antimatter.

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:24.980
All right? And so there, that

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:28.780
is typically making antiprotons,
as opposed to making all

00:51:28.820 --> 00:51:32.849
particles in general. So let's focus
on the antiproton side to begin with.

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:33.180
All right?

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:37.820
So Fermilab doesn't make antiprotons
anymore. We stopped making them in 2011,

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:42.340
and it's because we shut our big
accelerator down to concentrate

00:51:42.420 --> 00:51:50.540
on a different facet of particle physics.
However, at the time, we would smash

00:51:50.760 --> 00:51:54.420
protons with an energy of 120 GeV,

00:51:55.240 --> 00:51:58.800
and in that, we would make antiprotons.
So that's a ton of energy.

00:52:00.540 --> 00:52:04.090
It's true that the CERN
accelerator, the big accelerator,

00:52:04.500 --> 00:52:08.420
is now much higher energy than
the Fermilab accelerator was. No

00:52:08.460 --> 00:52:12.199
problem. But that's not
how they make antiprotons.

00:52:12.960 --> 00:52:16.640
The-- A-all of these big
beam big laboratories,

00:52:17.580 --> 00:52:21.460
it's not one accelerator. At Fermilab, there
were five distinct accelerators, and it

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:25.420
was basically like shifting an old standard
car, 'cause you couldn't just go zero

00:52:25.480 --> 00:52:29.380
to super speed in one accelerator.
You had to go from one to another,

00:52:29.460 --> 00:52:33.340
getting higher and higher.
Well, at CERN, they use

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:37.300
one of the, basically their
second gear in their very

00:52:37.400 --> 00:52:41.000
big accelerator complex to
make antimatter protons, and

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:47.289
their accelerator is only 26 GeV
compared to the 120 GeV at Fermilab.

00:52:47.600 --> 00:52:51.540
Fermilab's not operating, but when
it was operating, it operated at

00:52:51.580 --> 00:52:55.020
an energy about four times higher
than what CERN is doing now.

00:52:55.570 --> 00:52:59.500
And why is that? Well, it's
because what CERN needs to do

00:52:59.640 --> 00:53:03.060
is to not make as many
antiprotons as Fermilab did.

00:53:03.540 --> 00:53:07.340
They are doing a very different current
experimental program. They're doing

00:53:07.440 --> 00:53:10.960
a fascinating experimental program,
including trying to figure out does

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:14.840
antigravity fall up or down, which is
kinda neat. And we sort of know the answer

00:53:14.920 --> 00:53:21.020
to that. That's separate. But anyways, so
getting back to the antiproton business-

00:53:21.120 --> 00:53:24.000
... while Fermilab doesn't do it
now, it was top dog. It's not

00:53:24.060 --> 00:53:27.380
anymore. The only really big antiproton

00:53:27.460 --> 00:53:31.620
accelerator creator is a
small accelerator at CERN.

00:53:31.660 --> 00:53:35.750
Okay, so that's the antiproton thing, and if we
get back to antimatter, we can talk about that-

00:53:35.750 --> 00:53:36.900
... 'cause that is way cool.

00:53:36.940 --> 00:53:37.580
- Yeah, super cool.

00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:40.500
- But now the other side of
your thing about making

00:53:40.660 --> 00:53:44.840
high-energy unknown
particles, bigger is better.

00:53:44.910 --> 00:53:48.800
And it is true that the LHC is a
very high-energy machine. It is

00:53:48.860 --> 00:53:52.560
about seven times more powerful
in terms of energy per

00:53:52.620 --> 00:53:56.040
collision. It is also about 100 times more

00:53:56.060 --> 00:54:03.560
collisions per second than the Fermilab
machine. So it is true that the LHC can make

00:54:03.640 --> 00:54:10.640
bigger, heavier particles that the old
Fermilab, the Tevatron, ever could.

00:54:11.140 --> 00:54:14.960
And that is true. So if you wanna look
at high-energy stuff, yeah, you go to

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:20.420
CERN now, which is why many of my
colleagues, including myself, once we had

00:54:21.340 --> 00:54:25.260
measured all of the sort of
frontier measurements we thought we

00:54:25.300 --> 00:54:29.180
could make with the Fermilab
accelerator, we saw

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:33.090
this bigger, more powerful machine with
seven times the energy and 100 times

00:54:33.180 --> 00:54:37.120
more collisions per second. We
said, "Heck yeah, let's go work

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:40.640
on that." And to give you a sense of
scale, the top quark, which is the

00:54:40.680 --> 00:54:44.440
heaviest particle ever discovered,
discovered at Fermilab in

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:48.440
1995, there were two discovery
papers, and the one on which I was a

00:54:48.580 --> 00:54:52.080
co-author, we had worked
for a good chunk of

00:54:52.460 --> 00:54:56.340
between six months and a year of
collecting collisions, and there were

00:54:56.400 --> 00:55:00.420
a lot of collisions, and our paper had 38

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:05.240
top quark candidates. 38. And we knew that

00:55:05.260 --> 00:55:09.180
half of them were crap because when you
make a detector like that, there's what you

00:55:09.220 --> 00:55:13.040
call background, so you have the background and
the good stuff, and we know it was about 50/50.

00:55:13.120 --> 00:55:16.850
So we had maybe 19 top
quarks after working

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:22.200
for between six months and a year of
collecting data. But now, at the LHC,

00:55:23.040 --> 00:55:28.004
we make a top quark every
second. And that's what

00:55:28.124 --> 00:55:32.044
higher energy and more collisions per
second will do for you. That extra energy,

00:55:32.604 --> 00:55:36.463
you're above threshold, you make a
ton of them, and when you compare

00:55:36.504 --> 00:55:40.284
the 1995 Fermilab
accelerator to the current

00:55:41.104 --> 00:55:44.424
CERN accelerator, it's probably 1,000
times of collisions per second.

00:55:44.904 --> 00:55:48.384
So it went from
painstaking, pulling teeth,

00:55:48.444 --> 00:55:52.314
to, yeah, now top quarks are a background.
We try to get rid of them. There's just

00:55:52.364 --> 00:55:56.254
too many of them. They get in the way
of searching for the stuff we really

00:55:56.324 --> 00:55:58.824
wanna search. They are,
like, so 30 years ago.

00:55:59.234 --> 00:56:02.824
- By the way, is there something to be
said about the kind of sort of signal

00:56:02.844 --> 00:56:06.814
processing here, how you remove the
noise, how you remove the background,

00:56:07.324 --> 00:56:09.344
how you determine which particle is which?

00:56:09.454 --> 00:56:11.664
There's probably some, like,
incredible nuance there,

00:56:12.784 --> 00:56:14.584
even outside of the scope
of this conversation.

00:56:14.784 --> 00:56:18.544
- So let me just throw some numbers
out, all right? So at the

00:56:18.584 --> 00:56:22.334
CERN accelerator, when it's
operating, the collisions occur at a

00:56:22.424 --> 00:56:27.164
prodigious rate. We get about a billion,
with a B, collisions per second.

00:56:28.044 --> 00:56:29.704
Now, each one of those

00:56:29.824 --> 00:56:29.834
- Wow.

00:56:29.844 --> 00:56:30.914
- Yeah, yeah, that's what I said.

00:56:30.984 --> 00:56:31.603
- Wow.

00:56:31.644 --> 00:56:35.274
- Now, it turns out some of them are happening
at the same time, so there's about, of

00:56:35.364 --> 00:56:41.384
order 40 million moments in time per
second where you would take a shot,

00:56:41.444 --> 00:56:46.304
and inside that moment, there
might be 20 collisions.

00:56:46.454 --> 00:56:48.054
So that's why we get to the billion.

00:56:48.384 --> 00:56:51.484
- Yeah, but can you individually
pinpoint the collisions?

00:56:51.604 --> 00:56:55.644
- Sort of, to a degree. So
the beams are, you know...

00:56:56.604 --> 00:57:00.263
When people think of beams, they think of,
like, laser beams, but that's not really what

00:57:00.304 --> 00:57:04.054
particle beams look like. Particle
beams look like little tiny

00:57:04.244 --> 00:57:08.084
sticks of spaghetti, except they're much
thinner. They're not as fat as a stick of

00:57:08.144 --> 00:57:12.124
spaghetti, and they're
at the LHC, different

00:57:12.204 --> 00:57:16.144
accelerators are different, they're about
this long. And so you have one of them going

00:57:16.244 --> 00:57:17.754
one way full of protons--

00:57:18.044 --> 00:57:22.364
...and another one going the other way full
of protons, and they pass through each other.

00:57:22.424 --> 00:57:23.014
And as they--

00:57:23.014 --> 00:57:26.354
...pass through each other, you should
think of this as like a swarm of bees.

00:57:26.404 --> 00:57:26.724
- Yep.

00:57:26.764 --> 00:57:30.654
- And this is like a swarm of bees, and
mostly the bees pass through each other and

00:57:30.704 --> 00:57:34.504
don't do anything. But every so often,
some of the bees hit nose on and

00:57:35.644 --> 00:57:38.544
stripes and wings and
everything everywhere.

00:57:38.664 --> 00:57:39.244
- That's awesome. That's awesome.

00:57:39.284 --> 00:57:43.024
- And so as they collide through each
other, you know, one collision's

00:57:43.084 --> 00:57:46.404
here, and one's here, and one's
here. And you can't tell too much

00:57:46.904 --> 00:57:50.664
side to side because the beams are really
small. They're sort of the thickness of a

00:57:50.704 --> 00:57:51.684
human hair.

00:57:51.704 --> 00:57:55.504
But you can see along the direction. And
they're, you know, this is about the

00:57:55.544 --> 00:57:59.444
right size. And so we have
detectors around them, and

00:57:59.484 --> 00:58:03.774
we can actually see, oh, particles came
from here, and particles came from here.

00:58:04.064 --> 00:58:06.184
And that's amazing. All right. So

00:58:07.144 --> 00:58:10.824
at any one crossing, there's
maybe 20 collisions. Now, most

00:58:10.924 --> 00:58:14.624
collisions are absolutely
boring. They're boring

00:58:14.684 --> 00:58:18.664
because they are-- they
exemplify physics that

00:58:18.704 --> 00:58:22.444
we know a great deal about
already. We've tested it for

00:58:22.504 --> 00:58:26.344
decades. We know all about it. We
don't care. I mean, it's kind of

00:58:26.444 --> 00:58:30.404
blasé that we can say, "Oh, yeah, yeah,
we're making a billion subatomic particles

00:58:30.784 --> 00:58:34.394
every second," but who cares because,
you know? But that's just the way of,

00:58:34.784 --> 00:58:38.684
you know, frontier scientists.
So what you need is you

00:58:38.764 --> 00:58:42.544
need to pick out the cool ones, the
weird ones, the ones that nobody's seen

00:58:42.604 --> 00:58:49.934
before. And so what happens is,
these things, these beams collide,

00:58:50.424 --> 00:58:54.104
and we surround the collision
point with an enormous

00:58:54.114 --> 00:58:58.084
detector. There are two absolutely
ginormous detectors at the

00:58:58.144 --> 00:59:01.974
LHC, one of them called CMS,
which is the one I'm on,

00:59:02.504 --> 00:59:04.644
and the other one is called ATLAS--

00:59:04.744 --> 00:59:08.624
...which is the other one and we don't
speak of-- no, they're both really amazing.

00:59:08.944 --> 00:59:12.844
- Okay. It's good to know that there's
friendly competition even inside CERN.

00:59:13.004 --> 00:59:13.164
- Yes, yes.

00:59:13.364 --> 00:59:13.664
- That's awesome.

00:59:13.724 --> 00:59:17.764
- I mean, the fact is they are both
amazing, absolutely amazing detectors.

00:59:17.794 --> 00:59:19.584
- Right. But CMS is just a
little cooler than ATLAS.

00:59:19.624 --> 00:59:23.524
- Oh, yeah, yeah. I mean, you know,
in particle physics, we really

00:59:23.624 --> 00:59:27.504
absolutely want our competitors
to do extremely well,

00:59:27.604 --> 00:59:29.664
just not quite as well as we do.

00:59:29.944 --> 00:59:30.204
- Got it.

00:59:30.244 --> 00:59:30.554
- Yeah, yeah.

00:59:30.584 --> 00:59:30.804
- All right.

00:59:30.924 --> 00:59:30.984
- So-

00:59:31.034 --> 00:59:32.324
- So these two giant detectors.

00:59:32.464 --> 00:59:37.224
- Right. So, but one of them, our detector,
the CMS detector, it's the small one.

00:59:37.344 --> 00:59:41.044
It is 70 feet long, 50 feet
high, 50 feet wide. It's

00:59:41.064 --> 00:59:43.744
five stories tall. It weighs 14,000 tons.

00:59:43.853 --> 00:59:45.144
- Mm-hmm. Small one, yep.

00:59:45.244 --> 00:59:51.294
- Small. ATLAS experiment is 150 feet long,
80 feet across. It weighs only 7,000 tons.

00:59:51.294 --> 00:59:52.264
Just piece of cake.

00:59:52.304 --> 00:59:56.244
You could take the ATLAS detector, and
you could put four of them on a soccer or

00:59:56.254 --> 01:00:00.044
a football field, and it would fill the
field up with just enough room on the

01:00:00.104 --> 01:00:04.084
sidelines for the cheerleaders and the water boy
and the coaches and stuff. That's how big they

01:00:04.164 --> 01:00:04.444
are.

01:00:04.504 --> 01:00:04.834
- Nice.

01:00:04.864 --> 01:00:08.144
- So these are absolutely ginormous
detectors, and basically they're cameras,

01:00:08.844 --> 01:00:12.724
and what they can do is they can
take pictures 40 million times per

01:00:12.804 --> 01:00:16.744
second. Now, all the data comes
streaming off that detector, and

01:00:16.784 --> 01:00:20.604
we can't record it all. It would just fill up all of
our tapes, and it would be full of all these boring

01:00:20.664 --> 01:00:25.544
things we don't care about. So what we do
is as the beams pass through one another,

01:00:26.464 --> 01:00:30.254
we teach our detectors to say, "We only

01:00:30.364 --> 01:00:33.944
want one where there are certain
configurations that might be

01:00:33.984 --> 01:00:37.404
interesting," like there's gobs
of energy in the detector,

01:00:37.504 --> 01:00:41.104
or there's a gob of energy on one
side and nothing on the other

01:00:41.124 --> 01:00:45.604
side, or there's four gobs of energy or
whatever. These are called triggers.

01:00:45.724 --> 01:00:49.384
And so these-- what we have is
fast electronics that take the

01:00:49.604 --> 01:00:57.044
40 million possible pictures per second,
and it says, "You know, about 100,000 of

01:00:57.124 --> 01:01:00.924
those are really cool. We should
think about them." And then

01:01:01.004 --> 01:01:04.244
it passes not all of the
40 million, but those

01:01:04.264 --> 01:01:10.114
100,000 to the next level, which are
commercial processors that have,

01:01:10.924 --> 01:01:14.604
Basically our final analysis code, but

01:01:14.684 --> 01:01:18.484
optimized to run very, very quickly.
And what they do is they do a really

01:01:18.704 --> 01:01:22.304
quick and dirty analysis
to say, to further

01:01:22.364 --> 01:01:28.844
refine what's good and what's not. And
that, that computer farm then accepts about

01:01:29.024 --> 01:01:32.704
1,000 collisions per second, and we record

01:01:32.784 --> 01:01:36.504
those for further analysis. So that's
what's really happening. Of the 50

01:01:36.524 --> 01:01:40.444
million possible collisions per second,
the fast electronics and then the

01:01:40.464 --> 01:01:44.290
computers pick the thousand.
And then we pass those

01:01:44.400 --> 01:01:48.370
through analysis software and hand them to the graduate
students, and they pick through them, looking and

01:01:48.460 --> 01:01:52.360
finding the handful that are
the next Nobel Prize. So that's

01:01:52.380 --> 01:01:56.140
how that works, and that, that
is truly astonishing. I'm--

01:01:56.200 --> 01:01:59.560
hats off to the accelerator
builders, the detector builders,

01:01:59.580 --> 01:02:03.380
the people who make the software
work, the people who make the

01:02:03.860 --> 01:02:07.540
not gigabytes, not terabytes,
but petabytes of data flow

01:02:07.600 --> 01:02:11.400
around the world seamlessly. It's
really amazing. I'm very grateful.

01:02:12.440 --> 01:02:18.360
- So take me to July 4th, 2012,
the discovery of Higgs boson.

01:02:19.160 --> 01:02:23.090
- So this is really fun
because the people searching

01:02:23.100 --> 01:02:30.740
for the Higgs, it's a community, and
the entire community knew that the LHC

01:02:30.860 --> 01:02:34.680
was coming online. So even though
many of us had been working

01:02:34.800 --> 01:02:40.640
on the Fermilab accelerators, a lot
of us were transitioning to the CERN

01:02:40.820 --> 01:02:44.400
accelerator. So we were in
the very funny business of

01:02:44.480 --> 01:02:48.200
wearing our Fermilab
detector people hats, trying

01:02:48.240 --> 01:02:51.860
desperately to find the
Higgs boson at Fermilab-

01:02:51.920 --> 01:02:56.760
- Mm-hmm while simultaneously wearing
our CERN hats, knowing that CERN

01:02:56.840 --> 01:03:00.560
was going to be able to find it if existed.
And so, you know, we were a little

01:03:00.600 --> 01:03:04.240
neurotic, kind of wanted, you
know, our, our old stuff to work

01:03:05.120 --> 01:03:08.000
and, and there was an awful lot
of people on both experiments.

01:03:08.240 --> 01:03:11.920
Did you have a sense that one of the two

01:03:12.020 --> 01:03:15.720
places would be able to find the Higgs?
First, did you think the Higgs boson

01:03:15.760 --> 01:03:19.840
existed, and second, did you
think that these accelerators

01:03:20.740 --> 01:03:22.020
have the chance to find them?

01:03:22.200 --> 01:03:26.080
- So I was cognizant of the fact
that the Higgs boson might not

01:03:26.140 --> 01:03:30.980
exist, but there was a lot of evidence
pointing in the direction that it might be.

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:35.560
I knew that both experiments,
the Fermilab accelerator

01:03:36.120 --> 01:03:41.920
and the CERN accelerator, would either
find or rule out the Higgs if it existed.

01:03:42.500 --> 01:03:43.200
- Rule out?

01:03:43.340 --> 01:03:46.440
- Well, that's a possibility. I mean-
... maybe the Higgs theory was wrong.

01:03:46.560 --> 01:03:49.830
Right? Until you, till you know it's there,
it might be wrong. It's like dark matter.

01:03:49.900 --> 01:03:52.380
People talk about dark
matter, it might not be real.

01:03:52.420 --> 01:03:54.740
I mean, I-- it probably
is, but it might not be.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:58.640
- So you knew at these energy levels, you
would be-- you should be able to find-

01:03:58.780 --> 01:03:58.900
- Yes

01:03:58.920 --> 01:03:59.210
- ... the Higgs boson.

01:03:59.280 --> 01:04:03.130
- Yes. So that's the nice thing
about this kind of physics,

01:04:03.200 --> 01:04:07.140
because there was a theory,
that theory made predictions.

01:04:07.760 --> 01:04:11.729
Now, there were parameters in the theory
we didn't know. If the mass was this,

01:04:11.920 --> 01:04:15.720
we'd get this thing. If the mass was this,
we'd get this thing. But we could do the

01:04:16.240 --> 01:04:20.180
the calculation for every
conceivable Higgs mass, and

01:04:20.260 --> 01:04:23.950
so then we could search. Look,
well, let's say the Higgs mass is

01:04:23.980 --> 01:04:27.300
100 in some units. Did
we see it there? No.

01:04:27.860 --> 01:04:31.530
Then it's not 100. Well,
let's look at 103. Is it

01:04:31.620 --> 01:04:35.480
there? No. So we could do
that. Both accelerators

01:04:35.600 --> 01:04:39.100
could either find it or
definitively rule out the

01:04:39.140 --> 01:04:44.220
predictions of simple Higgs
theory, 100% guaranteed.

01:04:45.040 --> 01:04:52.980
However, the CERN accelerator had 10
times the collisions per second and three

01:04:53.020 --> 01:04:54.260
and a half times the energy.

01:04:55.080 --> 01:04:58.640
So remember when I said it-- with the
top quarks, it was, like, six months for

01:04:58.680 --> 01:05:02.080
19 versus one a second? There's no

01:05:02.220 --> 01:05:05.600
question. The writing is on
the wall. The Hi- the, the

01:05:05.680 --> 01:05:08.440
LHC was gonna have an easier time of it-

01:05:08.450 --> 01:05:12.440
... if it was real. However, so but,
you know, I'm a Fermilab scientist,

01:05:12.560 --> 01:05:15.569
and we wanted Fermilab, you know, come
on, we want Fermilab- ... to win.

01:05:15.590 --> 01:05:15.800
- Of course.

01:05:15.920 --> 01:05:20.680
- Not, you know. So we were busting our
butt, and we had done what I said. We

01:05:20.720 --> 01:05:24.400
had ruled out this region.
We had certain mass ranges.

01:05:24.700 --> 01:05:28.400
We knew it wasn't there. And
we finally said, if there

01:05:28.460 --> 01:05:32.280
was a Higgs boson, if it existed,
which we didn't know at the

01:05:32.340 --> 01:05:36.170
time, its mass was somewhere
between, if I recall, between,

01:05:36.240 --> 01:05:40.440
like, 120 and 145. All right? We'd
ruled out all the other stuff.

01:05:41.560 --> 01:05:45.380
And so wearing our CERN hat, we said,

01:05:45.430 --> 01:05:48.960
"Okay, we're gonna find that." But we were
really, really, really trying to do it.

01:05:49.120 --> 01:05:52.940
Now, if we had had another
two years or maybe three

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:55.380
years of running the Fermi accelerator,

01:05:57.460 --> 01:06:01.410
Fermilab would have discovered or ruled
out, or in this case, it turned out,

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:05.280
discovered the Higgs boson, 'cause it's a
real thing. We would have found it without a

01:06:05.340 --> 01:06:12.680
question. But we didn't have enough data
in July of 2012. We needed a couple

01:06:12.780 --> 01:06:18.100
more years. Unfortunately,
in 2008, or fortunately, the

01:06:18.140 --> 01:06:21.100
LHC had turned on. It broke. They
had to fix it. Turned on again in

01:06:21.260 --> 01:06:24.660
2010. It ran poorly in 2011. In

01:06:24.780 --> 01:06:28.620
2012, they pushed up their sleeves
and said, "Let's do this,"

01:06:29.440 --> 01:06:32.720
and it turned on. And so,
you know, there was this--

01:06:33.440 --> 01:06:37.020
the Fermilab knew if it didn't
have it now, it wasn't--

01:06:38.060 --> 01:06:45.400
it was too late. Anyways, come 2012
rolls around, and like two days before,

01:06:46.620 --> 01:06:49.770
The announcement at CERN was July
4th, so two days before that,

01:06:50.260 --> 01:06:54.220
Fermilab made a measurement
and said, "We can rule out

01:06:55.080 --> 01:06:59.060
certain regions, but certain
regions we can't rule out. But what

01:06:59.100 --> 01:07:02.820
we know, and this is
important, if the Higgs boson

01:07:02.880 --> 01:07:08.950
exists, it must be in this region for which
we are not capable yet of ruling out."

01:07:08.980 --> 01:07:14.230
So that's where we were two
days before the LHC said,

01:07:15.380 --> 01:07:18.980
"We got it." That was July 4th, 2012.

01:07:19.980 --> 01:07:23.260
- So detecting the Higgs boson confirmed the

01:07:23.300 --> 01:07:27.020
existence of the Higgs field,
the mechanism through which

01:07:27.040 --> 01:07:31.170
fundamental particles like electrons and
quarks acquire mass in the standard model.

01:07:31.340 --> 01:07:39.080
- Correct. Although, let's be very specific
of what we did then. We found a particle

01:07:39.260 --> 01:07:42.240
consistent with the existence
of the Higgs boson.

01:07:43.040 --> 01:07:46.460
There were alternative theories at
the time that predicted not one,

01:07:47.040 --> 01:07:50.629
but multiple Higgs bosons.
So there's a theory called

01:07:50.720 --> 01:07:54.620
supersymmetry, which said that
there was not one, but five Higgs

01:07:54.640 --> 01:07:58.600
bosons. The standard original
1964 Higgs theory says there

01:07:58.640 --> 01:08:02.360
was one. And so all we really
knew at the time was we

01:08:02.440 --> 01:08:05.890
found a theory. We did not
necessarily confirm that Higgs was

01:08:05.920 --> 01:08:09.820
right. We found data that said
that it looked like Higgs

01:08:09.880 --> 01:08:17.100
was right, but until we ran for longer, we
were unable to rule out other alternative

01:08:17.120 --> 01:08:22.220
theories. So that's the deal.
Now, in the fullness of time, it

01:08:22.300 --> 01:08:26.160
is after all what, 14 years now later, we

01:08:26.220 --> 01:08:29.880
have been able to basically rule out
some of those other things, and by

01:08:29.940 --> 01:08:33.460
now we have validated things.
We found the mass of the

01:08:33.500 --> 01:08:37.170
particle. We know the spin
of the Higgs boson. It has

01:08:37.320 --> 01:08:40.900
a spin of zero. We have
discovered the Higgs

01:08:40.960 --> 01:08:44.500
boson decays. It
preferentially decays into the

01:08:44.580 --> 01:08:48.420
heaviest particles it can
through energy conservation.

01:08:49.100 --> 01:08:53.080
Can't decay into top quarks, it's too
light to decay into top quarks, but it can

01:08:53.100 --> 01:08:56.520
decay into bottom quarks.
It can decay into W and Z

01:08:56.560 --> 01:09:00.420
particles, can decay into a
weird way into photons. And

01:09:00.780 --> 01:09:07.780
we have looked for all of the hypothesized
decays of the original Higgs theory-

01:09:07.860 --> 01:09:11.360
... and we have validated
that it decays in those ways

01:09:11.800 --> 01:09:15.720
at the rates that theory
predicted. And so now

01:09:15.900 --> 01:09:19.820
in the fullness of time, I'm pretty
comfortable saying Peter Higgs

01:09:20.140 --> 01:09:23.980
and Robert Brout and François Englert and
his colleagues, they were right back in the

01:09:23.990 --> 01:09:27.860
'60s. But we weren't sure on July 4th. All

01:09:27.940 --> 01:09:31.920
we knew was we found a particle
consistent. But the thing is, with

01:09:31.980 --> 01:09:35.800
these discoveries, they're often
just barely discoveries. It takes a

01:09:35.860 --> 01:09:39.780
while to go and do the more complex,
detailed measurements and that's what

01:09:39.840 --> 01:09:40.240
we've done.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:46.120
- So at the time, I remember it being
called referred to as the God particle.

01:09:46.800 --> 01:09:51.780
Uh, you also had a minor in theology, so

01:09:52.920 --> 01:09:56.740
throwing that all together, so
calling it the God particle is

01:09:56.860 --> 01:10:00.540
speaking to the importance, the potential
importance of discovering this particle.

01:10:01.040 --> 01:10:04.960
Do you think that is in some degree
justified? Like, if we look at the big impact

01:10:05.040 --> 01:10:09.140
of it on the history of physics,
how important was it to find

01:10:09.980 --> 01:10:13.210
and show that the Higgs field is real?

01:10:14.100 --> 01:10:17.800
- Well, I don't think it is as important
as, for instance, some of Einstein's

01:10:17.860 --> 01:10:21.560
stuff. I mean, it was-- it's an
important prediction. Like, the

01:10:21.600 --> 01:10:25.570
prediction of quarks was very important
and interesting in validating this.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:29.800
The Higgs was kinda like
validating that quarks

01:10:29.860 --> 01:10:33.520
existed. It's an important
stepping stone, and I,

01:10:34.120 --> 01:10:38.000
I do not wish to denigrate it
in any way, but there's ones

01:10:38.009 --> 01:10:41.920
that changed the way we thought about
the world, like Einstein did. It

01:10:41.980 --> 01:10:45.860
wasn't that sort of thing. And there is a funny
story. So the reason they call it the God

01:10:45.880 --> 01:10:52.789
particle is this book by Leon
Lederman, and if you read his book, he

01:10:53.260 --> 01:10:58.400
he says, "Well, you know, we call it the
God particle, but we should call it the

01:10:58.420 --> 01:11:03.380
goddamn particle because it's been causing
us so much trouble trying to find it."

01:11:03.390 --> 01:11:07.300
And Leon ran Fermilab, so— and he wrote
a foreword for one of my books and,

01:11:07.360 --> 01:11:10.220
you know, I talked to him. He's
a-- he was a really funny guy.

01:11:10.280 --> 01:11:13.840
And the real truth was the
book was called "The God

01:11:13.920 --> 01:11:17.160
Particle" because his publisher
thought it would sell more copies.

01:11:18.009 --> 01:11:21.900
But, you know, then that got into the mindset
of the reporters and so forth, and we

01:11:21.940 --> 01:11:24.990
called it the God particle. Leon
never really thought of it as

01:11:25.880 --> 01:11:29.480
anything to do with the religious or even— I
mean, the, he was an incredible jokester, the

01:11:29.540 --> 01:11:30.340
goddamn particle.

01:11:30.700 --> 01:11:33.660
- It is a really important part
of our model of the universe.

01:11:33.860 --> 01:11:34.200
- It is.

01:11:34.240 --> 01:11:38.090
- That there's this field that it gives mass
to some particles and not others, that's-

01:11:38.340 --> 01:11:42.020
- Right. It-- I-- it's a huge
thing, but it was part of the

01:11:42.080 --> 01:11:45.700
Standard Model. The Standard Model
had known forces, it had known

01:11:45.740 --> 01:11:49.610
particles, it had all that. The,
the Higgs boson, the one thing that

01:11:49.680 --> 01:11:56.260
is true is it was the last unvalidated
piece of the Standard Model. The

01:11:56.320 --> 01:12:00.140
Standard Model does not answer
all questions, which is why we

01:12:00.260 --> 01:12:04.040
have unanswered questions in
physics, but it was a punctuation

01:12:04.110 --> 01:12:07.960
point, end of about 50 years of
discovery and searching, where we

01:12:08.020 --> 01:12:11.970
finally were able to say the
Standard Model, while, while

01:12:12.100 --> 01:12:15.660
incomplete, it's mostly
right as far as it goes.

01:12:16.960 --> 01:12:20.940
- Quick 10-second thank you to our sponsors.
Check them out in the description. It

01:12:20.960 --> 01:12:23.500
really is the best way to
support this podcast. Go to

01:12:23.540 --> 01:12:27.530
lexfridman.com/sponsors.
And now, dear friends,

01:12:28.120 --> 01:12:33.880
back to my conversation with Don
Lincoln. We did a whirlwind tour

01:12:34.750 --> 01:12:38.200
of the history of physics
and took a little

01:12:38.340 --> 01:12:41.640
tangent on this incredible
discovery of the Higgs boson.

01:12:42.560 --> 01:12:46.290
But we didn't go all the way
yet. There's this dream of the

01:12:46.360 --> 01:12:50.220
grand unified theory, the GUT, that

01:12:50.540 --> 01:12:54.480
is a step towards the TOE, theory of
everything. So can we talk about the GUT

01:12:54.540 --> 01:12:57.440
first? So what, what's,
what's entailed in the GUT?

01:12:58.040 --> 01:13:01.380
- So the GUT is short for grand unified

01:13:01.400 --> 01:13:05.040
theory. We talked about that
there were four known subatomic

01:13:05.140 --> 01:13:09.070
forces, the electromagnetic force,
gravity, the strong force, and the

01:13:09.120 --> 01:13:12.520
weak force. And electroweak
symmetry unification

01:13:12.980 --> 01:13:16.720
merged the weak force and
electromagnetism into the

01:13:16.740 --> 01:13:20.590
electroweak force. So
what GUT hopes to do is

01:13:20.620 --> 01:13:24.360
to merge the electroweak
force and the strong force

01:13:24.420 --> 01:13:28.380
into one grand unified force.
Now, that leaves gravity outside

01:13:28.500 --> 01:13:32.490
because gravity is seemingly
fundamentally significantly different.

01:13:32.660 --> 01:13:36.600
Then subsequently, it is hoped
that a higher energy, we will be

01:13:36.660 --> 01:13:40.560
able to blend the theory of
everything together with all of the

01:13:40.600 --> 01:13:44.480
known subatomic forces, the strong,
weak, and electromagnetic forces, and

01:13:44.500 --> 01:13:48.320
then gravity. But so, as you
say, GUT is sort of a, a, a

01:13:48.360 --> 01:13:51.390
way station along the
way. That's the goal, and

01:13:52.860 --> 01:13:57.080
at this point, I would have
to say that I do not see a

01:13:58.320 --> 01:14:02.220
fast progress in the immediate future.
I think we're a ways away from

01:14:02.260 --> 01:14:02.900
that at this point.

01:14:02.940 --> 01:14:04.300
- You mean on the gravity front?

01:14:04.600 --> 01:14:08.400
- Maybe we'll come up with something really
cool. We certainly had some ideas back

01:14:08.500 --> 01:14:11.820
in the early '80s that we
tested, and they didn't pan out.

01:14:12.360 --> 01:14:16.580
- Uh, speaking of which, string theory
is the thing you're referring to.

01:14:16.760 --> 01:14:21.840
Uh, so string theory posits that
particles are tiny vibrating strings,

01:14:22.480 --> 01:14:26.440
and by tiny we mean extremely
tiny at the scale of a

01:14:26.460 --> 01:14:30.420
Planck length. Then there's
other leading candidates like

01:14:30.580 --> 01:14:34.320
loop quantum gravity. Maybe
there's some alternate

01:14:34.340 --> 01:14:39.120
theories in the works. So can you
link on that a little bit more?

01:14:40.260 --> 01:14:41.870
Do you think a theory
of everything exists?

01:14:42.660 --> 01:14:46.260
- So I hold personally that
there are rules that govern

01:14:46.580 --> 01:14:50.480
matter and energy, space, time, and
they probably are rules that I don't

01:14:50.540 --> 01:14:54.420
know. There are probably phenomena
I'm not aware of. But I do

01:14:54.440 --> 01:14:59.660
believe that something, there are,
is a rule that governs reality.

01:15:00.480 --> 01:15:04.200
And so in that sense,
once we understand the

01:15:04.220 --> 01:15:07.760
rules that govern reality, the fundamental
rules, that would be a theory of everything.

01:15:08.600 --> 01:15:12.460
You know, there are things that are unknowable,
like for instance, inside black holes, we

01:15:12.540 --> 01:15:16.080
don't know what's inside there, but that doesn't
mean that there's not something inside there.

01:15:16.600 --> 01:15:20.770
So there's a distinction between
what we can know and truth.

01:15:20.880 --> 01:15:24.700
So I do believe that there are the rules,

01:15:25.500 --> 01:15:29.240
and I do believe that with
sufficient time, technology, effort,

01:15:29.460 --> 01:15:32.940
we will be able to figure this all out.
Now, this isn't a thing in my lifetime.

01:15:34.100 --> 01:15:37.660
It's not a thing in my grandchildren's
lifetime or even their grandchildren's

01:15:37.720 --> 01:15:38.140
lifetime.

01:15:38.200 --> 01:15:40.850
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. That's a
pretty strong statement, right?

01:15:40.860 --> 01:15:42.520
That's a pretty strong
statement saying we're,

01:15:44.060 --> 01:15:48.400
we're fifty to a hundred years out
from finding a theory of everything.

01:15:48.800 --> 01:15:52.700
- It took two hundred years to
go from unifying gravity to

01:15:52.760 --> 01:15:56.260
unifying electromagnetism. It
took a hundred years to go from

01:15:56.520 --> 01:16:00.360
unifying electromagnetism to unifying
the electroweak force. Now, you could

01:16:00.420 --> 01:16:04.219
say, well, gee, that's went from two hundred
to a hundred, so it's getting faster.

01:16:04.590 --> 01:16:07.780
But it's also getting harder
because the unification

01:16:07.920 --> 01:16:11.840
scale is of order ten to the fifteen,

01:16:12.200 --> 01:16:15.980
which we can do the math. That's
a quadrillion times higher

01:16:16.340 --> 01:16:19.420
than the highest energy
accelerator we can build today.

01:16:19.820 --> 01:16:23.660
And it was one thing to, you
know, we are reaching diminishing

01:16:23.720 --> 01:16:26.800
returns. We get something
like a factor of seven

01:16:27.440 --> 01:16:31.310
increase in particle
accelerator energy every twenty

01:16:31.440 --> 01:16:36.660
years. And so we have to get
to a quadrillion times. Now,

01:16:37.580 --> 01:16:39.140
you know, if you really did believe,

01:16:40.080 --> 01:16:43.880
A factor of seven every twenty years,
then that's-- we're talking like five

01:16:43.940 --> 01:16:47.470
hundred years. But you know, this is
like Moore's Law, that it doesn't

01:16:47.480 --> 01:16:51.400
continue forever. We're not going to every
seven year-- I mean, every twenty years

01:16:51.440 --> 01:16:55.400
get another factor of seven. So yes, I
think it's a very long time. That's my

01:16:55.420 --> 01:16:59.160
prediction. You know, some people
are far more optimistic, and

01:16:59.640 --> 01:17:00.840
we can talk about that.

01:17:00.980 --> 01:17:06.090
- We should also, I should mention that I
guess your intuition behind that is not just

01:17:07.040 --> 01:17:10.710
the part where you come up with
a theory that's beautiful and

01:17:10.960 --> 01:17:14.890
seems to be internally
consistent, but you have to have

01:17:14.920 --> 01:17:19.360
a theory that's making
falsifiable, testable predictions.

01:17:19.520 --> 01:17:19.820
- Correct.

01:17:20.360 --> 01:17:26.660
- And you have to have a feasible
engineering construction, a

01:17:26.700 --> 01:17:29.840
methodology for creating an
experiment that tests that

01:17:29.860 --> 01:17:33.840
prediction. So I think a
lot of your, this is fifty,

01:17:33.880 --> 01:17:37.590
a hundred, two hundred years from
now, intuition is maybe about the

01:17:37.660 --> 01:17:41.320
second part of that, which is like,
you need to have an experiment.

01:17:41.820 --> 01:17:45.080
- Yes. Yes. But you know, let's say, I mean,

01:17:46.600 --> 01:17:49.980
you alluded to super strings. I haven't answered
that question. I'll table that for a moment.

01:17:50.380 --> 01:17:54.260
Super strings is a fascinating
idea. I don't believe it but

01:17:54.440 --> 01:17:58.410
I love it. I hope it's true. And
there's a real, you know, aphorism,

01:17:58.960 --> 01:18:02.940
and it says you should absolutely never
believe what you think. So even if you

01:18:02.960 --> 01:18:06.930
think super strings is true, you shouldn't
believe it because it hasn't been tested.

01:18:06.960 --> 01:18:09.640
Now, let's say super string is correct.

01:18:11.100 --> 01:18:14.900
I mean, hypothesis, it's correct, hundred
percent correct. I don't know it's

01:18:14.940 --> 01:18:18.840
correct, so I don't care. I
mean, you know, it could be

01:18:18.900 --> 01:18:22.620
correct, but I don't, you know,
until it's validated, it's just a

01:18:22.660 --> 01:18:26.480
wild-ass guess, you know? So
I, we have to have a way of

01:18:26.600 --> 01:18:30.420
validating it. So yes, the empirical side

01:18:30.560 --> 01:18:34.140
of it is important. I mean, you
could wake up tomorrow and have the

01:18:34.220 --> 01:18:38.260
theory that is the perfect theory, but
if I can't prove it, I don't care.

01:18:39.260 --> 01:18:43.160
- If we were to think, this is going back
to The Great Courses on the evidence for

01:18:43.240 --> 01:18:50.560
modern physics- ... we're talking
about energy levels and tiny particles

01:18:51.760 --> 01:18:55.280
to the degree where the kind of
prediction we would be making is not

01:18:55.320 --> 01:18:58.380
accelerator-type predictions. So

01:19:00.040 --> 01:19:03.880
it's probably going to be impossible to
build an accelerator that detects something

01:19:03.940 --> 01:19:12.720
like a string. So you have to make
predictions about macro scale behaviors.

01:19:13.440 --> 01:19:14.740
- That's another alternative.

01:19:15.220 --> 01:19:18.120
- It's a different kind of prediction.

01:19:18.480 --> 01:19:22.220
Do we even have intuitions about what kind
of predictions they would be? So one,

01:19:22.400 --> 01:19:26.290
one of course, one of the lines of
intuitions has to do with black holes or in

01:19:26.320 --> 01:19:32.000
the singularity. The physics of black
holes combine certain elements of general

01:19:32.080 --> 01:19:34.870
relativity and quantum
mechanics. So there-

01:19:34.940 --> 01:19:37.920
... you could see some kind of
predictions you could make,

01:19:38.940 --> 01:19:42.900
But you can't really mess with a black hole.
It's not like you can create a black hole in

01:19:42.940 --> 01:19:43.380
the lab.

01:19:43.560 --> 01:19:47.120
- And the energies that we're talking
about, the sizes we're talking about are

01:19:47.200 --> 01:19:51.480
inside a black hole, which you
can intrinsically never see.

01:19:51.540 --> 01:19:54.920
So, you know, you can only see the outside
of a black hole, not the inside of a black

01:19:54.940 --> 01:19:58.920
hole. So what you said, you did say
something that was incredibly important and

01:19:58.960 --> 01:20:02.660
incredibly correct and probably
won't happen, but that's still

01:20:02.720 --> 01:20:06.636
good, okay? So we have
two choices. When you

01:20:06.676 --> 01:20:10.576
talk about superstrings, either superstrings
are correct and they're making predictions

01:20:10.716 --> 01:20:14.316
up at the Planck energy scale, at
which point we have to somehow

01:20:14.456 --> 01:20:18.256
build facilities that can
generate Planck energies. That's

01:20:18.296 --> 01:20:25.646
possibility one. Possibility two is
this theory, which is currently only

01:20:25.676 --> 01:20:29.656
applicable at Planck energy
scales, someone figures out a

01:20:29.696 --> 01:20:33.056
way to take those equations

01:20:33.156 --> 01:20:36.876
and solve them in a way that, say,
predicts the mass of the electron.

01:20:37.616 --> 01:20:41.556
Mm-hmm. Right? And that
is a tricky business.

01:20:41.696 --> 01:20:45.166
I am not a string theorist, so
I can't tell you that that's

01:20:45.336 --> 01:20:49.116
likely, but I can tell you that they've
been working on it since the '80s and they

01:20:49.156 --> 01:20:52.656
haven't gotten very far. Furthermore, if I

01:20:53.596 --> 01:20:56.576
I think it's fair to characterize
that string theory is still

01:20:57.496 --> 01:21:01.436
a vague idea, and that's
unfair, but let me tell

01:21:01.476 --> 01:21:04.666
you why I say that because
what they have are

01:21:04.716 --> 01:21:08.436
approximate solutions to
approximate equations

01:21:10.236 --> 01:21:13.956
and that is already saying that we're a

01:21:13.996 --> 01:21:17.736
ways away from really
getting a handle on that. So

01:21:18.536 --> 01:21:22.486
yes, there could be some bright young
lad or lass out there, someone listening

01:21:22.516 --> 01:21:26.496
to this podcast right now who figures
out a way to take superstring theory

01:21:26.616 --> 01:21:30.276
and solve them in tractable ways
that makes predictions from the

01:21:30.376 --> 01:21:34.036
scale at which they currently
apply down to measurable scale

01:21:34.196 --> 01:21:38.156
today. And if that happens,
well, then I might retract my

01:21:38.216 --> 01:21:42.166
question or my concept.
There's a reason why I

01:21:42.236 --> 01:21:45.916
think that probably isn't
true. That's probably not

01:21:45.936 --> 01:21:49.856
valid. So let me-- I, I
love this, all right? So

01:21:49.896 --> 01:21:53.776
let's back up. I'm going to pitch. I
wrote this book for Oxford, Einstein's

01:21:53.836 --> 01:21:57.136
Unfinished Dream, and Einstein's unfinished dream
was to come up with a theory of everything.

01:21:57.176 --> 01:21:59.516
It was unfinished because,
well, it's unfinished.

01:22:00.416 --> 01:22:04.246
And so the, the second part, the
tagline of that book is Practical

01:22:04.396 --> 01:22:07.336
Progress Towards a Theory of Everything,
with the emphasis on practical

01:22:07.996 --> 01:22:11.606
because when you read books about

01:22:11.676 --> 01:22:15.576
theories of everything, when you see
podcasts, when you listen to YouTube videos

01:22:15.636 --> 01:22:19.036
or whatever, they are often
written by theorists.

01:22:19.776 --> 01:22:24.646
Mm. And theorists are-- they're big
idea people. They're very, very smart,

01:22:25.496 --> 01:22:30.666
but there's a pragmatism
that is often missing in the

01:22:30.696 --> 01:22:34.646
sense that they say, "Well, superstrings, look,
you know, have these little vibrating things,

01:22:34.676 --> 01:22:37.556
and wouldn't it be cool?" And, you
know, but you gotta get to the

01:22:38.416 --> 01:22:42.376
do you know it? So let's pretend
superstring theory or something like

01:22:42.416 --> 01:22:49.476
it is correct. The energy scale at
which that should occur is of order,

01:22:50.216 --> 01:22:54.176
um, 10 to the 15 times
higher, 10 to the 19 GeV.

01:22:54.256 --> 01:22:58.076
We can currently do things at
10 to the fourth GeV, give or

01:22:58.116 --> 01:23:01.996
take. So that is 10 to the 15. That's
a quadrillion times higher energy.

01:23:03.336 --> 01:23:06.936
So what we are doing now is we
are looking at the world with our

01:23:07.256 --> 01:23:11.036
very best measurements, and we
are trying to project out a

01:23:11.116 --> 01:23:16.426
quadrillion times higher and figure
out a theory that explains everything.

01:23:17.256 --> 01:23:21.216
Now, I have this-- I have a couple of
analogies, but I like this. Suppose that

01:23:21.276 --> 01:23:25.016
you were some, you know, Joe
Australopithecus 2 million years

01:23:25.076 --> 01:23:28.936
ago or something in Africa,
wandering around somewhere in

01:23:28.956 --> 01:23:32.896
Kenya. Mm-hmm. Right? You're
about a meter in size, so you

01:23:32.956 --> 01:23:36.836
can walk a meter. Meter scale is
like your scale. Mm-hmm. You can

01:23:36.856 --> 01:23:40.676
walk 10 meters in every direction. That's 30
feet, no problem. You can work 100 meters,

01:23:40.936 --> 01:23:44.646
300 feet. You can work 1,000
meters. That's half a mile. You can

01:23:44.656 --> 01:23:47.736
work 10,000 meters. That's 60 miles.

01:23:48.116 --> 01:23:52.056
100,000 meters is 10 to the
fifth and that's unlikely.

01:23:52.856 --> 01:23:56.836
But the distance that we need
to go from what we can see to

01:23:56.856 --> 01:23:59.636
the Planck scale, it's not 10 to
the fifth, it's 10 to the 15th.

01:24:00.596 --> 01:24:04.446
So that means, in my analogy,
think about this guy who's

01:24:04.536 --> 01:24:08.456
walking around Africa. Now, if he
walks, you know, 100 feet or something,

01:24:08.496 --> 01:24:12.296
it looks a lot like what it is now. He
can make a prediction about what he sees,

01:24:12.376 --> 01:24:16.096
and when he goes to that new place, it's
probably going to be okay. But if he

01:24:16.136 --> 01:24:19.276
starts walking 500 miles east, well, he,

01:24:20.156 --> 01:24:23.856
walking around the center of Africa,
has no concept of, for instance,

01:24:24.116 --> 01:24:27.686
the Indian Ocean. He would
never predict sperm whales or

01:24:27.755 --> 01:24:31.536
kraken. He would never predict
what it's like the bottom of the

01:24:31.576 --> 01:24:35.296
ocean is going north.
He's in Africa. He would

01:24:35.476 --> 01:24:38.936
never, ever have a clue about the Alps or

01:24:38.996 --> 01:24:42.976
Antarctica. Going even smaller
distances, going a mile up,

01:24:43.116 --> 01:24:46.916
things wouldn't be very different. But if he
goes 10 miles up, he wouldn't breathe and

01:24:46.936 --> 01:24:50.856
he'd freeze. If he goes 100 miles
up, he would die. If he goes two

01:24:50.896 --> 01:24:54.886
miles down, he would
roast. The point being is

01:24:56.656 --> 01:25:00.556
we are like that
Australopithecus. We have a

01:25:00.576 --> 01:25:04.156
realm that we can study, and we can even

01:25:04.176 --> 01:25:08.056
predict to some validity what
would happen if we go some

01:25:08.076 --> 01:25:11.756
distance away. But the
farther away we go, the

01:25:11.816 --> 01:25:15.376
less and less our local prediction really

01:25:15.416 --> 01:25:19.336
represents the reality of those
more distant times. And so

01:25:20.036 --> 01:25:23.776
basically, his theory about
the world would be totally

01:25:23.836 --> 01:25:27.556
bogus. So even if he had the best
theory, his theory would not have

01:25:27.596 --> 01:25:32.316
anticipated the Alps. It would
not have anticipated penguins.

01:25:33.456 --> 01:25:37.336
Right? Flamingos, not
there. You know? And that

01:25:37.416 --> 01:25:40.996
is just the case. So now that's
what we're doing. We are

01:25:41.056 --> 01:25:44.596
taking something and we have
reason to understand what we

01:25:44.636 --> 01:25:49.736
know and we can predict a factor of 10
or 100. But I think it is the absolute,

01:25:51.226 --> 01:25:55.076
the pinnacle of arrogance to think
that what we can do given the

01:25:55.136 --> 01:25:58.716
understanding that we have from what
we've measured now and predict it out

01:25:59.096 --> 01:26:02.796
a quadrillion times higher
than we can see now.

01:26:02.896 --> 01:26:06.596
So my opinion, and this is partly
because I'm an experimentalist,

01:26:07.216 --> 01:26:11.156
the correct way to make progress,
practical progress towards a theory of

01:26:11.216 --> 01:26:15.086
everything is to look around
at the things that we don't

01:26:15.136 --> 01:26:19.116
have answers to right now.
For instance, are there some

01:26:19.126 --> 01:26:22.788
things smaller than quarks?
I don't know. Is dark matter

01:26:22.928 --> 01:26:26.908
real? I don't know. If
it's real, what is it?

01:26:27.388 --> 01:26:30.608
I don't know. Is dark energy real?
Yes, probably, but I don't know.

01:26:31.248 --> 01:26:35.108
What is the nature of space
and time? I don't know.

01:26:35.128 --> 01:26:39.098
But these are questions we can
explore, and I would expect, and this

01:26:39.128 --> 01:26:42.888
is my prediction, that, all right, we're
gonna figure things out at a factor of

01:26:42.928 --> 01:26:46.688
10 or 100 times better than we can do now,
and we might be able to do that in my

01:26:46.768 --> 01:26:50.468
kid's lifetime or something
like that. But in order for us

01:26:50.588 --> 01:26:54.348
to predict a quadrillion
times higher, I'm pretty sure

01:26:54.388 --> 01:26:58.197
superstring theory is wrong. Not
because people aren't smart, but

01:26:58.248 --> 01:27:02.108
because something new is going to happen.
I mean, if you were talking about

01:27:02.148 --> 01:27:06.068
chemistry, you would have never
predicted nuclear physics, and that's

01:27:06.148 --> 01:27:10.108
a small increase in energy, right?
The idea that there's something

01:27:10.148 --> 01:27:13.848
in the nucleus of atoms that causes
the sun to burn, there's a reason why

01:27:13.908 --> 01:27:17.688
people didn't believe, you know,
they calculated how old the

01:27:17.708 --> 01:27:21.648
sun should be, and it should only be 10 million
years old because otherwise it would burn

01:27:21.768 --> 01:27:25.348
out. Well, that's clearly wrong,
and it's wrong because of nuclear

01:27:25.408 --> 01:27:28.908
physics. That is why I feel fairly

01:27:28.968 --> 01:27:32.788
confident to say, while someone
could think, well, superstring

01:27:32.828 --> 01:27:36.508
might be right or something, and maybe it's right, and
I hope it's right. It would be awesome if it's right.

01:27:37.028 --> 01:27:40.768
But what are the odds when you're
making something with that

01:27:40.848 --> 01:27:44.368
tiny lever arm, predicting
it out a quadrillion

01:27:44.408 --> 01:27:48.238
away and say, "Oh, yeah, we got it
right." What are the odds? And my

01:27:48.348 --> 01:27:50.488
answer is, you gotta be kidding me.

01:27:50.588 --> 01:27:54.528
Now, I could be wrong, and I admit
that I could be wrong, but that's

01:27:54.588 --> 01:27:58.428
why I think the real issue
is not the brilliance of

01:27:58.468 --> 01:28:02.428
humanity. It's the stuff
we haven't found. We

01:28:02.468 --> 01:28:05.838
don't know— I mean, the simple
one, I, and I'm saying it simple,

01:28:06.508 --> 01:28:09.408
and it's not, but what is dark matter?

01:28:09.488 --> 01:28:13.608
We don't have a bleeping clue. Not a
clue. We know a lot of what it isn't,

01:28:14.408 --> 01:28:18.328
but we don't know what it is. And so, you know,
talk about superstrings. All right, well,

01:28:18.368 --> 01:28:22.288
maybe dark matter fits in superstrings,
or maybe dark matter is governed

01:28:22.328 --> 01:28:26.428
by a physics that is completely diametrically
opposed to the superstring concept.

01:28:26.968 --> 01:28:30.737
- And allow me a bit of a thought
experiment here, a brief thought.

01:28:31.547 --> 01:28:34.958
My intuition says that when you
propose a theory of everything,

01:28:35.608 --> 01:28:41.648
the kind of prediction you want to make
involves a kind of leap of conceptual

01:28:41.688 --> 01:28:45.868
understanding that Einstein did. So,
for example, you want to come up

01:28:46.748 --> 01:28:49.897
with something like
spacetime and then gravity—

01:28:50.408 --> 01:28:50.498
- Sure

01:28:50.508 --> 01:28:52.128
- ...bends space, spacetime.

01:28:53.108 --> 01:28:58.268
So it's not merely that you have this
beautiful mathematical framework, but

01:28:59.228 --> 01:29:07.148
that framework allows you to rethink
how you see reality enough to make a

01:29:07.188 --> 01:29:10.888
prediction that's about the macro world.

01:29:10.928 --> 01:29:12.708
- I mean, to come up with something like

01:29:13.608 --> 01:29:17.358
spacetime, you know, there's one idea,
for instance, to say that space and

01:29:17.428 --> 01:29:20.748
time aren't real. They,
they emerge from entropy.

01:29:21.328 --> 01:29:25.048
Yeah, that's a way of, a new way of thinking,
and maybe there's some validity, and I want

01:29:25.108 --> 01:29:29.728
people to think about it. But
in the end, it's just an idea,

01:29:30.528 --> 01:29:34.468
and that's the real key thing. And,
and as you say, it has to tie to a

01:29:34.528 --> 01:29:38.428
macro world. You have to validate. If
you don't validate, it's a crazy idea.

01:29:39.068 --> 01:29:42.968
Theorists are incredibly creative, smart,

01:29:43.728 --> 01:29:47.358
wonderfully interesting
people, but I don't

01:29:47.408 --> 01:29:51.378
care. I want a measurement that
validates the idea because

01:29:51.408 --> 01:29:54.888
there are so many-- I mean, if
you read the, the journals, there

01:29:54.968 --> 01:29:59.008
are so many theoretical papers with
all these nifty ideas that die.

01:29:59.848 --> 01:30:03.698
You know one that was recently I
liked and, and might still be true

01:30:04.348 --> 01:30:08.318
was that dark matter that, you know, our

01:30:08.348 --> 01:30:12.258
simple model of dark matter is that there's a
subatomic particle out there that's heavy, and

01:30:12.288 --> 01:30:16.148
it's floating around, and it's causing gravity.
But someone said, "Well, you know, maybe there's

01:30:16.208 --> 01:30:19.788
complex dark matter," which means there's
a whole dark sector, so there are dark

01:30:19.868 --> 01:30:24.348
atoms, and they interact with one another.
And that is a nifty idea, and I love it.

01:30:25.528 --> 01:30:29.488
And that was all the rage for a while,
and we looked at it, and it may still

01:30:29.508 --> 01:30:33.308
be true, but the simple ideas
have been mostly invalidated

01:30:33.788 --> 01:30:37.508
because we've tested it and it doesn't
work. Same thing, there was a talk

01:30:37.587 --> 01:30:41.268
about large extra dimensions. The
reason that gravity is so much

01:30:41.328 --> 01:30:44.928
weaker than the other forces was, well,
maybe gravity can sneak into more

01:30:44.948 --> 01:30:46.948
dimensions than the other forces.

01:30:47.248 --> 01:30:48.977
- It leaks into those dimensions.

01:30:49.048 --> 01:30:52.948
- That was a cool idea. I mean but that's
the point is you have these lovely, cool,

01:30:53.168 --> 01:30:57.128
interesting ideas that constantly die.

01:30:57.168 --> 01:31:03.308
And so, you know, I would love for
a new nifty idea to be the idea,

01:31:03.428 --> 01:31:08.348
but I don't know how to pick it out
of the hurricane of wrong ideas.

01:31:08.828 --> 01:31:11.988
- I mean, that's the real beauty
of science. It really is--

01:31:12.838 --> 01:31:16.208
I mean, the theories kind of get
some of the glory sometimes,

01:31:16.888 --> 01:31:20.798
but the real beauty emerges from the
experiment and the demonstration that

01:31:20.828 --> 01:31:22.328
the theory is correct.

01:31:22.588 --> 01:31:26.308
- And there are two directions. You're talking a top-
down. Someone comes up with this big idea that's

01:31:26.368 --> 01:31:30.168
testable. But you also have
the other way that science

01:31:30.308 --> 01:31:36.308
advances, and it's not with a theory that
is then tested. It's with the, "Huh,

01:31:37.128 --> 01:31:40.948
that's weird." For
instance, either in, in the

01:31:40.988 --> 01:31:44.808
1930s with Fritz Zwicky
or in the 1970s with Vera

01:31:44.848 --> 01:31:48.508
Rubin, she did a simple thing.
She said, "How fast are galaxies

01:31:48.588 --> 01:31:52.518
rotating?" 'Cause it's an easy thing to calculate.
You could literally calculate that with

01:31:52.548 --> 01:31:56.488
high school physics. And you get an answer,
and then you measure it, and it's wrong.

01:31:57.148 --> 01:32:02.828
And so I'll-- That's the, wow, huh, I don't
know what that is. And that led to the

01:32:02.848 --> 01:32:06.168
hypothesis of dark matter. Now, dark
matter is not a theory of everything,

01:32:06.748 --> 01:32:10.468
but it's a clue. It's a powerful clue.
We should pull, tug at that thread.

01:32:10.988 --> 01:32:14.708
Maybe our entire theoretical
edifice unravels, or maybe it

01:32:14.728 --> 01:32:18.228
doesn't. Maybe it's just a snag, and we
can fix what we have now. I'm not sure.

01:32:18.848 --> 01:32:22.408
So that's another option
is to simply look at many

01:32:22.448 --> 01:32:26.248
measurements that are very
precise and find ones where

01:32:26.328 --> 01:32:32.128
the outcome and the prediction with established
theory disagree, and that is a clue

01:32:33.268 --> 01:32:36.978
- Before we leave the topic, we
gotta talk about string theory.

01:32:37.508 --> 01:32:39.828
In your view, is it basically dead?

01:32:40.808 --> 01:32:44.448
As I understand one of the
primary flaws of string

01:32:44.508 --> 01:32:48.868
theory, outside of the testable
experiments that we're talking about,

01:32:49.748 --> 01:32:57.208
is because it relies on these unobserved
extra dimensions, there was a hope that it

01:32:57.288 --> 01:33:01.198
uniquely could explain our universe, but
it turns out this, quote, "landscape,"

01:33:01.968 --> 01:33:05.728
there's an enormous so-called
landscape of possibilities it leads

01:33:05.768 --> 01:33:09.128
to. And so it renders the theory basically

01:33:09.188 --> 01:33:13.408
unpredictive, 'cause it can
describe all kinds of universes-

01:33:13.448 --> 01:33:13.458
- Sure

01:33:13.458 --> 01:33:18.528
- ... and therefore you can just
select, tune it to describe ours.

01:33:19.488 --> 01:33:21.288
- I agree to a degree.

01:33:21.308 --> 01:33:28.968
But I bring it back to my prior
objection. It is absolutely true that

01:33:29.208 --> 01:33:33.748
super string theory at, in
its current manifestation,

01:33:34.548 --> 01:33:38.228
aside from the extra dimensions,
which are some level small

01:33:38.248 --> 01:33:45.668
potatoes, it allows for an
extremely large number of possible

01:33:45.988 --> 01:33:55.948
universes. But if we were able to take
those predictions and somehow connect it

01:33:56.048 --> 01:33:59.848
to a physical measurement, then
what we would do is we'd lop off

01:34:00.268 --> 01:34:03.608
those alternatives. We'd throw them
away as saying, "Well, you know,

01:34:04.128 --> 01:34:08.078
those are like an
equation, you know, X plus

01:34:08.148 --> 01:34:12.008
five." I can put in any number I want in
there, it doesn't matter. But if X plus five

01:34:12.048 --> 01:34:15.688
equals nine, then I've ruled
out a whole bunch of--

01:34:15.848 --> 01:34:19.408
numbers except four. And
so this is a case of

01:34:19.668 --> 01:34:23.378
string theory does allow
for many predictions, but

01:34:23.468 --> 01:34:27.348
if we could rule them out by connection
to a measurement, then it would no

01:34:27.448 --> 01:34:31.228
longer do it. We would modify string
theory, and we would retain the

01:34:31.308 --> 01:34:36.468
vibrating string concept, which I really,
really like. I mean, I really like it. But

01:34:37.708 --> 01:34:42.768
until we can validate this,
it's, it's, I, I, we can't. So

01:34:43.868 --> 01:34:45.188
now you ask, is it dead or not?

01:34:46.088 --> 01:34:49.777
In my opinion, it is very difficult to
kill such a theory. I mean, really,

01:34:49.928 --> 01:34:53.388
truly kill it, 'cause kill it means
make a prediction and it fails.

01:34:54.108 --> 01:34:57.988
But what can happen and what is
happening is people have been working

01:34:58.048 --> 01:34:59.468
on it since the '70s.

01:35:00.308 --> 01:35:04.108
So we're talking of order 50 years,
people have been working on it,

01:35:05.068 --> 01:35:09.018
and it has not solved
the problem. And so I

01:35:09.028 --> 01:35:12.777
think what's happening is people
are looking at that and saying,

01:35:14.148 --> 01:35:18.008
"Do I wanna spend my life working
in this direction with the

01:35:18.068 --> 01:35:21.958
very likely possibility that
30 years from now we'll

01:35:21.968 --> 01:35:25.608
be not much farther along than we are
now?" It's a lot like back in the

01:35:25.628 --> 01:35:30.648
1940s when people started thinking
about the meaning of quantum mechanics.

01:35:31.488 --> 01:35:35.057
And I wanted to do that when
I was a kid in the '70s.

01:35:35.508 --> 01:35:39.368
But then when I went to grad school, I
realized that people, very smart people,

01:35:39.488 --> 01:35:43.368
people smarter than me, had been working
on that for most of their lives and

01:35:43.408 --> 01:35:46.828
made no definitive progress.
And so you have to decide,

01:35:47.428 --> 01:35:51.368
as a scientist who wants to answer
questions, do I really wanna take on a

01:35:51.428 --> 01:35:55.248
question that is so hard that it will
not be answered in my lifetime? And I

01:35:55.268 --> 01:35:59.188
think that's what's happening with a lot of
superstring theories. People are saying, "It's

01:35:59.228 --> 01:36:00.538
really neat. It might be right,

01:36:01.468 --> 01:36:06.008
but I don't wanna devote my life to
something that I might not see progress

01:36:07.068 --> 01:36:08.508
forward in my lifetime."

01:36:08.928 --> 01:36:12.808
- What do you think about the alternate
theories? Do you think there's anything

01:36:12.868 --> 01:36:13.868
interesting in those?

01:36:14.568 --> 01:36:19.288
- You know, many of those theories are espoused
by passionate people. They have fans.

01:36:20.268 --> 01:36:24.248
People love them, but they don't
do what science needs to do,

01:36:24.288 --> 01:36:28.268
which is make predictions. Now,
loop quantum gravity is a little

01:36:28.328 --> 01:36:32.308
different. That one is better
developed, and that one is not a theory

01:36:32.348 --> 01:36:36.338
of everything, so we should make that
clear. Loop quantum gravity is not a theory

01:36:36.368 --> 01:36:39.938
of everything. It is simply
a theory of quantum gravity,

01:36:40.428 --> 01:36:44.228
period. It does not aspire
to include all of the known

01:36:44.308 --> 01:36:51.988
forces. It simply tries to take gravity,
which is currently intrinsically, it treats

01:36:52.088 --> 01:36:55.668
space as smooth and continuous.
For those of your viewers who are

01:36:55.728 --> 01:37:01.078
mathematically inclined, in Einstein's
theory of general relativity,

01:37:01.708 --> 01:37:05.588
gravity is infinitely
divisible. There is no

01:37:05.648 --> 01:37:10.578
smallest bit, and so essentially
the laws of calculus apply.

01:37:11.088 --> 01:37:14.828
However, it is possible that
at a small enough scale,

01:37:15.828 --> 01:37:19.748
space is no longer divisible in the same

01:37:19.788 --> 01:37:23.588
way that you can, you know, take a cup of
water out of a swimming pool and then a

01:37:23.648 --> 01:37:27.568
quarter a cup and so forth. But eventually,
once you've taken out a single molecule

01:37:27.628 --> 01:37:31.608
of water, you can no longer take
out a smaller thing. So loop

01:37:31.668 --> 01:37:35.588
quantum gravity attempts to
quantize gravity, so that's

01:37:35.628 --> 01:37:43.408
what it does. And so this is unlike string
theory, which attempts to bring gravity

01:37:43.508 --> 01:37:47.268
in with the other forces. And in fact,
the reason, the fundamental, the

01:37:47.348 --> 01:37:55.548
one reason why string theory became so
interesting to the theoretical community is

01:37:56.248 --> 01:37:58.038
string theory was not

01:37:59.128 --> 01:38:02.748
being developed as a theory of
everything. It was being developed as a

01:38:02.808 --> 01:38:06.758
theory of the strong force, and it was

01:38:06.788 --> 01:38:10.848
in competition with QCD, which is the
currently accepted theory of the strong force.

01:38:11.708 --> 01:38:15.608
And it turned out the two groups,
the string theory groups and

01:38:15.708 --> 01:38:19.288
the QCD groups competed
for a while, and string

01:38:19.448 --> 01:38:23.098
theory basically failed the race, and

01:38:23.388 --> 01:38:26.688
people paid attention to
quantum chromodynamics, QCD.

01:38:27.308 --> 01:38:30.768
But then somebody noticed in string
theory that one of the things it

01:38:30.808 --> 01:38:38.608
predicted was a zero mass spin-2 particle.
And you can prove that any zero mass

01:38:38.788 --> 01:38:42.768
spin-2 particle is the
graviton. And so if you see

01:38:42.808 --> 01:38:46.798
a theory that has a zero mass
spin-2 particle, you now

01:38:46.828 --> 01:38:50.808
have a candidate for dragging gravity
in, and then, oh my gosh, people got

01:38:50.828 --> 01:38:54.808
terribly excited because now
this theory, which was working

01:38:54.908 --> 01:38:58.648
in the direction of the other quantum
forces, brought in gravity, and now it was a

01:38:58.708 --> 01:39:02.300
candidate theory for everything. But

01:39:02.660 --> 01:39:06.140
but that's not what loop quantum gravity is.
Loop quantum gravity is simply trying to

01:39:06.180 --> 01:39:10.370
understand the nature of space itself,
which is already a fantastic thing.

01:39:11.210 --> 01:39:14.960
And, you know, I talk to Rovelli
every so often. I write about his

01:39:15.020 --> 01:39:18.980
theory and I point out some
of the issues with the

01:39:19.040 --> 01:39:22.840
theory, but I'm usually about,
like, two months behind as he and

01:39:22.900 --> 01:39:26.450
his colleagues are developing and so
forth. 'Cause one of the things is

01:39:26.500 --> 01:39:29.890
originally loop quantum gravity predicted

01:39:30.200 --> 01:39:34.100
that the speed of light would not be
universal. The speed of light would

01:39:34.140 --> 01:39:38.060
depend on the frequency of
the light. So high frequency

01:39:38.120 --> 01:39:42.090
would travel at one speed, and low frequency
would travel at a different speed, and it had

01:39:42.120 --> 01:39:45.900
to do with the wavelength of
light basically interacting with

01:39:45.940 --> 01:39:49.120
the structure of space
if, you know. And so that

01:39:49.260 --> 01:39:53.040
was an issue with loop quantum gravity.
And so if you look at gamma ray

01:39:53.160 --> 01:39:56.880
bursters, which are, you
know, super explosions of

01:39:56.940 --> 01:39:59.580
astronomical events that are a
billion light years away or more,

01:40:00.380 --> 01:40:04.220
and they spit out light in all
wavelengths, and if that loop

01:40:04.260 --> 01:40:07.900
quantum gravity prediction
were correct, when you saw a,

01:40:08.500 --> 01:40:12.180
One of these gamma ray bursters,
you would see the wavelength

01:40:12.400 --> 01:40:16.380
of one light appearing on Earth at a
different time than another wavelength

01:40:16.440 --> 01:40:20.180
because of the different speeds, and that
wasn't the case. They appear at the same

01:40:20.240 --> 01:40:24.130
time. And so I went on to say, "Well, this

01:40:24.380 --> 01:40:28.300
pretty much killed loop quantum
gravity," only to get a prickly note

01:40:28.360 --> 01:40:31.990
from Mr. or Dr. Rovelli
saying, "You know, we've

01:40:32.020 --> 01:40:35.670
disproved that. We've changed the
theory. That's no longer true, and now

01:40:35.760 --> 01:40:39.580
that, that prediction, that old prediction
of loop quantum gravity is no longer

01:40:39.660 --> 01:40:45.790
valid." And so that observation
of the uniformity of the

01:40:45.860 --> 01:40:49.680
speed of light no longer
kills the new loop quantum

01:40:49.700 --> 01:40:51.660
gravity. It would've killed the old
one, but it didn't kill the new one.

01:40:51.980 --> 01:40:55.670
- By the way, that example
of different speeds of

01:40:55.740 --> 01:40:59.720
light based on wavelength,
that's a beautiful thing

01:40:59.780 --> 01:41:02.160
that a theory-- That's a testable thing.

01:41:02.440 --> 01:41:02.740
- It is.

01:41:03.160 --> 01:41:06.980
- Right? So, like, those kinds of things,
and if it in fact did explain a

01:41:07.020 --> 01:41:10.160
phenomena of that sort, that's a
good sign for the theory, right?

01:41:10.620 --> 01:41:11.839
If it correctly predicted.

01:41:11.900 --> 01:41:15.500
- There was another brilliant
observation recently. Love it.

01:41:16.140 --> 01:41:19.940
The observation of gravity waves.

01:41:20.180 --> 01:41:27.860
And it was from two neutron stars
orbiting and coalescing. And so they made

01:41:27.880 --> 01:41:31.730
gravitational waves, fantastic, but
they also, because they were not

01:41:31.740 --> 01:41:35.620
black holes, they were neutron
stars, they hit and exploded, gave

01:41:35.680 --> 01:41:41.900
off a tremendous bright flash of light.
And so astronomers saw the flash.

01:41:42.360 --> 01:41:48.880
Gravitational wave astronomers saw
the ripples of space-time. It was 140

01:41:49.060 --> 01:41:52.840
million light years away, which
means light would've traveled 140

01:41:52.980 --> 01:41:56.730
million years to get here, and
the two incidents, light and

01:41:56.780 --> 01:42:00.530
gravity, both arrived within
1.7 seconds of one another.

01:42:01.260 --> 01:42:04.600
And that tells you that gravity
travels at the speed of light.

01:42:05.140 --> 01:42:08.740
That was a brilliant, fantastic
measurement. Now, we thought

01:42:08.840 --> 01:42:12.760
gravity traveled at the speed of light, but
now we have a measurement, we proved it, and

01:42:13.040 --> 01:42:14.420
damn it, I am impressed.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:19.940
- Our universe is so fascinating. Speaking
of which, since we brought up antimatter,

01:42:20.960 --> 01:42:24.460
we'll have to talk about it. You've
talked about it in several of your

01:42:24.500 --> 01:42:28.349
lectures from different
angles, including the dark

01:42:28.420 --> 01:42:32.300
energy crisis and including empty
space and vacuum and so on.

01:42:32.740 --> 01:42:35.790
So let's look at the empty space angle. So

01:42:36.680 --> 01:42:39.240
you know, it turns out that
empty space is not empty.

01:42:40.140 --> 01:42:42.200
- It's true. Which is kind of bizarre.

01:42:42.620 --> 01:42:47.160
- Can you speak about what do we know
about what makes up empty space?

01:42:47.600 --> 01:42:52.520
- That's a hard question because we don't
know what space is. But let's start out—

01:42:52.540 --> 01:42:56.080
... let's just start out with
something simple. We'll assume that

01:42:56.140 --> 01:42:59.720
space is not quantized, okay?

01:43:00.100 --> 01:43:04.020
Now, it probably is, I don't know, but, you
know, we gotta start with somewhere. So

01:43:04.060 --> 01:43:07.840
let's start out with sort of the space
of calculus, the space that you can

01:43:07.860 --> 01:43:13.660
divide forever. The modern version of
quantum mechanics is called quantum

01:43:13.680 --> 01:43:19.160
field theory, and it postulates
that, A, space exists. Then

01:43:19.259 --> 01:43:26.600
it postulates that within space there
exist fields for every known subatomic

01:43:26.610 --> 01:43:30.540
particle. So there is a photon field,
there's an electron field, there's an

01:43:30.580 --> 01:43:33.890
up quark field, there's a down quark
field. There's all the fields.

01:43:35.650 --> 01:43:37.260
And those fields can vibrate,

01:43:38.280 --> 01:43:42.140
and when they vibrate, those
are the subatomic particles.

01:43:42.180 --> 01:43:47.760
So an electron field vibrating in a
characteristic way is an electron.

01:43:48.580 --> 01:43:52.480
Now, it's also possible
for the electron field to

01:43:52.520 --> 01:43:56.400
vibrate not in the characteristic
way, but in a way that's

01:43:56.460 --> 01:44:00.430
still vibrating, but it's not
an exact electron. So this

01:44:00.500 --> 01:44:04.670
is what we call virtual particles.
Now, virtual particles,

01:44:05.680 --> 01:44:09.200
there are lots of ways to talk about
them, and the way I'm talking about now

01:44:09.360 --> 01:44:16.500
is the most correct and the most
sophisticated way that we can talk

01:44:16.600 --> 01:44:20.470
about them. I will talk about
them briefly in a simpler way

01:44:20.500 --> 01:44:24.350
to help. But right now, that's
the important thing, is that

01:44:24.380 --> 01:44:27.820
there are these fields. Specific
vibrations are the known

01:44:27.880 --> 01:44:31.300
particles. Vibrations that
are a little different are,

01:44:32.280 --> 01:44:35.920
these virtual particles. They're
particles that don't truly

01:44:35.980 --> 01:44:44.620
exist. And so that is what we think
space is. There is all of these these,

01:44:44.840 --> 01:44:48.300
these fields. They're all
vibrating a little. If you

01:44:48.380 --> 01:44:51.820
insert the right amount of energy,
you can get it to vibrate in the

01:44:51.860 --> 01:44:55.660
characteristic way and make that
subatomic particle. But even when

01:44:55.720 --> 01:44:59.596
you don't—there is the particles, I

01:44:59.636 --> 01:45:03.616
mean the fields are there and they are vibrating.
So those vibrating vibrations are what we

01:45:03.656 --> 01:45:07.536
called virtual particles. Now, your
viewers may have heard of virtual

01:45:07.636 --> 01:45:11.576
particles in other ways, in which
case it says that space is just

01:45:11.616 --> 01:45:15.376
empty, and what happens is matter
and antimatter particles briefly

01:45:15.416 --> 01:45:18.856
appear for a very short
period of time before they

01:45:18.876 --> 01:45:26.136
coalesce back again and disappear and,
re-emerge back into the field. And so that--

01:45:26.516 --> 01:45:30.456
these are both correct. So what happens
is, is that's what quantum field theory

01:45:30.536 --> 01:45:34.476
says, is it says that these ripples are
appearing or these particles are appearing and

01:45:34.536 --> 01:45:38.376
disappearing. And so
that just sounds nuts.

01:45:39.076 --> 01:45:42.666
You look at empty space, you're not
seeing anything happening. But they're

01:45:42.696 --> 01:45:46.576
happening fast enough that they
can't be seen, but they do have

01:45:46.696 --> 01:45:50.616
consequences. And there are two
experimental measurements that

01:45:50.756 --> 01:45:54.436
I can think of that validate that this

01:45:54.476 --> 01:45:58.936
thing that sounds crazy is really happening,
and one is called the Casimir effect.

01:45:59.756 --> 01:46:03.636
So in the Casimir effect,
you take two metal plates,

01:46:04.276 --> 01:46:07.956
the parallel plates, and you put them
near one another, very, very close.

01:46:08.696 --> 01:46:12.486
Now, if this is the case, if these virtual

01:46:12.596 --> 01:46:16.576
particles exist, then in between
the plates, these particles

01:46:16.596 --> 01:46:20.456
appearing and disappearing, and
outside the plates, the particles are

01:46:20.536 --> 01:46:25.796
appearing and disappearing. However, because
these plates are close to one another,

01:46:26.596 --> 01:46:30.516
this puts a constraint on the
wavelength of the particles that can

01:46:30.556 --> 01:46:34.406
occur between the two plates
because they, the particles

01:46:34.476 --> 01:46:36.376
cannot extend outside the plates.

01:46:37.276 --> 01:46:41.116
So the short wavelength
particles can exist inside the—

01:46:41.136 --> 01:46:44.776
between the plates, but
the longer ones cannot.

01:46:44.896 --> 01:46:48.276
However, outside the plates,
there is no constraint, so short

01:46:48.336 --> 01:46:51.836
wavelength and long wavelength
particles can exist

01:46:51.896 --> 01:46:55.636
there. And the net effect is
there are more virtual particles

01:46:55.676 --> 01:46:59.566
outside and less particles
inside, and therefore you have a

01:46:59.616 --> 01:47:03.596
net pressure which would then push
those two plates together. That

01:47:03.656 --> 01:47:07.276
is a prediction we've been talking
about, and guess what? It happens.

01:47:07.836 --> 01:47:11.796
Those plates push together. So
that is a validation for the

01:47:11.836 --> 01:47:15.416
existence of these particles in
empty space. Now, there is another

01:47:15.456 --> 01:47:18.746
measurement, and this changes the magnetic

01:47:18.856 --> 01:47:22.636
properties of particles like the
electron, the muon and, and so

01:47:22.776 --> 01:47:30.976
forth. And so this was discovered in
1948. So if you take old school standard

01:47:31.056 --> 01:47:34.976
quantum mechanics you know the
spin of an electron, you know

01:47:35.016 --> 01:47:38.916
its charge, you can calculate its
magnetic moment, and it comes out to

01:47:38.956 --> 01:47:44.725
a number. If you do the measurement,
what you find is the measurement

01:47:45.096 --> 01:47:49.076
disagrees with the quantum mechanics,
the nineteen thirties quantum mechanical

01:47:49.176 --> 01:47:53.976
prediction by point one percent, and that
was measured in nineteen forty-eight.

01:47:54.956 --> 01:48:01.366
And people went, "Huh". So this happened
at Shelter Island Conference in New

01:48:01.416 --> 01:48:05.376
York. And on the way home,
someone who saw the,

01:48:05.386 --> 01:48:09.005
this measurement thought
about it, and they

01:48:09.056 --> 01:48:12.986
invented what we now call quantum
electrodynamics. So old quantum

01:48:13.036 --> 01:48:16.756
mechanics quantizes matter.
The second quantization

01:48:16.816 --> 01:48:20.716
quantizes both matter
and the fields, in this

01:48:20.776 --> 01:48:28.396
case, quantized the electric fields.
And so in this quantized field,

01:48:29.016 --> 01:48:32.896
it predicts that surrounding
a bare, say, electron,

01:48:32.976 --> 01:48:36.676
which is spinning and has
a, has a charge, there is

01:48:36.756 --> 01:48:40.396
this, this bath of
particles, virtual particles

01:48:40.436 --> 01:48:44.256
appearing and disappearing all
around it. And the ensemble of

01:48:44.336 --> 01:48:47.906
all of those particles
appearing and disappearing will

01:48:47.976 --> 01:48:51.616
alter the magnetic properties
that you can measure for the

01:48:51.636 --> 01:48:55.296
subatomic particle, and it
changes it by point one

01:48:55.376 --> 01:48:59.136
percent. And we have measured this,
and we have not measured this

01:48:59.196 --> 01:49:03.136
imprecisely. We have measured
the magnetic properties

01:49:03.176 --> 01:49:10.576
of both the electron and the muon to twelve,
count them, twelve significant figures.

01:49:11.036 --> 01:49:14.855
And the theory and the
data agree number for

01:49:14.896 --> 01:49:18.796
number for ten places. And
then once you get out to

01:49:18.836 --> 01:49:22.616
the very end where both
the theory and the data

01:49:22.716 --> 01:49:26.436
have some imprecision, they then
disagree. And so maybe there's some

01:49:26.476 --> 01:49:31.036
interesting stuff going on there. But
ten figures, it's just staggering.

01:49:31.576 --> 01:49:37.416
- So virtual particles refer to matter and
antimatter particles coming to life.

01:49:37.656 --> 01:49:37.956
- Correct.

01:49:38.156 --> 01:49:42.056
- Can we just talk about the antimatter
part of that? So starting with Paul

01:49:42.076 --> 01:49:49.396
Dirac, one of the most legendary examples
of math leading to physics. So the math

01:49:49.456 --> 01:49:53.376
suggesting that something
like antimatter should exist,

01:49:53.416 --> 01:49:56.736
and Paul Dirac taking
it seriously and then

01:49:56.816 --> 01:50:01.826
eventually showing that it does exist. So
what evidence do we have for antimatter?

01:50:02.256 --> 01:50:06.056
- So antimatter was predicted in
nineteen twenty-eight. Paul Dirac was

01:50:06.096 --> 01:50:09.756
trying to merge quantum mechanics
and relativity because the

01:50:09.796 --> 01:50:13.696
original Schrödinger equation did
not, was not relativistic. And in

01:50:13.716 --> 01:50:17.096
doing so, he basically, the
equations were complex, but

01:50:17.716 --> 01:50:21.356
in the end it came down to something
like equation squared equals

01:50:21.436 --> 01:50:25.376
one. You take the square root of both
sides, you get equation equals plus

01:50:25.456 --> 01:50:29.376
one or minus one. Plus one was the
electron, minus one was something.

01:50:29.436 --> 01:50:33.356
He didn't know what it was. There was
some conversation for a while, thought

01:50:33.396 --> 01:50:37.306
maybe it might be the proton, but that
didn't seem to work out. And so he insisted

01:50:37.356 --> 01:50:41.016
that his equations were right and
that there was an antimatter,

01:50:41.376 --> 01:50:48.456
he didn't call it an antimatter, but a
positively charged sibling of the electron,

01:50:48.736 --> 01:50:52.436
what we now call the positron, the
antimatter electron. So it was predicted.

01:50:52.906 --> 01:50:56.496
It was discovered in
nineteen thirty-two by Carl

01:50:56.596 --> 01:51:02.146
Anderson and his student Seth
Neddermeyer. They saw an antimatter

01:51:02.196 --> 01:51:06.140
electron. And that was pretty cool. So

01:51:06.200 --> 01:51:09.830
that right there, they knew it was
real. Antimatter was predicted, it was

01:51:09.860 --> 01:51:13.720
observed, that's that. In nineteen
fifty- six, the antimatter

01:51:13.800 --> 01:51:17.720
proton was created, and that required
a large particle accelerator,

01:51:18.060 --> 01:51:21.940
high enough energy to make
it, and that was done at

01:51:21.960 --> 01:51:25.120
Berkeley. And a year later,
the antimatter neutron was

01:51:25.140 --> 01:51:29.260
discovered. So at this point,
and now jumping ahead to now,

01:51:30.060 --> 01:51:33.820
we can make, using energy by

01:51:33.860 --> 01:51:37.340
smashing particles together, we
can make antimatter protons,

01:51:38.040 --> 01:51:41.780
we can make antimatter electrons.
We have gone so far to

01:51:41.860 --> 01:51:49.240
make antimatter helium nuclei. So we
have made two antiprotons and two

01:51:49.880 --> 01:51:53.680
antineutrons, combined them together
to make an antimatter helium

01:51:53.750 --> 01:51:56.880
nuclei. This has been done,
been observed, no question.

01:51:57.700 --> 01:52:01.080
At CERN, they have gone so far as to make

01:52:01.160 --> 01:52:05.149
antimatter hydrogen. They take
a beam off one of their lower

01:52:05.280 --> 01:52:08.899
energy accelerators. They
make antimatter protons.

01:52:09.500 --> 01:52:13.200
They collect them, they slow them down,
they cool them to almost absolute

01:52:13.320 --> 01:52:20.320
zero. They take Sodium-22, which makes
antimatter electrons. They slow them

01:52:20.360 --> 01:52:23.740
down, they bring them together, they
coalesce them, and they make literal

01:52:24.300 --> 01:52:27.980
antimatter hydrogen
atoms with an antimatter

01:52:28.040 --> 01:52:31.860
proton surrounded by an
antimatter electron. And

01:52:31.940 --> 01:52:35.920
they have done incredible
measurements. They have

01:52:36.020 --> 01:52:39.870
agitated the atoms and caused it to
emit light. They have looked at the

01:52:40.020 --> 01:52:43.970
light that comes out of antimatter
atoms. And the question is,

01:52:44.020 --> 01:52:47.440
is does the light coming out of
antimatter hydrogen atoms have

01:52:47.500 --> 01:52:51.320
exactly the same spectral characteristics
as ordinary hydrogen, which

01:52:51.400 --> 01:52:52.460
we predict that it does?

01:52:53.880 --> 01:52:57.620
And the answer is it does. So
the tests have been staggering.

01:52:58.300 --> 01:53:02.150
We now know a great deal about
antimatter hydrogen. Recently,

01:53:02.380 --> 01:53:06.140
recently like 2023, I believe it
was, one of the experiments called

01:53:06.200 --> 01:53:13.560
ALPHA at CERN made antimatter hydrogen,
put it in a bottle and released

01:53:13.620 --> 01:53:16.800
it and watched which way it would go.

01:53:17.640 --> 01:53:21.600
Did it fall up or did it
fall down? Because while

01:53:21.660 --> 01:53:25.500
it kind of makes sense maybe
to think that maybe antimatter

01:53:25.540 --> 01:53:29.300
falls up in the same way that we have
Coulomb's law, you've got electric

01:53:29.360 --> 01:53:32.820
charges, and they might
attract or repel. However,

01:53:33.240 --> 01:53:36.780
there was lots of ample
theoretical reasons to

01:53:36.820 --> 01:53:40.690
believe that antimatter also
would fall down. So they did this

01:53:40.740 --> 01:53:41.790
fantastic measurement,

01:53:42.640 --> 01:53:46.620
and they first they put in hydrogen,
and they calculated that some-- if they

01:53:46.720 --> 01:53:50.680
did this, something like eighty
percent of the hydrogen atoms would

01:53:50.780 --> 01:53:54.760
fall through the bottom of the
bottle, and twenty percent would go

01:53:54.800 --> 01:53:58.420
through the top just because
gravity is very weak

01:53:58.900 --> 01:54:02.620
and the atoms will escape wherever
they do, but there will be a bias

01:54:02.720 --> 01:54:06.180
pulling hydrogen atoms down. So
they did exactly the same thing,

01:54:07.120 --> 01:54:10.180
and what did they find?
They find that antimatter

01:54:10.900 --> 01:54:14.730
falls down. Now, they do not have
a good enough measurement at

01:54:14.780 --> 01:54:21.420
this time to say that the gravity that
antimatter experiences is one hundred percent

01:54:22.000 --> 01:54:25.149
that of matter. What they have measured

01:54:25.680 --> 01:54:29.570
is that antimatter fell
down with a seventy-five

01:54:29.600 --> 01:54:33.020
percent the strength of regular matter,

01:54:33.660 --> 01:54:37.440
but there were big uncertainties.
There was plus or minus .13

01:54:37.580 --> 01:54:45.239
three due to the experiment, which was
good but imperfect, and plus or minus .16

01:54:45.320 --> 01:54:49.140
due to their theoretical
model. So it's like point

01:54:49.260 --> 01:54:52.600
seven five plus or minus
something like point two nine.

01:54:53.340 --> 01:54:57.380
And that means there's a good chance
it's between point five and one-

01:54:57.420 --> 01:55:02.400
... which means it's consistent with one.
So they are improving their measurements.

01:55:02.920 --> 01:55:06.860
- Well, if I can, I would love to
