02:01:58.920 --> 02:02:02.220
that has a lot of mysteries.
There's a lot of exploration to be

02:02:02.260 --> 02:02:06.180
done. And so this kind
of connection to energy

02:02:06.240 --> 02:02:10.100
means that if we have a bunch
of breakthroughs on the

02:02:10.140 --> 02:02:13.820
antimatter side, that
might lead to a better

02:02:13.840 --> 02:02:16.580
propulsion system, better
energy generation systems.

02:02:16.820 --> 02:02:17.300
- In principle.

02:02:17.480 --> 02:02:21.450
- There's some combination of engineering here,
but there's some combination of understanding

02:02:21.450 --> 02:02:22.920
the fundamental physics.

02:02:22.980 --> 02:02:24.480
- I mean, we know how to do this.

02:02:25.840 --> 02:02:29.590
You know, we know you take
energy, you make antimatter.

02:02:30.140 --> 02:02:33.320
You have to contain it. You have to store
it. You have to do all the hard things.

02:02:34.100 --> 02:02:39.410
But I, I would be shocked if there
was some, like, new addition to the-

02:02:39.440 --> 02:02:41.640
... theory that made
antimatter production easier.

02:02:42.100 --> 02:02:45.860
- Interesting. So we know how to
produce antimatter with accelerators.

02:02:46.300 --> 02:02:50.100
You're saying there's not breakthroughs in

02:02:50.140 --> 02:02:54.360
physics that could lead to different
mechanisms for the generation of antimatter.

02:02:54.540 --> 02:02:58.520
- You have to concentrate energy. That's
it. If there's another way to concentrate

02:02:58.600 --> 02:03:00.140
energy, that would work too.

02:03:00.660 --> 02:03:03.920
- And our best knowledge of how to
concentrate energy is the accelerator.

02:03:03.950 --> 02:03:07.760
- And remember, we're talking
concentrating it into volumes

02:03:07.840 --> 02:03:11.800
the size of a proton. I mean, if you
concentrate it to the size of your thumb,

02:03:12.600 --> 02:03:16.180
well, then, you know, it's really
the density that matters, the local

02:03:16.200 --> 02:03:20.152
density. And so when you smash two
protons together, all of that's

02:03:20.192 --> 02:03:24.161
occurring in a tiny, tiny volume, so it's
the local density of energy that matters.

02:03:24.252 --> 02:03:27.382
If you had a lot of energy
in a thimble or something-

02:03:28.532 --> 02:03:32.552
... It's probably not
dense enough. You know-

02:03:32.562 --> 02:03:36.482
... it really has to be in close proximity
for that to happen, and then when

02:03:36.492 --> 02:03:40.092
it does, it's okay. So

02:03:40.432 --> 02:03:44.392
if there's another way, we know
how to do it, to make that density

02:03:44.492 --> 02:03:48.392
thing with accelerators. If
someone has a bright idea on

02:03:48.432 --> 02:03:51.912
how to make highly dense energy,

02:03:52.452 --> 02:03:57.102
then yeah making antimatter is a
piece of cake. But that's the crux-

02:03:57.192 --> 02:03:58.652
... concentrated energy.

02:03:59.532 --> 02:04:04.432
- Yeah, and how to do so in a cost-efficient
manner, not trillions of dollars.

02:04:05.092 --> 02:04:05.492
- Well, yeah.

02:04:05.812 --> 02:04:10.232
- So one of the big mysteries with
antimatter is the bigger why.

02:04:11.372 --> 02:04:14.852
Where is the antimatter that
should kind of be there

02:04:15.532 --> 02:04:19.072
if the whole idea is that
anytime you generate matter, you

02:04:19.152 --> 02:04:23.092
generate the same amount of antimatter, and
yet when we look out into the observable

02:04:23.192 --> 02:04:27.152
universe, it seems like there's not
antimatter for the most part there.

02:04:27.432 --> 02:04:27.592
- Correct.

02:04:27.632 --> 02:04:31.492
- So what do we understand about this mystery?
What are the possible explanations as

02:04:31.552 --> 02:04:31.952
to why?

02:04:32.712 --> 02:04:38.332
- So there's this thing called
baryogenesis and, as you say, so

02:04:39.652 --> 02:04:43.092
reiterating a little bit what
you just said these are both

02:04:43.172 --> 02:04:47.152
Einstein things. Einstein says that when you
take energy, you make matter and antimatter in

02:04:47.212 --> 02:04:51.112
equal quantities, and Einstein says after
the Big Bang, there was a lot of energy

02:04:51.172 --> 02:04:54.112
in the universe, which should
have made matter and antimatter.

02:04:54.172 --> 02:04:58.292
We only see matter. Where'd the antimatter
go? And the answer is, we don't know.

02:04:59.532 --> 02:05:04.612
However, there are some ideas, and
there's a lot of thinking on it, and

02:05:04.712 --> 02:05:08.192
in fact, for me, it's doing
an experiment right now with

02:05:08.202 --> 02:05:15.292
neutrinos, trying to better
understand what it was that made

02:05:15.492 --> 02:05:21.432
the matter and antimatter not be the
same. Now, we do have a measurement

02:05:21.492 --> 02:05:25.442
of how much different it should be,
and it's kind of neat. We can do this

02:05:25.472 --> 02:05:29.152
by counting the number of protons in the

02:05:29.191 --> 02:05:33.132
universe, just looking at galaxies
and so forth, and then we can

02:05:33.172 --> 02:05:37.012
look at the cosmic microwave background,
which is sort of the aftermath of the Big

02:05:37.092 --> 02:05:41.032
Bang, and we can count the number
of photons from the cosmic

02:05:41.072 --> 02:05:45.452
microwave background. And with a
little bit of math, what we can do

02:05:46.552 --> 02:05:54.312
is we can then say that somehow in the
early universe, something made a very,

02:05:54.432 --> 02:06:00.912
very tiny asymmetry, so that for
every billion, billion with a B,

02:06:01.852 --> 02:06:05.772
antimatter particles that existed
in the universe, there were

02:06:05.832 --> 02:06:09.272
a billion and one matter particles.

02:06:09.692 --> 02:06:13.372
The billions canceled, annihilated,
destroyed each other, and that

02:06:13.432 --> 02:06:16.582
extra one that's left over is us.

02:06:17.552 --> 02:06:24.512
And so what physics mechanism
made that ever so slight

02:06:25.632 --> 02:06:29.432
asymmetry is not understood.
There are some thoughts.

02:06:29.612 --> 02:06:33.512
One thought is that, well, it's

02:06:33.572 --> 02:06:37.422
just how it was. When the universe was
formed, there was an asymmetry. It was

02:06:37.512 --> 02:06:44.052
not made by matter and antimatter.
Another possibility is there are

02:06:44.092 --> 02:06:48.012
various numbers of theories all
under the word baryogenesis,

02:06:48.352 --> 02:06:52.172
baryo coming from word baryon,
which basically means protons,

02:06:52.782 --> 02:06:55.712
and genesis meaning the creation
of, and we'd say that simply

02:06:55.752 --> 02:06:59.692
because the protons are the
heaviest particles. And so

02:06:59.712 --> 02:07:01.912
baryogenesis is just
the creation of matter.

02:07:02.772 --> 02:07:06.512
And there are just a number of
theories in quantum mechanics that say

02:07:06.592 --> 02:07:08.272
that matter and antimatter can,

02:07:09.312 --> 02:07:13.152
can oscillate back and forth
into one another, and there

02:07:13.272 --> 02:07:16.962
is a slight, slight asymmetry in how that

02:07:17.032 --> 02:07:23.612
happens. And we know that this is true to
a degree. We've measured it in the 1960s

02:07:23.692 --> 02:07:29.432
with a different form of matter. I
mean you know, not protons, but a,

02:07:30.412 --> 02:07:34.352
a type of ephemeral matter that only
exists in particle accelerators. And so

02:07:34.392 --> 02:07:38.272
we know that there is a slight difference
between matter and antimatter,

02:07:38.352 --> 02:07:42.132
but it's not enough. It doesn't explain
that. We're not sure. So at Fermilab,

02:07:42.772 --> 02:07:46.682
we have this idea which kind of
turns things on its head, and it's

02:07:46.752 --> 02:07:50.952
not baryogenesis, it's leptogenesis.
So leptons are the electrons.

02:07:52.072 --> 02:08:00.692
And because Fermilab is currently the
world's most powerful neutrino accelerator,

02:08:01.732 --> 02:08:05.592
and neutrinos are leptons, there
is this idea. Now, leptogenesis is

02:08:05.612 --> 02:08:09.052
incredibly complicated, but the idea is

02:08:10.052 --> 02:08:13.872
that it is possible. We know
that neutrinos actually

02:08:13.922 --> 02:08:17.872
change their identity. There are three
different types of neutrinos like

02:08:18.292 --> 02:08:21.992
I don't know, cats and jaguars and
tigers, and if you have a beam of just

02:08:22.052 --> 02:08:25.922
cats, if you go along a little while,
you find there's cats and jaguars and

02:08:25.932 --> 02:08:29.662
then tigers, and then they'll be
back to all cats again. And so this

02:08:29.752 --> 02:08:33.072
oscillation thing is called neutrino
oscillation. We've known it's been true since

02:08:33.092 --> 02:08:38.892
1998, and what we are studying
is we're going to make

02:08:38.952 --> 02:08:42.592
a beam of neutrinos and
another beam of antimatter

02:08:42.632 --> 02:08:46.592
neutrinos, and we're going to study
the oscillation behavior of the two of

02:08:46.632 --> 02:08:49.982
them. And it is possible,
it is unlikely, but it is

02:08:50.012 --> 02:08:55.152
possible that the two of them will
oscillate at slightly different rates.

02:08:55.772 --> 02:08:59.572
And if the neutrinos oscillate
at slightly different rates,

02:09:00.032 --> 02:09:03.752
then that, along with several
other highly improbable

02:09:03.762 --> 02:09:10.602
things, can tie together and might explain
why there is more matter in the universe.

02:09:11.192 --> 02:09:15.032
So if I was gonna bet the farm,
I'll bet that they oscillate at the

02:09:15.072 --> 02:09:18.932
same rate, but I don't know, and you don't
know till you do the measurements, so that's

02:09:18.972 --> 02:09:22.832
what we're doing. There are some other
experiments trying to measure it

02:09:22.852 --> 02:09:26.812
right now, so there's a big race
between the Fermilab group and

02:09:26.872 --> 02:09:30.812
another group in Japan to see who gets
there first and, and make this measurement,

02:09:31.632 --> 02:09:35.438
and we will find out. If it turns out,
though, that there is a difference in

02:09:35.488 --> 02:09:39.428
this oscillation rate between matter
and antimatter, it will be a huge

02:09:39.808 --> 02:09:42.268
clue in this very, very difficult puzzle.

02:09:43.128 --> 02:09:47.108
I wish I could tell you I knew
what the answer is, but literally

02:09:47.408 --> 02:09:51.328
nobody knows. I mean, and that's the
thing of being a research scientist like

02:09:51.368 --> 02:09:55.148
me is if you're not confused-
... you're not doing your job.

02:09:55.648 --> 02:09:59.208
- So there is this desperate or
not desperate, exciting search

02:09:59.428 --> 02:10:01.408
for this tiny asymmetry.

02:10:01.808 --> 02:10:02.048
- Yes.

02:10:02.238 --> 02:10:06.868
- It's so, so crazy to think that
everything we see around us

02:10:08.228 --> 02:10:11.988
is a result of this tiny asymmetry,
that there was this gigantic

02:10:12.188 --> 02:10:14.868
annihilation of matter and
antimatter in the early-

02:10:14.948 --> 02:10:14.958
- Yes

02:10:14.958 --> 02:10:20.238
- ... universe, and this is just
some little accident. But yeah.

02:10:20.268 --> 02:10:20.998
- Yeah, that's crazy.

02:10:21.028 --> 02:10:22.068
- It's a happy accident.

02:10:22.748 --> 02:10:24.688
- That is—I mean, it's totally crazy.

02:10:25.288 --> 02:10:29.728
- This is one of the areas of physics
where there's a lot of mystery.

02:10:31.928 --> 02:10:35.748
Okay. So can we pull at that thread a

02:10:35.848 --> 02:10:39.688
little further? Let's talk about
our intuition of what is dark

02:10:39.728 --> 02:10:42.868
energy as it connects to empty space and
everything we've been talking about.

02:10:43.788 --> 02:10:46.408
What's the cleanest
definition of dark energy?

02:10:46.908 --> 02:10:54.228
- So dark energy is either energy
of space or energy in space.

02:10:54.828 --> 02:10:58.578
The most common statement
is the energy of space,

02:10:59.688 --> 02:11:04.108
and it is essentially a
repulsive form of gravity.

02:11:05.328 --> 02:11:09.178
And we believe this is real,
and the reason we believe

02:11:09.178 --> 02:11:13.168
this is real is from observation.
This is one of those things where

02:11:13.188 --> 02:11:17.118
we talked about a while ago where I said
that, you know, you can think about things

02:11:17.168 --> 02:11:21.058
up this theoretical stuff and try to
come up with a measurement, or you

02:11:21.088 --> 02:11:24.688
can make measurements and
see where they disagree with

02:11:24.748 --> 02:11:28.528
predictions and lead that in
a direction. So back in the

02:11:28.588 --> 02:11:32.548
late 1990s, some astronomers were
looking at the expansion rate of the

02:11:32.608 --> 02:11:35.908
universe. So the Big Bang occurred,
the universe is expanding,

02:11:36.608 --> 02:11:40.468
the universe is full of matter,
matter attracts, so the

02:11:40.648 --> 02:11:44.608
gravity due to the matter of the
universe should slow the expansion of

02:11:44.648 --> 02:11:48.348
the universe. And the only
question was how much?

02:11:48.788 --> 02:11:52.088
There were three possibilities. The
possibilities were there was so much

02:11:52.128 --> 02:11:55.988
gravitational force that the
expansion of the universe

02:11:56.048 --> 02:11:59.708
would slow, stop, and be pulled
back together in a big crunch.

02:12:00.268 --> 02:12:03.668
Number two was that the
universe would continue

02:12:03.678 --> 02:12:07.558
expanding, slowing down,
but never really stopping.

02:12:08.148 --> 02:12:11.878
And then the third possibility was
the exact critical case, where

02:12:11.888 --> 02:12:15.408
expansion would slow forever and
approach zero only at infinity,

02:12:15.968 --> 02:12:19.868
never quite stopping or reversing. So
those were the possibilities, door number

02:12:19.968 --> 02:12:23.458
one, two, or three. So they did
the measurement, and what did they

02:12:23.488 --> 02:12:27.468
found? It was door number
four. The universe was not

02:12:27.528 --> 02:12:31.508
only expanding, but the expansion was speeding
up, and the only way that could happen,

02:12:31.548 --> 02:12:35.428
given that gravity slows it down,
is there was a repulsive force, and

02:12:35.488 --> 02:12:39.308
the name we give to that
repulsive force is dark energy.

02:12:40.048 --> 02:12:47.448
This is something that Einstein postulated
early on in his development of,

02:12:47.568 --> 02:12:51.528
of general relativity, but then because

02:12:51.568 --> 02:12:55.108
at the time, he knew that his theory
predicted that the universe would

02:12:55.148 --> 02:12:58.728
collapse but he believed the
universe was eternal and not

02:12:58.788 --> 02:13:02.747
unchanging, and so he needed
something to counterbalance the

02:13:03.928 --> 02:13:07.768
that collapse, and so he invented
dark energy. He didn't call it that.

02:13:08.168 --> 02:13:11.588
Called it the cosmological
constant. But then a few years

02:13:11.628 --> 02:13:15.558
later, Edwin Hubble discovered that
the universe was indeed expanding,

02:13:16.008 --> 02:13:19.748
and so since the universe was no
longer static, Einstein said,

02:13:20.388 --> 02:13:23.378
"No need for cosmological
constant," took it back out.

02:13:23.497 --> 02:13:27.328
Thought it was a dumb idea that he
put it in, and was embarrassed.

02:13:27.448 --> 02:13:31.437
However, in 1998 it became clear that
his original idea that there should

02:13:31.468 --> 02:13:38.288
be some sort of repulsive form of gravity
was real, and it's put back in the theory.

02:13:38.328 --> 02:13:42.268
And so that's what it is. We are pretty
confident at this point that the expansion

02:13:42.328 --> 02:13:46.168
of the universe is speeding
up, and the thing driving

02:13:46.228 --> 02:13:51.668
it is dark energy. Now, what is dark
energy? I don't know. As I said,

02:13:52.588 --> 02:13:57.448
the most common thought is that
it is the energy of space itself,

02:13:58.368 --> 02:14:04.408
but it is at least conceivable that there
is a field in space where space exists-

02:14:05.308 --> 02:14:07.868
... and that field is pushing space apart.

02:14:08.698 --> 02:14:12.468
That's another conceivability
that I'm not sure that we

02:14:12.508 --> 02:14:16.398
have the instrumentation to distinguish,
but that's not what normally people

02:14:16.428 --> 02:14:18.648
think. People think it is
literally a property of space.

02:14:19.828 --> 02:14:21.788
- But there is the

02:14:23.388 --> 02:14:26.798
what, what you call the worst
prediction in physics, which is a nice-

02:14:26.798 --> 02:14:27.818
- Oh, yeah. That's another one

02:14:27.888 --> 02:14:31.718
- ... a nice little insight about
the complicated nature of

02:14:31.788 --> 02:14:34.828
dark energy. So the observations,

02:14:35.828 --> 02:14:39.468
as you describe, say that empty space
has a tiny energy density that, to

02:14:39.528 --> 02:14:45.428
accelerates expansion of the universe.
But quantum field theory's prediction

02:14:46.248 --> 02:14:51.748
for what vacuum energy should be when
coupled with gravity is much larger.

02:14:52.308 --> 02:14:56.278
Uh, so this is what makes for the
quote, you have a video on this worst

02:14:56.388 --> 02:14:58.327
prediction in physics.

02:14:58.448 --> 02:14:58.928
- Yes.

02:14:58.968 --> 02:15:00.608
- Can you, can you explain this crisis?

02:15:00.688 --> 02:15:04.268
- Well, the-- there's a measurement, and
you can measure how fast the universe is

02:15:04.308 --> 02:15:07.788
expanding, and from that you get
a measurement of dark energy.

02:15:08.568 --> 02:15:15.588
However, if you then say, well,
suppose the dark energy is due to

02:15:15.598 --> 02:15:19.418
fields in space. So that's quantum
field theory. Hey, I know a lot

02:15:19.488 --> 02:15:24.068
about quantum field theory. And so we can
take the quantum field theory, and we can

02:15:24.148 --> 02:15:27.888
calculate what the density of energy is

02:15:28.148 --> 02:15:35.137
due to quantum field theory. And basically
what you do is you take within a volume

02:15:35.728 --> 02:15:39.498
the all of the wavelengths, the
longer wavelengths, the shorter

02:15:39.548 --> 02:15:41.818
wavelengths, the shorter wave-- shorter
and shorter, and you can add them all

02:15:41.868 --> 02:15:49.488
up. And each wavelength adds a certain
amount of energy, and if you add that all

02:15:49.518 --> 02:15:56.798
up, then you get a number, and that
number is the rather embarrassing

02:15:56.898 --> 02:16:04.188
10 to the 120 power times, that's
a one with 120 zeros after

02:16:04.318 --> 02:16:08.078
it, bigger than the
measurement of dark energy.

02:16:08.678 --> 02:16:13.528
So you go, "Yuck, that is not fun at all."

02:16:13.838 --> 02:16:17.598
And that is because the equation comes to

02:16:17.678 --> 02:16:20.918
the highest energy or
the smallest wavelength

02:16:21.418 --> 02:16:25.218
particle that you can imagine
to the fourth power, since

02:16:25.358 --> 02:16:28.638
anything to the fourth
power is a big deal. So

02:16:29.538 --> 02:16:33.078
that's where you get that awful
number. Now, if it turns out

02:16:33.518 --> 02:16:37.208
that there is some new physics
that's just about at the energy

02:16:37.298 --> 02:16:41.278
scale we can measure using our biggest
particle accelerators, remember I told

02:16:41.318 --> 02:16:45.088
you that that was a factor,
the maximum energy scale,

02:16:45.088 --> 02:16:48.988
Planck scale, is 10 to
the 15 times bigger than

02:16:49.018 --> 02:16:52.768
what we can measure now.
So let's say that we don't

02:16:52.898 --> 02:16:56.838
have to calculate up to the Planck
scale because something happens,

02:16:56.918 --> 02:16:59.898
something changes at the
energy that we know right

02:16:59.938 --> 02:17:03.898
now. Well, then that means we don't
have to integrate to Planck scale, we

02:17:03.958 --> 02:17:07.798
integrate to 10 to the 15th less
of the Planck scale, and this

02:17:07.838 --> 02:17:12.918
thing is to the fourth power, so 10 to the
15th to the fourth power is 60. So now,

02:17:14.278 --> 02:17:18.218
even if we say, you know, Don, he's
brilliant, he's gonna find something at

02:17:18.258 --> 02:17:22.128
the LHC tomorrow that's gonna solve all
this problem, now we've solved it, it's

02:17:22.218 --> 02:17:25.808
much better. It's only different
by 10 to the 60th power,

02:17:26.378 --> 02:17:30.238
which is still pretty bleeding
big. So the short answer

02:17:30.438 --> 02:17:33.898
is there is very clearly
something going on, something

02:17:33.938 --> 02:17:37.778
wrong, very badly wrong in
the quantum field theory.

02:17:38.818 --> 02:17:42.398
You know, we have to have, maybe there's
another field that balances out the

02:17:42.418 --> 02:17:45.918
energy, that cancels it
down. And even that,

02:17:46.638 --> 02:17:50.258
you know, that's not so
outrageous. You know, you could

02:17:50.318 --> 02:17:54.118
imagine that there's another, you know,
like we have matter and antimatter, they

02:17:54.158 --> 02:17:58.018
balance pretty well. Okay, maybe there's
something going on, you could cancel that

02:17:58.078 --> 02:18:01.858
out, that'd be perfect. But
canceling something to zero

02:18:02.218 --> 02:18:06.998
is easy 'cause, you know, plus one and
minus one, zero. Plus two, minus two, zero.

02:18:07.838 --> 02:18:11.718
But we still have dark energy. Dark energy
is a little bit, so if it cancels, it

02:18:11.758 --> 02:18:15.618
doesn't cancel exactly 'cause
it left over that little bit of

02:18:15.658 --> 02:18:19.378
dark energy. So that is its own curiosity.

02:18:19.818 --> 02:18:23.478
Perfect cancellation, pretty easy.
Theorists do that, you know, eight

02:18:23.578 --> 02:18:27.558
times before breakfast. Imperfect
cancellation, much harder.

02:18:27.758 --> 02:18:31.478
- Just to elaborate that a little bit,
what do you think solving, in quotes,

02:18:31.638 --> 02:18:33.438
solving dark energy would look like?

02:18:33.458 --> 02:18:37.208
- Well, what you would do is you would
hypothesize that there existed some other

02:18:37.238 --> 02:18:43.838
field that had the reverse effect
of existing quantum fields.

02:18:44.038 --> 02:18:44.938
- But not to zero.

02:18:45.198 --> 02:18:49.158
- But not to zero. So if you had
it to go to zero, you know

02:18:49.278 --> 02:18:52.418
sure, maybe there's a field
that, that exists at really high

02:18:52.478 --> 02:18:56.238
energies that we haven't seen
yet. I don't know, but it

02:18:56.298 --> 02:18:57.698
canceled things out, and we're cool.

02:18:58.038 --> 02:19:00.478
- How would we then demonstrate
the existence of that field?

02:19:00.818 --> 02:19:03.118
- Uh, well, that would depend
on the, the prediction.

02:19:03.278 --> 02:19:05.338
- How do you even come up with a new field?

02:19:05.758 --> 02:19:09.398
- Like all theorists do. Well, let's add
something to my equation and see what happens.

02:19:10.038 --> 02:19:12.168
I mean, and that's okay. I mean, I—

02:19:12.318 --> 02:19:16.018
... I'm being glib about that, but that
is precisely what you do. You say,

02:19:16.058 --> 02:19:19.958
what change? We, we have this thing
that works quite beautifully except

02:19:19.978 --> 02:19:25.198
it fails here. What is the addition
that we need to make that changes

02:19:25.738 --> 02:19:31.478
very little in the realm that we
measured and yet fixes this hard thing?

02:19:31.718 --> 02:19:35.038
And so you literally just go, da,
da, da, okay, what do I need?

02:19:35.798 --> 02:19:40.318
Plus six or something. And as
long as it makes no changes where

02:19:41.398 --> 02:19:45.338
it would hurt our measurements and
fixes the big thing, then that is

02:19:45.418 --> 02:19:49.158
at least a candidate theory. Now,
that doesn't mean it's right, but

02:19:49.358 --> 02:19:58.718
it at least gives you an understanding of
what the right answer should look like.

02:19:58.998 --> 02:20:02.858
And so that's the first step, is what
should the real answer look like or what

02:20:02.958 --> 02:20:06.778
is a possible real answer?
And then once you kind of

02:20:06.818 --> 02:20:10.618
know that, then other people can look
and say, "Well, let me think about a

02:20:10.678 --> 02:20:14.198
theory that kind of has
the required properties

02:20:15.178 --> 02:20:18.987
to do what we need it to do." So it's
a multi-step process, but the first

02:20:19.058 --> 02:20:24.428
step is how do we tame
this problem without

02:20:25.298 --> 02:20:31.198
coming up with really terrible
predictions that we've already ruled out?

02:20:31.238 --> 02:20:36.058
And so that's what you do. And,
you know, that is literally a

02:20:37.218 --> 02:20:41.118
sensible, viable, theoretical thing,
you know, 'cause you have to explore

02:20:41.238 --> 02:20:41.838
cool ideas.

02:20:42.298 --> 02:20:47.398
- I mean, one of the reasons dark energy is
super interesting is it kind of gives us

02:20:48.218 --> 02:20:52.198
a mechanism by which we can talk about
the deep future of the universe. I

02:20:52.238 --> 02:20:56.198
mean, it's making-- We have observations
about the expansion of the universe,

02:20:57.518 --> 02:21:00.878
but it's also giving us the
mechanism of that, right?

02:21:00.998 --> 02:21:01.008
- Sure.

02:21:01.008 --> 02:21:01.978
- So we can talk about,

02:21:03.818 --> 02:21:07.618
Any weirdness, any good model we
have that, that captures some of the

02:21:07.658 --> 02:21:11.458
weirdness of dark energy
might give us insights about

02:21:11.518 --> 02:21:13.738
how this thing ends, how the universe-

02:21:13.858 --> 02:21:14.268
- Sure, sure

02:21:14.268 --> 02:21:15.888
- ... about the deep future
of the universe, right?

02:21:15.978 --> 02:21:19.778
- Absolutely. As it stands right now,
if dark energy is real, and who

02:21:19.818 --> 02:21:22.628
knows, you know, if it's real
exactly as we've measured it,

02:21:23.358 --> 02:21:27.948
then as the universe
gets bigger and bigger,

02:21:29.078 --> 02:21:33.398
dark energy becomes a bigger
and bigger component of the-

02:21:33.418 --> 02:21:36.998
... energy balance of the universe,
and it takes over, and it drives the

02:21:37.038 --> 02:21:40.168
continued accelerated
expansion of the universe.

02:21:40.882 --> 02:21:44.531
And if dark energy gets lower, you
know, for some reason that we don't

02:21:44.562 --> 02:21:47.961
understand, maybe it changes over time,
gets smaller. That could change things.

02:21:48.002 --> 02:21:49.852
If it gets bigger, it could change things-

02:21:50.022 --> 02:21:53.422
- That is one of the big open questions,
whether it's constant over time or not

02:21:53.722 --> 02:21:57.521
- ... Right. And there has been a recent measurement
that suggests that dark energy is getting

02:21:57.602 --> 02:22:01.242
smaller. However, that is
a new measurement, not

02:22:01.342 --> 02:22:04.482
confirmed, blah, blah, blah, blah,
blah. Nobody should believe it,

02:22:05.242 --> 02:22:09.122
but it's a hint that maybe it's
changing, which is kind of cool

02:22:09.242 --> 02:22:13.001
in itself because the
current bias until recently

02:22:13.082 --> 02:22:16.782
is that dark energy is
constant. Now, I wanna be

02:22:16.842 --> 02:22:20.582
super careful because
it's misleading. People

02:22:20.602 --> 02:22:25.002
say dark energy is constant.
Dark energy is a density.

02:22:25.442 --> 02:22:29.222
Now, that-- think about that. You have a
certain density, let's start with that.

02:22:29.972 --> 02:22:36.122
Then the universe expands. So energy is
volume times density. If the universe

02:22:36.162 --> 02:22:42.032
gets bigger and the density is constant,
that means dark energy is increasing.

02:22:42.182 --> 02:22:45.512
It's not just increasing as
a fraction and overwhelming

02:22:45.982 --> 02:22:49.762
ordinary matter, but ordinary
matter, as the universe

02:22:49.802 --> 02:22:53.662
expands, its density decreases
because it's constant and the

02:22:53.702 --> 02:22:57.602
volume gets bigger, the density
drops. Dark energy, until

02:22:57.702 --> 02:23:01.382
recently, is thought to
be constant density.

02:23:02.022 --> 02:23:05.982
- So that's what's implied when you say constant. You
say constant density, which means it's actually

02:23:06.022 --> 02:23:08.792
increasing because space is
increasing. The size of space-

02:23:08.902 --> 02:23:09.072
- Right

02:23:09.072 --> 02:23:09.832
- ... is increasing. Interesting.

02:23:09.832 --> 02:23:13.282
- And so that's a weirdness,
and that then ties

02:23:13.402 --> 02:23:17.322
into the nature of space.
Why does that tie into the

02:23:17.342 --> 02:23:20.722
nature of space? Well, because
if dark energy is a field

02:23:21.262 --> 02:23:26.332
in space, if you increase the volume, you
would think the energy density would drop.

02:23:26.682 --> 02:23:30.662
But if space is increasing and space
is quantized, and I don't know

02:23:30.722 --> 02:23:34.282
if it is, then maybe what's
happening is space isn't

02:23:34.442 --> 02:23:38.102
stretching, but like little
space particles are appearing

02:23:38.322 --> 02:23:42.282
as the space, you know, there's like
bubbles of space appearing, and each

02:23:42.302 --> 02:23:46.092
bubble contains a certain amount
of dark energy. And so therefore,

02:23:46.182 --> 02:23:49.842
that would give you a sense that
dark energy is a property of

02:23:49.902 --> 02:23:57.522
space rather than a field in space. But
that's all very hand-wavy guess-worky

02:23:57.642 --> 02:23:57.962
stuff.

02:23:58.462 --> 02:24:02.582
- So if you had to bet all your
money, is dark energy like a real

02:24:03.522 --> 02:24:09.142
physical, what does that even mean, thing
that exists versus is this just an,

02:24:09.962 --> 02:24:12.622
a renaming of the cosmological constant?

02:24:13.122 --> 02:24:17.132
- Unfortunately, I think it's
both. I mean, well, I mean—

02:24:17.132 --> 02:24:20.822
it is, it's describing a
reality, but it's also

02:24:20.962 --> 02:24:23.782
maybe telling us something about space.

02:24:24.162 --> 02:24:25.702
- Literally a property of space.

02:24:25.762 --> 02:24:29.582
- Yeah. It's, I mean, that's kind of what
it looks like. Given that it seems to

02:24:29.622 --> 02:24:35.202
be constant density, that seems to
me-- Now, this is not something

02:24:35.562 --> 02:24:38.262
anybody should believe. Please,
nobody believe this. But

02:24:39.462 --> 02:24:43.762
it seems to me that this is
leaning towards the idea

02:24:44.762 --> 02:24:52.002
that, A, it's a property of space, B,
space is quantized, C, as space is

02:24:52.042 --> 02:24:55.982
expanding, little quanta of
space are appearing, and D,

02:24:56.522 --> 02:25:00.412
each one of those quanta has a certain amount
of energy associated with it, and that

02:25:00.422 --> 02:25:01.772
would kind of explain

02:25:02.762 --> 02:25:07.671
the constant density. Now, please, that's
not— Anybody should— Nobody accepts that.

02:25:07.682 --> 02:25:09.141
This is just nonsense.

02:25:09.722 --> 02:25:13.072
- But a lot of the stuff that you
just said is experimentally,

02:25:13.722 --> 02:25:16.542
probably experimentally testable.
You can probably construct-

02:25:17.082 --> 02:25:17.382
- Well

02:25:17.422 --> 02:25:18.632
- ... experimentally the bubbles of

02:25:19.822 --> 02:25:23.552
- Well, finding out the bubbles of space,
but those quanta conceivably are

02:25:23.642 --> 02:25:25.162
Planck size bubbles.

02:25:25.282 --> 02:25:26.102
- Yeah, the quanta.

02:25:26.502 --> 02:25:30.222
- Well, they'd be quanta of space. I mean,
the idea is, you know, you look at a sand

02:25:30.302 --> 02:25:33.992
dune and it looks smooth and continuous,
but you can see individual grains of

02:25:34.082 --> 02:25:38.682
sand, right? And so what this is
saying is as this dune expands,

02:25:39.622 --> 02:25:43.062
new grains of sand are appearing, and
each one of them is a quantum of space.

02:25:43.722 --> 02:25:47.402
- So what kind of experiments can
we do in the coming decades

02:25:48.122 --> 02:25:50.542
or centuries to understand
dark energy better?

02:25:51.262 --> 02:25:55.572
- I mean, people have been talking about
quantum entanglement of gravity.

02:25:56.802 --> 02:25:59.922
In standard quantum mechanics, a particle
can be in two places at the same

02:25:59.942 --> 02:26:03.722
time. All right? So now
you have two particles. So

02:26:03.802 --> 02:26:07.782
this particle can be in two places at the same time.
This particle can be in two places at the same time,

02:26:07.822 --> 02:26:11.622
and you put them near one another. Well, if
they're close to each other, there's a certain

02:26:11.642 --> 02:26:15.562
gravitational force. If they're far apart,
there are certain... And if they, one

02:26:15.582 --> 02:26:18.722
is close and one is far, you have
another one. You can calculate

02:26:18.842 --> 02:26:22.722
the effects of gravity having to

02:26:22.822 --> 02:26:27.122
do with quantum entangled
particles being in two places. And

02:26:28.022 --> 02:26:31.342
people are talking about
doing this and trying to

02:26:31.502 --> 02:26:35.422
see if in doing such a
measurement, they might

02:26:35.462 --> 02:26:42.322
be able to definitively determine
whether gravity is a quantum phenomenon

02:26:43.002 --> 02:26:45.822
or a continuous phenomenon.

02:26:45.962 --> 02:26:49.952
And that is potentially a
measurement that could be done

02:26:51.262 --> 02:26:54.582
soon-ish because the technologies of

02:26:55.422 --> 02:26:59.342
inherent in all of this recent
work on quantum mechanics

02:26:59.522 --> 02:27:03.022
is allowing people to be able to make

02:27:04.302 --> 02:27:08.062
instrumentation that might be precise
enough to do this measurement.

02:27:08.982 --> 02:27:12.952
Now, this will not tell us what quantum gravity
is. It will not tell us anything, but it

02:27:12.962 --> 02:27:16.462
will tell us that gravity is quantized.

02:27:17.192 --> 02:27:20.842
And just knowing that, well,
for one thing, it shuts out a

02:27:20.902 --> 02:27:24.882
whole realm of continuous
gravity, and the theoretical

02:27:24.892 --> 02:27:28.692
community will then turn its attention,
forget this stuff, and, and think

02:27:28.762 --> 02:27:32.622
over here. Now, that doesn't tell you
that space is quantized, but it tells you

02:27:32.682 --> 02:27:36.502
that gravity is quantized if it bears out.

02:27:37.182 --> 02:27:41.002
So if gravity is quantized, then people
will start thinking more about space

02:27:41.062 --> 02:27:41.922
being quantized.

02:27:42.522 --> 02:27:46.498
- I have to ask 'cause you mentioned dark
matter is perhaps even more mysterious

02:27:46.778 --> 02:27:47.538
than dark energy.

02:27:47.958 --> 02:27:48.138
- Okay.

02:27:48.338 --> 02:27:48.538
- Can you,

02:27:49.418 --> 02:27:53.348
can you build up the intuition why it's
more mysterious? What is dark matter?

02:27:53.478 --> 02:27:59.338
- Oh gosh, what is dark matter? A, I don't
know. B, it's terribly fascinating.

02:27:59.378 --> 02:28:02.738
All right? So first thing, and the
most important thing 'cause I'm an

02:28:02.778 --> 02:28:04.098
experimentalist, by God,

02:28:04.918 --> 02:28:08.798
the first thing is why do we believe
there's dark matter? And the reason is that

02:28:09.178 --> 02:28:13.118
astronomical measurements do
not agree with predictions by

02:28:13.178 --> 02:28:17.038
Newtonian or relativity
theory. Galaxies spin too

02:28:17.178 --> 02:28:20.418
fast, clusters of galaxies
move too quickly,

02:28:21.158 --> 02:28:25.058
and the distortion of
very distant galaxies due

02:28:25.098 --> 02:28:27.288
to the gravitational
field of nearer galaxies

02:28:28.138 --> 02:28:31.678
disagrees with the prediction
from what we see from the

02:28:31.718 --> 02:28:35.598
observed matter. So there are three very

02:28:35.638 --> 02:28:39.478
distinct reasons why we
are predicting that,

02:28:39.538 --> 02:28:46.758
something is wrong in our understanding of
either the laws of physics or the matter

02:28:46.858 --> 02:28:50.698
budget of the universe. The
easiest one to talk about is the

02:28:50.718 --> 02:28:54.658
spinning galaxies. Now, this is--
what I'm saying is not unique to

02:28:54.718 --> 02:29:01.538
spinning galaxies, just easiest to talk
about. So galaxies are observed to spin more

02:29:01.618 --> 02:29:05.378
quickly than they should if we add up the

02:29:05.398 --> 02:29:09.278
gravity we see. By all rights, galaxies
spinning that fast should blow themselves

02:29:09.298 --> 02:29:16.478
apart, and they don't. So what can be
the answer? Well, you have the force

02:29:16.518 --> 02:29:20.358
required for a star to orbit to
move in a circle, and you have the

02:29:20.418 --> 02:29:23.418
force due to gravity, and they're
connected by an equal sign,

02:29:24.218 --> 02:29:29.028
and the prediction is wrong. So either
the force due to gravity is wrong,

02:29:30.088 --> 02:29:33.958
the force needed to move in a circle is
wrong, or the equal sign is wrong. I mean,

02:29:33.998 --> 02:29:36.538
this is really simple. One
of those things is wrong.

02:29:38.098 --> 02:29:41.938
So one possibility is
simply that Newton's law of

02:29:41.998 --> 02:29:46.338
gravity, mass times the mass over R squared
times a constant, that's just wrong.

02:29:47.238 --> 02:29:51.098
Another possibility is Newton's
F equals ma that we are taught

02:29:51.218 --> 02:29:55.138
in introductory physics is wrong.
Both of those are eminently

02:29:55.158 --> 02:29:58.598
possible. Over here, maybe
we don't understand gravity,

02:29:59.778 --> 02:30:03.618
or maybe there's more
mass than we can see.

02:30:04.458 --> 02:30:08.438
So these, you know, I mean, it's nice that you
can look at this really simply and come up

02:30:08.458 --> 02:30:12.788
with a list, you know, a cookbook
of things we can test. And

02:30:14.078 --> 02:30:17.348
and so we've done that. We've
gone and said, "What are the

02:30:17.418 --> 02:30:21.128
possibilities?" Well, the most
obvious possibility is that there is

02:30:21.598 --> 02:30:24.718
more mass than we can see.
There's black holes, there's,

02:30:25.558 --> 02:30:29.348
hydrogen gas that we can't see,
whatever. There's something out there.

02:30:29.798 --> 02:30:33.778
So that was the first thing. So you go and you
look, and there's no hydrogen gas because we

02:30:33.818 --> 02:30:35.837
can see that with radio
waves. That's not it.

02:30:36.698 --> 02:30:40.618
In the '90s, we went looking for black
holes, rogue planets, things like

02:30:40.718 --> 02:30:43.638
that. Those exist, but not enough of them.

02:30:43.758 --> 02:30:49.278
That's not it. And so now we're left
with there's some sort of matter that we

02:30:49.338 --> 02:30:53.098
can't see, or we don't understand
gravity, or we don't understand

02:30:53.158 --> 02:31:01.038
inertia. Now, I personally, if you asked
me this, oh, I don't know, 25 years ago, I

02:31:01.058 --> 02:31:08.598
would've said the most likely answer is that
we don't understand inertia or gravity.

02:31:09.158 --> 02:31:12.918
You know, I-- if 20 years ago, 25 years
ago, that's what I would've said, no

02:31:12.938 --> 02:31:18.198
problem. However, there have been
a couple of observations that

02:31:19.508 --> 02:31:23.238
that have caused me to change my
thinking, and I think that dark matter is

02:31:23.358 --> 02:31:26.958
more likely. One of them is called
the Bullet Cluster. So the Bullet

02:31:27.018 --> 02:31:30.418
Cluster, there are two
large clusters of galaxies.

02:31:31.458 --> 02:31:35.258
In these large clusters of
galaxies, well, any galaxy

02:31:35.268 --> 02:31:38.738
consists of a couple of
components. There are the

02:31:38.778 --> 02:31:42.558
galaxies themselves, there is the
hydrogen gas that surrounds the

02:31:42.598 --> 02:31:44.858
galaxies, and maybe there is dark matter.

02:31:46.118 --> 02:31:49.928
And if dark matter is real
or dark matter is not real,

02:31:50.418 --> 02:31:54.068
you will get different answers if those
two galaxies pass through one another.

02:31:54.858 --> 02:31:58.778
The galaxies themselves should pass through one
another basically not interacting, but the big thing

02:31:58.818 --> 02:32:02.738
is the gas clouds. So if
there's big clouds of gas, as

02:32:02.778 --> 02:32:06.738
the galaxies pass through one another, the clouds
should interact, and the gas clouds should

02:32:06.898 --> 02:32:10.778
stop in the middle and be really,
really hot. So then you would see, if

02:32:10.818 --> 02:32:14.378
there were no dark matter,
you would see a cluster of

02:32:14.418 --> 02:32:17.398
galaxies, cluster of galaxies,
a big gas cloud in the middle,

02:32:18.298 --> 02:32:22.158
and because the big gas
cloud in the middle

02:32:22.298 --> 02:32:26.138
is much more massive than the
galaxies themselves, you would

02:32:26.158 --> 02:32:30.378
expect to see distortions that we call
dark matter distortions in the middle.

02:32:31.378 --> 02:32:35.108
If, however, dark matter is real, the
galaxies pass through one another, the

02:32:35.158 --> 02:32:39.058
cloud stops, dark matter doesn't interact
with the cloud, so it passes through.

02:32:39.138 --> 02:32:42.998
In that case, you would expect to see
the distortions where the galaxies are.

02:32:43.498 --> 02:32:47.358
And that's what we see. So
that is strong evidence in my

02:32:47.378 --> 02:32:51.198
mind. The Bullet Cluster is strong
evidence that dark matter is a real thing.

02:32:51.258 --> 02:32:54.818
And there is another example which is much
more recent, dark Bullet Cluster was a while

02:32:54.898 --> 02:32:58.538
ago, called the Dragonfly
galaxies. There's Dragonfly 2 and

02:32:58.558 --> 02:33:07.358
Dragonfly 4. These are galaxies that
rotate exactly according to Newton's laws.

02:33:08.178 --> 02:33:12.678
And so the fact that they rotate
exactly according to Newton's laws

02:33:13.698 --> 02:33:17.618
says that whatever's causing
galaxies to rotate too fast

02:33:17.658 --> 02:33:23.228
is not a property of matter. But if you had
a galaxy where there was no dark matter,

02:33:23.858 --> 02:33:27.498
for whatever reason it got stripped off
or something, this is one of those lovely

02:33:27.598 --> 02:33:31.468
ironies that the existence of a
galaxy with no dark matter is

02:33:31.638 --> 02:33:35.598
very strong evidence that dark matter is
real because you can take the dark matter

02:33:35.698 --> 02:33:42.398
out. So the DF2 and DF4 also suggests
to me that dark matter is real. So now,

02:33:43.178 --> 02:33:46.978
while it remains possible that we need to

02:33:47.038 --> 02:33:50.858
modify the laws of inertia or we need to
modify the laws of gravity, those are possible

02:33:50.958 --> 02:33:54.858
still. In my opinion, and
now this is Don's opinion,

02:33:54.918 --> 02:33:58.908
but it's probably the opinion of
most of the scientific community,

02:34:00.458 --> 02:34:03.258
dark matter is likely a real thing.

02:34:04.018 --> 02:34:07.998
Now, that's great. I've taken you all the
way to dark matter. So now you're gonna ask

02:34:08.038 --> 02:34:10.818
me, you're gonna say, "Don, what is dark
matter?" I'm gonna go, "I don't know."

02:34:12.548 --> 02:34:18.788
But I know what it isn't. Okay? I know
that it is not black holes. I know that it

02:34:18.838 --> 02:34:22.658
is not rogue planets. I know that
we've done the measurements. We've

02:34:22.738 --> 02:34:26.498
looked across nearly every mass range
for compact objects and ruled them

02:34:26.578 --> 02:34:30.128
out. So if dark matter is real,
it can't be made of those.

02:34:31.498 --> 02:34:35.438
So then you're left with the idea that dark matter
is a particle, and that's what we've thought

02:34:35.498 --> 02:34:39.398
The name for the dark matter particle
that we've called for a long time is a

02:34:39.478 --> 02:34:43.398
WIMP, for a weakly interacting massive
particle, and we have spent the

02:34:43.438 --> 02:34:47.138
last, God, 30 years looking
for them in the various ways.

02:34:47.258 --> 02:34:50.948
There are three ways that
we might see dark matter,

02:34:50.998 --> 02:34:54.618
the direct way, which says that
dark matter exists literally

02:34:54.638 --> 02:34:58.258
everywhere in this room, in our
laboratory, and the dark matter is

02:34:58.338 --> 02:35:02.238
passing through the Earth like a wind,
and we put up detectors trying to see

02:35:02.258 --> 02:35:05.498
those. We have done that,
and we've seen nothing.

02:35:06.038 --> 02:35:08.178
- So we should say we have
done that for neutrinos.

02:35:08.418 --> 02:35:12.158
- We've done that for many different types
of dark matter. We just simply put

02:35:12.198 --> 02:35:15.618
detectors in labs deep underground,

02:35:16.298 --> 02:35:19.578
and we can see neutrinos in them, it's
true, but dark matter would have,

02:35:19.718 --> 02:35:23.138
especially heavy dark
matter, what these WIMPs,

02:35:23.798 --> 02:35:27.158
They have a different signature,
and we've seen no evidence-

02:35:27.218 --> 02:35:27.228
- Got it.

02:35:27.228 --> 02:35:29.438
- ... of dark matter interaction
in these detectors.

02:35:29.638 --> 02:35:33.508
- So neutrinos are also weakly interacting
and also- ... have mass, but-

02:35:33.518 --> 02:35:34.048
- They are

02:35:34.438 --> 02:35:38.458
- ... but not enough so WIMPs
are- ... heavy on the M.

02:35:38.778 --> 02:35:42.598
- Right. Neutrinos are indeed WIMPs
of a sort. Now, we have to be

02:35:42.638 --> 02:35:46.298
careful what we mean by WIMPs. They are
weakly interacting massive particles,

02:35:46.638 --> 02:35:50.238
but we can calculate, and there's just
not enough mass in them. It's not it.

02:35:50.718 --> 02:35:51.058
- Got it. Got it.

02:35:51.138 --> 02:35:54.898
- So we need another form,
and we have seen zero

02:35:55.038 --> 02:35:58.938
evidence of this wind of
dark matter through the

02:35:59.038 --> 02:36:02.598
Earth. Another possibility is you
look where you think dark matter

02:36:02.918 --> 02:36:06.428
might be concentrated at
the center of galaxies, and

02:36:06.998 --> 02:36:10.788
if dark matter exists and
there's antimatter dark matter,

02:36:11.238 --> 02:36:15.058
maybe they annihilate and make photons.
And so we look for gamma rays and

02:36:15.098 --> 02:36:18.718
various other signatures of
annihilating dark matter, and there

02:36:18.818 --> 02:36:20.658
are always constantly

02:36:22.458 --> 02:36:26.018
announcements of, "Oh, we saw it. Oh, we
didn't. Oh, it..." You know, it's-- the problem

02:36:26.078 --> 02:36:29.948
is that way of looking for dark
matter is hard because there

02:36:29.998 --> 02:36:33.678
are other ways of making, for
instance, gamma rays like neutron

02:36:33.738 --> 02:36:37.698
stars and stuff, and you really need
to understand the details of galaxies

02:36:37.818 --> 02:36:41.338
really, really well to believe
that. And then the final

02:36:41.398 --> 02:36:45.238
option is what I do, where we smash
particles together at high or

02:36:45.278 --> 02:36:49.038
high energy. We try to make dark matter
particles. If you make dark matter

02:36:49.078 --> 02:36:52.808
particles, because they don't
interact except via gravity, they

02:36:52.818 --> 02:36:56.398
escape with your detector. So what you're
seeing, what you hope to see, is an

02:36:56.458 --> 02:37:00.058
event where you collide
particles, a dark matter particle

02:37:00.098 --> 02:37:04.018
escapes, and you don't see it, but
the recoil you see on the other side

02:37:04.058 --> 02:37:07.838
because momentum is conserved. So you see a blob
of energy on this side, nothing on the other

02:37:07.958 --> 02:37:11.668
side. Maybe that's dark
matter, and that also

02:37:11.718 --> 02:37:15.298
happens with neutrinos. So you need to
understand everything about neutrinos and

02:37:15.338 --> 02:37:19.198
calculate how many of those you see and then hope
you see more, and then that might be dark matter.

02:37:19.678 --> 02:37:20.598
Again, that hasn't worked.

02:37:21.918 --> 02:37:25.638
So we've ruled out some dark matter
particles, but the problem is

02:37:26.118 --> 02:37:32.358
the range of space of possible mass, if
dark matter is of a particulate form,

02:37:33.218 --> 02:37:37.148
the range of viable dark matter ranges

02:37:37.198 --> 02:37:40.938
from something like the
mass of an asteroid to far

02:37:40.998 --> 02:37:43.938
lighter than an electron
and everywhere in between.

02:37:45.208 --> 02:37:49.098
And we have looked. We've ruled out some
little spots in that phase space, but that's a

02:37:49.138 --> 02:37:50.078
big range.

02:37:50.578 --> 02:37:53.898
- Is it really possible to miss a
particle the size of an asteroid?

02:37:54.538 --> 02:37:58.378
- The astronomical searches were
not sensitive to that level of,

02:37:59.458 --> 02:38:03.298
of dark matter, but, you know, then
you would expect that there would be

02:38:03.418 --> 02:38:07.398
some of those in the solar system.
And if they're what we think, like

02:38:07.538 --> 02:38:11.478
asteroids or something, then we'd heat
them up, and we'd eventually see them.

02:38:11.537 --> 02:38:14.898
But if they're really, like,
truly dark matter, doesn't

02:38:14.938 --> 02:38:18.928
interact with matter, which means
they wouldn't absorb energy from the

02:38:18.998 --> 02:38:22.938
sun, so they'd be really dark. I don't
know. Maybe they're out there. But the only

02:38:23.018 --> 02:38:28.838
way we searched for them was a
thing called microlensing. So

02:38:29.638 --> 02:38:32.818
if a massive object, you
have a distant star,

02:38:33.648 --> 02:38:38.058
and a massive object passes
between that star and your eye,

02:38:38.938 --> 02:38:41.798
that star will momentarily brighten.

02:38:42.458 --> 02:38:46.238
And so you just look for these,
what they call microlensing

02:38:46.298 --> 02:38:50.288
events, and you count them, and you
see some. And we did see some. You

02:38:50.338 --> 02:38:54.298
know, black holes pass in front of
stars, and we've seen them, but we just

02:38:54.338 --> 02:39:01.258
haven't seen enough. And for very
low-mass particles like asteroids, they,

02:39:01.378 --> 02:39:04.938
They just wouldn't make
enough brightening effect to

02:39:04.978 --> 02:39:08.088
see. So there's, like, a minimum
sensitivity of brightening

02:39:08.818 --> 02:39:12.658
and that about a third the
mass of a moon, our moon,

02:39:13.138 --> 02:39:16.738
is about the sensitivity
that we had. So, you know,

02:39:17.038 --> 02:39:20.978
that nobody, I think, really thought
that these low-mass guys were

02:39:21.098 --> 02:39:24.998
likely. What they thought was more likely
they were just unseen black holes, which

02:39:25.058 --> 02:39:26.678
I thought- ... you know, I
think is completely reasonable.

02:39:26.998 --> 02:39:30.858
And then when that got ruled out,
I thought, okay, modified gravity

02:39:30.958 --> 02:39:34.928
or or inertia. Well, now the, you know,

02:39:35.018 --> 02:39:38.878
Bullet Cluster in Dragonfly seems to have
ruled that out. So I'm stuck in my head with

02:39:39.478 --> 02:39:43.458
dark matter seems to be real, and
it-- we don't know what it is.

02:39:43.838 --> 02:39:46.478
- And it makes up a giant percentage
of matter in the universe.

02:39:46.538 --> 02:39:46.838
- It is-

02:39:46.918 --> 02:39:47.068
- What is it?

02:39:47.068 --> 02:39:49.418
- ... five times more prevalent
than ordinary matter.

02:39:49.538 --> 02:39:51.398
- Wow. This is incredible.

02:39:51.538 --> 02:39:51.988
- It is incredible.

02:39:51.988 --> 02:39:52.678
- This is so fascinating.

02:39:52.758 --> 02:39:56.298
- And that's why it's cool. So if
someone out there is, you know,

02:39:56.658 --> 02:40:00.538
a young person who wants to get into
this, understanding dark matter is a

02:40:00.578 --> 02:40:04.398
big deal. I mean, it's five times more
prevalent. The problem is, is as I

02:40:04.458 --> 02:40:08.106
told you. If the mass is
ranging from an asteroid to far

02:40:08.146 --> 02:40:11.876
lighter than an electron, if you
get on an experiment that looks at

02:40:12.006 --> 02:40:15.736
one little range of mass, maybe
you weren't the lucky guy that

02:40:16.246 --> 02:40:18.146
measured the right place, you know?

02:40:19.226 --> 02:40:23.186
And that's one of the reasons why, as
fascinating as I think it is, I'm not doing dark

02:40:23.226 --> 02:40:24.705
matter experiments because,

02:40:25.846 --> 02:40:29.426
you know, if you make an experiment
that searches one mass range,

02:40:29.746 --> 02:40:31.636
it'll be blind to another mass range.

02:40:31.666 --> 02:40:35.526
So what you need is you need
many groups doing all sorts

02:40:35.586 --> 02:40:39.626
of radically different experiments,
exploring all sorts of parameter space.

02:40:41.326 --> 02:40:42.506
And with all that said,

02:40:43.446 --> 02:40:47.026
until you see it, there still is
the possibility that maybe we don't

02:40:47.066 --> 02:40:51.926
understand gravity or inertia right.
You know, you can't rule that out.

02:40:52.006 --> 02:40:56.486
- If there is dark matter out there, you're
hoping it's actually somehow detectable.

02:40:56.626 --> 02:40:59.546
- I mean, I don't know what it is. I
think it's cool. It's very, very

02:40:59.586 --> 02:41:03.346
fascinating. That is one
thing I really do hope in my

02:41:03.386 --> 02:41:07.166
lifetime is understood 'cause I'd
like to know the answer to that.

02:41:07.506 --> 02:41:10.246
- And that's the thing that you
could-- there legitimately you could

02:41:11.046 --> 02:41:12.386
see a discovery of-

02:41:12.486 --> 02:41:15.846
- You gotta get lucky though. I mean, you gotta
look in the right place, whatever it is.

02:41:16.306 --> 02:41:17.206
- Just imagine.

02:41:17.466 --> 02:41:21.386
- Or you have to come up with that really cool
theoretical idea that everybody's overlooked,

02:41:21.426 --> 02:41:25.356
which is another possibility. And
there are people who are really,

02:41:25.386 --> 02:41:28.746
really religiously hating
dark matter, largely

02:41:28.826 --> 02:41:32.106
because we've looked so hard
for so many years and the

02:41:32.146 --> 02:41:36.066
experiments in today's world are
a million times more sensitive

02:41:36.126 --> 02:41:38.476
than when I was a starting student-

02:41:38.476 --> 02:41:42.386
... and they still haven't seen anything.
And that's why people really hate

02:41:42.586 --> 02:41:44.196
dark matter. I mean, some of them-

02:41:44.196 --> 02:41:46.606
... because they think we should
have seen it by now, but-

02:41:46.906 --> 02:41:48.806
... you know I don't know.

02:41:49.406 --> 02:41:53.326
- I mean, I'm a sucker for direct observation.
Not-- In-indirect is o-obviously also

02:41:53.406 --> 02:41:57.166
really great, but direct, just
imagine pointing your telescope in a

02:41:57.226 --> 02:42:01.026
certain direction and
because of some artifact of

02:42:01.086 --> 02:42:04.706
cosmology being able to
directly detect a giant amount

02:42:04.766 --> 02:42:07.746
of a thing that you could
say is dark matter.

02:42:08.086 --> 02:42:10.126
- Yeah, you would see it
orbit, things orbit it.

02:42:10.206 --> 02:42:10.346
- Yeah.

02:42:10.426 --> 02:42:13.206
- Or it would- ... eclipse
things in front of it or-

02:42:13.346 --> 02:42:17.066
- Yeah, like in an obvious way. 'Cause
some of the stuff you mentioned with

02:42:17.106 --> 02:42:22.006
DF-2 and DF-4, those are
like brilliant indirect, um,

02:42:23.026 --> 02:42:26.566
deductions that there should
be something like dark matter.

02:42:27.046 --> 02:42:32.186
But some obvious, yeah, blocking,
occluding, this kind of thing.

02:42:32.626 --> 02:42:36.526
- We did that in the '90s with experiments
called MACHO, OGLE, and some others.

02:42:37.086 --> 02:42:41.046
They looked for a black hole that you
just can't see, you know, a black hole

02:42:41.106 --> 02:42:42.866
you can't see. It's
perfect. It's a perfect

02:42:43.986 --> 02:42:47.866
candidate for dark matter. And if there's enough
of them out there-- Now remember, there's

02:42:47.926 --> 02:42:48.956
five times-

02:42:49.246 --> 02:42:53.126
... the number of stars, which means there's a
whole lot of freaking black holes out there.

02:42:53.166 --> 02:42:56.506
We should have seen them, and we didn't.

02:42:56.666 --> 02:43:00.506
- What a grand mystery. We've covered
so many of them. I could talk to you

02:43:00.646 --> 02:43:04.546
for a thousand more hours,
Don. Let me, if I can

02:43:05.026 --> 02:43:06.806
ask you about a little bit more of a,

02:43:07.666 --> 02:43:12.206
On the personal side. You have
a really inspiring life story.

02:43:13.106 --> 02:43:15.166
Your folks didn't go to college.

02:43:15.966 --> 02:43:19.946
Can you just tell me about your
childhood and where you found the love

02:43:20.266 --> 02:43:24.126
for physics and science, and
maybe how you found your

02:43:24.186 --> 02:43:30.356
journey to become a physicist, given
the, the context of where you came from?

02:43:31.446 --> 02:43:36.666
- Well you know, I grew up a
poor kid in the boondocks.

02:43:37.586 --> 02:43:41.186
Great parents, but not ones
that could guide me terribly

02:43:41.246 --> 02:43:43.806
academically, but very very nurturing.

02:43:44.626 --> 02:43:48.346
You know, my mom would laugh that she could
stop helping me math after like sixth or

02:43:48.386 --> 02:43:54.136
seventh grade, you know. But they were
supportive. And there were a couple of things

02:43:54.606 --> 02:44:00.126
that-- couple, three things I think that
folded into it. One is I was a voracious

02:44:00.246 --> 02:44:03.946
reader as a kid. I loved science
fiction. I would read a book a day.

02:44:04.206 --> 02:44:08.016
It drove my mother nuts 'cause she would try
to be nice. She'd buy me a book, and I'd say,

02:44:08.106 --> 02:44:11.866
"Thank you," and the next day it'd be done.
You know, it just drove her completely nuts.

02:44:11.926 --> 02:44:14.606
But anyways, but science
fiction is good for

02:44:16.546 --> 02:44:20.066
fostering imagination, and so
that's precisely what it did.

02:44:20.906 --> 02:44:28.156
In addition, and this is where the more
serious science came along, there were lovely

02:44:30.326 --> 02:44:34.006
science communicators that
were popular in the 1970s,

02:44:34.146 --> 02:44:38.006
Isaac Asimov, Carl Sagan, a guy
by the name of George Gamow.

02:44:38.066 --> 02:44:41.976
They wrote books about science
aimed at a layperson. You know, as

02:44:41.986 --> 02:44:45.466
a kid, I surely couldn't
read a textbook and

02:44:45.526 --> 02:44:49.466
understand it, but I
could read and, you know,

02:44:49.566 --> 02:44:53.766
get a hint of what science
was. And on top of that,

02:44:54.786 --> 02:44:58.246
you know, I was, as most
people who became scientists,

02:44:59.046 --> 02:45:05.626
irrepressibly curious about everything.
And I had sort of a quasi-philosophical

02:45:06.426 --> 02:45:10.346
mind. I mean, I was interested in
things that, questions that have in the

02:45:10.426 --> 02:45:14.126
past been theological and then
philosophical and now are more scientific.

02:45:14.246 --> 02:45:17.766
Questions about how did the
universe come into existence?

02:45:18.466 --> 02:45:22.366
Why is the universe the way it
is? Why are the laws of the

02:45:22.406 --> 02:45:26.066
universe what we see them to be?
How will the universe-- Was it

02:45:26.106 --> 02:45:29.746
created? How will it be destroyed? These
are, you know, big questions that have

02:45:29.786 --> 02:45:33.726
bothered humanity for, well,
thousands of years. And so,

02:45:33.926 --> 02:45:37.406
you know, I did. You, you said I had,

02:45:38.226 --> 02:45:42.006
you know, philosophy and religion minors in
college, and I did 'cause I was curious about that.

02:45:42.666 --> 02:45:44.846
Um, I was hoping that learning

02:45:45.806 --> 02:45:49.676
that history might help me
understand these questions. And

02:45:49.726 --> 02:45:53.646
it was in college where I came to
realize that the answers that I was

02:45:53.686 --> 02:45:57.546
searching for were not to be found in
those directions, but I still learned

02:45:57.606 --> 02:46:02.326
about how those questions have
been asked in the past. And so

02:46:03.366 --> 02:46:07.326
I became a scientist, and the only
question was, was I going to be,

02:46:07.426 --> 02:46:10.286
A cosmologist/astrophysicist-

02:46:10.296 --> 02:46:14.094
... or a particle physicist? And
when I had to make that decision.

02:46:14.694 --> 02:46:22.153
It was the mid-'80s, and at the time, there
were a lot fewer cosmology measurements.

02:46:22.234 --> 02:46:26.084
There was an awful lot of thinking
about the universe and not

02:46:26.134 --> 02:46:30.054
enough measuring. Whereas
with particle physics, by

02:46:30.094 --> 02:46:33.954
God, you could do experiments.
And so the-- what attracted me

02:46:34.014 --> 02:46:37.814
was the ability to actually get
an answer and not just mull

02:46:37.914 --> 02:46:41.774
over what an answer might
be. And so I became a

02:46:41.814 --> 02:46:45.954
particle physicist. It was
difficult without having,

02:46:46.854 --> 02:46:53.564
you know, family mentors or anything like
that, but, you know, I managed. And that

02:46:54.234 --> 02:46:58.074
actually is why, well, I'm here
and why I have spent a fair

02:46:58.154 --> 02:47:02.134
bit of my time writing books
and so forth, because I figure

02:47:02.654 --> 02:47:06.634
that there has to be some other
kid out there in Iowa or Kansas,

02:47:06.734 --> 02:47:10.694
Montana, somewhere out in some
little town without a lot

02:47:10.794 --> 02:47:14.584
of access to the kinds
of thing that people,

02:47:15.134 --> 02:47:18.154
you know, who have highly
educated parents do.

02:47:19.314 --> 02:47:23.214
And I'm hoping that, you know, some
of them will have read some of the

02:47:23.234 --> 02:47:27.194
things I've written and will find
their own path forward, because

02:47:27.334 --> 02:47:30.734
I found it very rewarding
over the years. And,

02:47:30.834 --> 02:47:34.494
You know, I've been doing this
long enough that I'm sure

02:47:34.534 --> 02:47:38.494
this is true. I've had kids
come up to me at the lab and

02:47:38.554 --> 02:47:42.234
say, "Hey, I'm a summer intern because I saw
your video or read your book," or, you know,

02:47:42.334 --> 02:47:46.154
whatever. So I know that
at least I've made a small

02:47:46.234 --> 02:47:49.984
impact. I mean, I always would
like to do more, and, you know, I

02:47:50.134 --> 02:47:57.464
appreciate the opportunity that your
audience affords me 'cause I think it's

02:47:57.494 --> 02:48:01.134
important to talk about these
things. These are really cool,

02:48:01.194 --> 02:48:04.774
fascinating questions. They are
unanswered, and they are just

02:48:04.934 --> 02:48:08.774
waiting for youngsters to come
and spend some time thinking

02:48:08.834 --> 02:48:12.234
about them, 'cause one of your
viewers might be one of the

02:48:12.494 --> 02:48:17.514
people who answer these questions that have
stymied very smart people for decades.

02:48:18.394 --> 02:48:22.353
- And we should also say that
you're a legit scientist.

02:48:22.434 --> 02:48:26.314
So what-- we'll mention Sean
Carroll, who's a legit scientist,

02:48:26.394 --> 02:48:29.954
legit physicist, but is also
a good science communicator.

02:48:30.594 --> 02:48:34.554
Anyway, I did wanna mention, I don't
know if this is true, but I kind

02:48:34.564 --> 02:48:38.554
of heard you talk about this, that when you
first showed up to Fermilab, you were, like,

02:48:38.654 --> 02:48:43.894
working crazy hours, working extremely
hard- ... eight AM to midnight.

02:48:43.934 --> 02:48:44.143
- I did.

02:48:44.374 --> 02:48:46.214
- Uh, first of all, I love that.

02:48:47.934 --> 02:48:52.474
Can you speak to what drove you
and maybe the value of hard work

02:48:53.554 --> 02:48:56.434
in those contexts, in your early career

02:48:57.314 --> 02:48:59.394
when you discover a thing
you're passionate about?

02:49:00.234 --> 02:49:01.534
- Well, yeah. I mean,

02:49:02.374 --> 02:49:06.294
obviously being smart, you know, if you're
Einstein, then maybe you can slack, I

02:49:06.334 --> 02:49:10.274
guess. Although even he didn't do
that, but I'm not Einstein. But the

02:49:10.334 --> 02:49:14.274
fact is, when I was young, and
I was unencumbered, no, no

02:49:14.354 --> 02:49:15.734
family, no kids or something,

02:49:16.774 --> 02:49:20.654
I couldn't imagine anything I wanted to
do more. I mean, some people, they wanna

02:49:20.694 --> 02:49:24.434
go out to the club. They wanna, I don't
know, play soccer or something. But I

02:49:24.494 --> 02:49:28.414
wanted to make measurements,
and I wanted to understand and,

02:49:28.474 --> 02:49:32.354
and learn, and that was fantastic.
And so as a graduate student,

02:49:32.414 --> 02:49:34.694
and this isn't for everybody, but I worked

02:49:35.514 --> 02:49:39.434
outrageously. I would, from Monday
through Saturday, I would be at the

02:49:39.514 --> 02:49:43.434
lab voluntarily because I
wanted to be from eight AM

02:49:43.474 --> 02:49:47.254
to midnight, and on Sunday, I
would work from eight until about

02:49:47.314 --> 02:49:51.294
five, and that's because from five
to midnight, I had to wash clothes

02:49:51.314 --> 02:49:55.154
and buy groceries and things
like that. And I loved

02:49:55.194 --> 02:49:59.054
it, you know. And I still
love it. I can't do that

02:49:59.134 --> 02:50:06.374
anymore. But that's simply because
I have other obligations. But had I

02:50:06.454 --> 02:50:09.754
been rich, I would've done the same thing.

02:50:09.894 --> 02:50:15.354
You know, it's something I truly,
truly loved. And the-- I mean,

02:50:16.674 --> 02:50:20.354
there is absolutely nothing more
fascinating to me than having a

02:50:20.414 --> 02:50:24.214
hard problem and figuring
it out. And that, you know,

02:50:24.254 --> 02:50:26.734
that work ethic-- Well, there's
a couple of things that separate

02:50:28.074 --> 02:50:31.993
smart people from no-kidding scientists,
'cause all scientists are smart.

02:50:32.034 --> 02:50:35.794
But the thing that separates, that

02:50:35.934 --> 02:50:42.563
many scientists have is, A, a
drive and a real grit. The, um--

02:50:44.214 --> 02:50:47.054
For me and for so many
scientists that I know,

02:50:49.194 --> 02:50:53.114
trying to measure something and having
it not work just kinda ticks me off,

02:50:53.334 --> 02:50:56.914
and I am not going to let the
universe in my lab or whatever

02:50:58.834 --> 02:51:02.534
beat me. And, you know, some people- ...
they, you know, if the thing breaks, it's

02:51:02.574 --> 02:51:06.474
like, "Oh, man, that didn't work."
And a lot of people, "Well, I'm gonna

02:51:06.514 --> 02:51:10.414
go home. I'm fed up." Nah, it would
just kinda make me mad, and I'd put

02:51:10.514 --> 02:51:14.254
more effort into it. And, you know,
not every-- I mean, okay, I was

02:51:14.294 --> 02:51:17.094
crazy. I worked long hours. But I think-

02:51:17.194 --> 02:51:21.124
... the people who are really good at
this will do maybe not that much, you

02:51:21.174 --> 02:51:24.794
know. Some people have to have a
better life than that. But a lot,

02:51:24.954 --> 02:51:29.974
because it's just you can't
imagine not knowing the answer.

02:51:29.994 --> 02:51:32.134
And that if-- When, when you see that

02:51:33.194 --> 02:51:37.174
as an older guy, you don't-- maybe not to that
degree, but when you see that kinda drive, that,

02:51:37.634 --> 02:51:42.063
that intensity of trying
to get the answers,

02:51:43.234 --> 02:51:45.914
you know that person's
a winner. And so if,

02:51:46.854 --> 02:51:49.274
you know, some student
out there, if it doesn't,

02:51:50.074 --> 02:51:53.734
you know, bring you joy, as
uh, what's her name? The

02:51:53.854 --> 02:51:57.734
Japanese girl says, "If it doesn't bring you joy,
then it might not be for you." And then you could

02:51:57.754 --> 02:52:01.664
be a person who reads about it and, you
know, is involved. But if you wanna be a

02:52:01.674 --> 02:52:05.614
real scientist, it has to be
just part of what you are here.

02:52:06.534 --> 02:52:12.294
- And by the way, it is a hard life,
but it is also a very fulfilling one.

02:52:12.954 --> 02:52:19.274
So working hard towards the thing you
love is a really fulfilling way to be.

02:52:19.414 --> 02:52:23.084
- I think that's true for an artist or
something, you know, anybody, a musician, you

02:52:23.134 --> 02:52:27.654
know? Musician, they just keep
practicing because it is who they are.

02:52:27.974 --> 02:52:31.474
- Mm-hmm. Well, I'm glad there's
people like you at a place

02:52:32.314 --> 02:52:37.694
I admire, like Fermilab one of the many
places in the United States and the world

02:52:38.714 --> 02:52:44.124
that is carrying the beacon of great
science and great engineering forward.

02:52:45.254 --> 02:52:50.454
Uh, Don, thank you so much for everything
you do, for all the teaching you do,

02:52:51.314 --> 02:52:55.274
online, for all the incredible
physics work that you

02:52:55.334 --> 02:52:59.094
do at Fermilab, and thank you
so much for talking today.

02:52:59.814 --> 02:53:00.534
- Thank you for having me.

02:53:01.634 --> 02:53:05.594
- Thanks for listening to this conversation with Don
Lincoln. To support this podcast, please check

02:53:05.614 --> 02:53:09.354
out our sponsors in the description,
where you can also find links to

02:53:09.414 --> 02:53:12.574
contact me, ask questions,
give feedback, and so on.

02:53:13.454 --> 02:53:15.904
And now, let me leave you with
some words from Marie Curie,

02:53:16.814 --> 02:53:20.464
a two-time Nobel Prize
winner, first in physics,

02:53:20.714 --> 02:53:26.934
second in chemistry: "Nothing in life is to
be feared. It is only to be understood."

02:53:28.374 --> 02:53:31.514
Thank you for listening. I
hope to see you next time.

